{"title_page": "Death of Chan Yin-lam", "text_new": "{{short description|Death during the 2019 Hong Kong protests}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Chan Yin-lam\n| image = Chan Yin-lam on 19 September 2019.jpg\n| image_size = <!-- Image Size -->\n| alt = <!-- Image Substitution -->\n| caption = CCTV footage released by the [[Hong Kong Design Institute]] of Chan the day of her death, 19 September 2019\n| birth_date = 2004\n| birth_place = Hong Kong\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=y|2019|9|19|2004}}\n| death_place = Hong Kong\n| death_cause = \n| body_discovered = [[Yau Tong]], Hong Kong\n| monuments = <!-- Memorial Building -->\n| residence = <!-- place of residence -->\n| nationality = [[Hongkonger]]\n| permanent_residency = <!-- Permanent residency -->\n| other_names = <!-- alias -->\n| ancestor = \n| ethnicity = <!-- ethnic -->\n| language = <!-- Language -->\n| education = \n| alma_mater = [[Hong Kong Design Institute]]\n| occupation = Student\n| known_for = <!-- Well-known reasons -->\n| height = 1.53m (5 ft 0 inches)\n| weight = <!-- weight -->\n| movement = [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|2019 Hong Kong protests]]\n| influenced = <!-- influences -->\n}}\nThe '''death of Chan Yin-lam''', a 15-year-old female, occurred on or shortly after 19 September 2019. Her naked corpse was found floating in the sea near [[Yau Tong]], Hong Kong on 22 September 2019. Following a preliminary autopsy, police asserted that no foul play was suspected, and that Chan had committed suicide.<ref name=\"Suicide\">{{Cite web|url=https://thestandnews.com/politics/15-%E6%AD%B2%E5%A5%B3%E7%94%9F%E9%99%B3%E5%BD%A5%E9%9C%96%E6%B5%AE%E5%B1%8D%E6%B5%B7%E9%9D%A2-%E8%AD%A6-%E7%84%A1%E5%9B%A0%E5%8F%8D%E4%BF%AE%E4%BE%8B%E5%85%AC%E7%9C%BE%E6%B4%BB%E5%8B%95%E8%A2%AB%E6%8D%95-%E5%88%9D%E6%AD%A5%E8%AA%BF%E6%9F%A5%E8%A7%A3%E5%89%96%E6%AD%BB%E5%9B%A0%E7%84%A1%E5%8F%AF%E7%96%91/|title=15 \u6b72\u5973\u751f\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u6d6e\u5c4d\u6d77\u9762 \u8b66\uff1a\u7121\u56e0\u53cd\u4fee\u4f8b\u516c\u773e\u6d3b\u52d5\u88ab\u6355 \u521d\u6b65\u8abf\u67e5\u89e3\u5256\u6b7b\u56e0\u7121\u53ef\u7591 &#124; \u7acb\u5834\u5831\u9053 &#124; \u7acb\u5834\u65b0\u805e|website=Stand News |language=zh|location=Hong Kong|access-date=4 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116085725/https://thestandnews.com/politics/15-%E6%AD%B2%E5%A5%B3%E7%94%9F%E9%99%B3%E5%BD%A5%E9%9C%96%E6%B5%AE%E5%B1%8D%E6%B5%B7%E9%9D%A2-%E8%AD%A6-%E7%84%A1%E5%9B%A0%E5%8F%8D%E4%BF%AE%E4%BE%8B%E5%85%AC%E7%9C%BE%E6%B4%BB%E5%8B%95%E8%A2%AB%E6%8D%95-%E5%88%9D%E6%AD%A5%E8%AA%BF%E6%9F%A5%E8%A7%A3%E5%89%96%E6%AD%BB%E5%9B%A0%E7%84%A1%E5%8F%AF%E7%96%91/|archive-date=16 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Her death was the subject of a [[conspiracy theory]] that alleged that the government murdered her for participating in the [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|2019 Hong Kong protests]].<ref name=\"Yahoo\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/fake-news-stoking-violence-anger-210000243.html|title=How Fake News and Rumors Are Stoking Division in Hong Kong|date=12 November 2019|accessdate=3 December 2019|publisher=[[Bloomberg News]]|via=[[Yahoo! News|Yahoo!]]|author1=Shelly Banjo|author2=Natalie Lung|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128003944/https://news.yahoo.com/fake-news-stoking-violence-anger-210000243.html|archive-date=28 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Victim == \nChan Yin-lam was 15 years old, and her parents were separated. With a \"complicated\" family background, she had a history of running away from home.<ref name=appledaily20785021/> Prior to her disappearance, she had been staying at a [[Women's shelter|girls' home]].<ref name=thestandard212706/>\n\nShe attended the Pok Oi Hospital Tang Pui King Memorial College, Hong Kong, and had, just a few days prior to her disappearance, started a course at the Youth College attached to the [[Vocational Training Council]] (VTC). She also worked a part-time job in the restaurant trade.<ref name=appledaily20785021/> Media reports indicate that Chan had won awards in inter-school swimming competitions.<ref name=scmp3032907/> Chan had received regular diving training and was once a member of the diving team.<ref name=Apple20785020>{{Cite web|title=\u5168\u88f8\u5973\u6d6e\u5c4d \u70ba15\u6b72\u6cf3\u5c07 \u66fe\u8d74\u53cd\u9001\u4e2d\u793a\u5a01|url=https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20191011/20785020|date=11 October 2019|accessdate=14 October 2019|work=Apple Daily |language=zh|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014131043/https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20191011/20785020|archive-date=14 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to her friends, she had attended protests, while police confirmed that Chan had not been arrested during the [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|2019 protests]].<ref name=scmp3032907/>\n\n== Disappearance and death ==\nOn 19 September at 14:15, Chan separated from friends at Mei Foo and sent a message to her friends stating she was going back home. It was her last message before her disappearance.<ref name=appledaily20785021>{{Cite web|url=https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20191011/20785021|title=\u597d\u53cb\uff1a\u4f62\u60f3\u91cd\u65b0\u51fa\u767c|work=Apple Daily |language=zh|accessdate=14 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014131045/https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20191011/20785021|archive-date=14 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Friends put out a missing person's brief after she failed to reappear;<ref name=Apple20785020/> her family called the police on 21 September.<ref name=\"hkej-191011-1\">{{cite news|url=https://www2.hkej.com/instantnews/current/article/2273802/\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u4e8b\u4ef6+\u8b66\u65b9\u6307\u7d93\u89e3\u5256\u7121\u53ef\u7591|title=\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u4e8b\u4ef6 \u8b66\u65b9\u6307\u7d93\u89e3\u5256\u7121\u53ef\u7591|date=11 October 2019}}</ref> According to surveillance footage from Youth College she attended, she left the campus barefoot and walked towards the waterfront near Tseung Kwan O on 19 September. She was reported missing two days later.<ref name=scmp3032907/>\n\nMTR confirmed that station cleaners had found her mobile phone and some stationery belonging to Chan on the ground near an exit of [[Tiu Keng Leng Station]], while the station staff have contacted Chan's family members in accordance with the phonebook of the mobile phone. Her family member picked up the lost property two days later.<ref name=hk01386420>{{cite news|url=https://www.hk01.com/\u793e\u6703\u65b0\u805e/386420/\u6cb9\u5858\u5973\u6d6e\u5c4d-\u6e2f\u9435\u8b49\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u8abf\u666f\u5dba\u7ad9\u66fe\u907a\u624b\u6a5f-\u5bb6\u5c6c\u5169\u65e5\u5f8c\u9818\u56de|title=\u3010\u6cb9\u5858\u5973\u6d6e\u5c4d\u3011\u6e2f\u9435\u8b49\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u8abf\u666f\u5dba\u7ad9\u66fe\u907a\u624b\u6a5f\u3000\u5bb6\u5c6c\u5169\u65e5\u5f8c\u9818\u56de|date=15 October 2019|work=\u9999\u6e2f01|access-date=20 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016003035/https://www.hk01.com/%E7%A4%BE%E6%9C%83%E6%96%B0%E8%81%9E/386420/%E6%B2%B9%E5%A1%98%E5%A5%B3%E6%B5%AE%E5%B1%8D-%E6%B8%AF%E9%90%B5%E8%AD%89%E9%99%B3%E5%BD%A5%E9%9C%96%E8%AA%BF%E6%99%AF%E5%B6%BA%E7%AB%99%E6%9B%BE%E9%81%BA%E6%89%8B%E6%A9%9F-%E5%AE%B6%E5%B1%AC%E5%85%A9%E6%97%A5%E5%BE%8C%E9%A0%98%E5%9B%9E|archive-date=16 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt 11&nbsp;am on 22 September, a man who was fishing saw a floating object with a human form 100m off the coast from [[Devil's Peak, Hong Kong|Devil's Peak]]. Police boats were dispatched, and it was found to be the naked corpse of a human female. Police initially reported that the victim was a female suspected of being between 25 and 30 years of age, 1.5m in height, medium build, with long blond hair.According to a preliminary autopsy, there were no lacerations or contusions on her body, and no sign of sexual assault. Her death was therefore considered \"not suspicious\" by the police. Her body was cremated several days later.<ref name=\"Suicide\"/>\n\n==Conspiracy theories and reactions==\n[[File:Cy photo 20191015 upload 29.jpg|thumb|right|A [[Lennon Wall]] at [[Hong Kong Design Institute]], the school Chan attended before her death.]]\nFollowing her death, conspiracy theories emerged on social media that alleged that the police and government officials murdered her for participating in the [[2019 Hong Kong protests]] and then covered-up her death. The Hong Kong police and government have denied these allegations.<ref name=\"Suicide\"/><ref name=\"Yahoo\"/>\n\n=== HKDI footage ===\nFueled by these conspiracy theories, students from Youth College and [[Hong Kong Design Institute]] (HKDI) [[Tiu King Leng]] campus where she was a student gathered to demand the release of the CCTV footage taken on the evening of 19 September, where Chan was last seen before her death.<ref name=\"Yahoo\"/> On 15 October, after a sit-in, campus management agreed to accede to the demands and released some relevant footage. Dissatisfied with partial footage, disgruntled students demanded complete and unedited footage, giving a 30-minute deadline. Upon expiry of the deadline, the students vandalised school premises, damaged surveillance cameras and set off a fire alarm. The VTC later suspended all classes on the Tiu Keng Leng campus of the HKDI, Youth College and other institutions between 15 and 17 October.<ref name=scmp3032907>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3032907/classes-suspended-hong-kong-design-institute-after-students|title=Classes suspended at Hong Kong Design Institute after students vandalise campus demanding surveillance footage of classmate found dead in sea|last=Lew|first=Linda|date=15 October 2019|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020054908/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3032907/classes-suspended-hong-kong-design-institute-after-students|archive-date=20 October 2019|accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=20191016hongkongfp>{{cite web|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/10/16/protesters-demand-cctv-footage-tiu-keng-leng-school-following-death-15-year-old-student/|title=Protesters demand CCTV footage from Tiu Keng Leng school following death of 15-year-old student|last=Tong|first=Elson|date=16 October 2019|work=[[Hong Kong Free Press]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191018010938/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/10/16/protesters-demand-cctv-footage-tiu-keng-leng-school-following-death-15-year-old-student/|archive-date=18 October 2019|accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> The VTC has since released additional CCTV clips after 200 students, amid class suspension, rallied inside the campus to support an online appeal for an indefinite class boycott.<ref name=scmp3033257>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education/article/3033257/15-year-old-hong-kong-girl-found-dead-sea-had-walked|title=15-year-old Hong Kong girl found dead at sea had walked barefoot through campus before leaving school grounds on day she was last seen, new footage shows|last=Choi|first=Martin|date=16 October 2019|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020054907/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education/article/3033257/15-year-old-hong-kong-girl-found-dead-sea-had-walked|archive-date=20 October 2019|accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> The 16 clips released showed Chan wandering around campus for more than an hour.<ref name=thestandard212706/>\n\nAfter the Design Institute had disclosed surveillance videos and the girl's mother had appealed for an end to the speculation of Chan's death, students continued to demand the release of integral footage from surveillance cameras for 29 and 30 October. Masked protesters accused the school of downplaying the situation; they continued to damage facilities and equipment on campus for two days, with the police ended up having to be called.<ref name=\"scmp3035605\" />\n\n=== Interview of Chan's mother ===\nIn an interview with TVB News on 17 October, Chan's mother Ho Pui-yee said that after looking at all the relevant CCTV footage, she was satisfied that her daughter's death was suicide.<ref name=thestandard212706>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/section-news.php?id=212706|title=Mother of tragedy girl asks for peace|website=The Standard}}</ref><ref name=scmp3033448>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3033448/mother-15-year-old-hong-kong-girl-found-dead-sea-says|title=Mother says Hong Kong girl, 15, found dead in sea 'took her own life'|date=17 October 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref> She said that although she was initially suspicious of the death of Chan, she said that her daughter was emotionally unstable, and she may well have had psychosis as demonstrated by auditory hallucination.<ref name=thestandard212706/><ref name=scmp3033448/><ref name=asiatimes>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/10/article/friends-not-convinced-girls-death-was-suicide/|title=Friends not convinced girl's death was suicide |website=Asia Times Online|access-date=27 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030094011/https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/10/article/friends-not-convinced-girls-death-was-suicide/|archive-date=30 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"MKUltra\">{{YouTube|id=TeHp6YoMkBw|title=\u9999\u6e2f\u4fdd\u885b\u6230\u4e4bMK Ultra\u9673\u5f65\u9716}}</ref> She said that her daughter once participated in distributing the leaflet of the protests in June, but had become disillusioned by July.<ref name=thestandard212706/><ref name=scmp3033448/> She added that she had been [[doxing|dox]]xed since her daughter's death, resulting in her being harassed at work and telephoned at all hours.<ref name=scmp3033448/><ref name=tvb6038380295/> Ho pleaded to the general public to end the speculation and for her to be left alone.<ref name=thestandard212706/><ref name=scmp3035605>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education/article/3035605/hong-kong-design-institute-vandalised-second-straight-day|title=Design institute vandalised again after school chiefs fail to meet students|date=30 October 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref name=scmp3033448/><ref name=tvb6038380295>{{Cite web|url=http://news.tvb.com/local/5da84727e6038380295c27b2/\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u5abd\u5abd\u63a5\u53d7\u5c08\u8a2a\u6307\u76f8\u4fe1\u5973\u5152\u81ea\u6bba-\u5180\u8b20\u8a00\u76e1\u5feb\u505c\u6b62\u9084\u5979\u5011\u5be7\u975c|title=\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u5abd\u5abd\u63a5\u53d7\u5c08\u8a2a\u6307\u76f8\u4fe1\u5973\u5152\u81ea\u6bba \u5180\u8b20\u8a00\u76e1\u5feb\u505c\u6b62\u9084\u5979\u5011\u5be7\u975c|website=TVB News|access-date=12 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017121914/http://news.tvb.com/local/5da84727e6038380295c27b2/%25E9%2599%25B3%25E5%25BD%25A5%25E9%259C%2596%25E5%25AA%25BD%25E5%25AA%25BD%25E6%258E%25A5%25E5%258F%2597%25E5%25B0%2588%25E8%25A8%25AA%25E6%258C%2587%25E7%259B%25B8%25E4%25BF%25A1%25E5%25A5%25B3%25E5%2585%2592%25E8%2587%25AA%25E6%25AE%25BA-%25E5%2586%2580%25E8%25AC%25A0%25E8%25A8%2580%25E7%259B%25A1%25E5%25BF%25AB%25E5%2581%259C%25E6%25AD%25A2%25E9%2582%2584%25E5%25A5%25B9%25E5%2580%2591%25E5%25AF%25A7%25E9%259D%259C|archive-date=17 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHo's interview and the police's assertion that Chan had committed suicide were met with skepticism. A political activist who knows Chan's brother cast doubt on the assertion that Chan had committed suicide by drowning herself in the sea, citing the fact that Chan was an award-winning swimmer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/10/article/friends-not-convinced-girls-death-was-suicide/|title=Friends not convinced girl's death was suicide |website=Asia Times Online|access-date=3 February 2020}}</ref> Retired [[coroner]] Philip Beh commented that the circumstances of the discovery and cremation of Chan's body were suspicious: discoveries of fully naked bodies in the sea are generally treated as suspect and would require thorough investigations, yet Beh's opinion is that Chan's body was hastily cremated after a preliminary autopsy. Beh opined that police should release further information about the autopsy and a coroner's inquest should be undertaken to allay suspicions of police misconduct.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hk.appledaily.com/local/20191014/SMRVGN2YZC7J6ULDZZX6BVU6LI/|title=\u8cc7\u6df1\u6cd5\u91ab\u99ac\u5ba3\u7acb\uff1a\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u6d6e\u5c4d\u5168\u88f8\u6709\u53ef\u7591\u8b66\u61c9\u516c\u958b\u66f4\u591a\u8abf\u67e5\u8cc7\u6599|website=Apple Daily |language=zh|access-date=3 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hkcnews.com/article/24280/\u99ac\u5ba3\u7acb-\u6cd5\u91ab-\u9673\u5f65\u9716-24287/\u4efb\u6cd5\u91ab30\u5e74\u99ac\u5ba3\u7acb\uff1a\u59e6\u6bba\u6848\u4ee5\u5916\u751a\u5c11\u907a\u9ad4\u4e00\u7d72\u4e0d\u639b-\u5fc5\u9808\u5728\u6b7b\u56e0\u5ead\u89e3\u958b\u7591\u5718|title=\u4efb\u6cd5\u91ab30\u5e74\u99ac\u5ba3\u7acb\uff1a\u59e6\u6bba\u6848\u4ee5\u5916\u751a\u5c11\u907a\u9ad4\u4e00\u7d72\u4e0d\u639b \u5fc5\u9808\u5728\u6b7b\u56e0\u5ead\u89e3\u958b\u7591\u5718|website=\u773e\u65b0\u805e|language=zh|access-date=3 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Death of Chow Tsz-lok]]\n*[[Death of Luo Changqing]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019 Hong Kong protests|state=autocollapse}}\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n\n[[Category:2019 in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests]]\n[[Category:Suicides by drowning in China]]\n[[Category:Female suicides]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Death during the 2019 Hong Kong protests}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Chan Yin-lam\n| image = Chan Yin-lam on 19 September 2019.jpg\n| image_size = <!-- Image Size -->\n| alt = <!-- Image Substitution -->\n| caption = CCTV footage released by the [[Hong Kong Design Institute]] of Chan the day of her death, 19 September 2019\n| birth_date = 2004\n| birth_place = Hong Kong\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=y|2019|9|19|2004}}\n| death_place = Hong Kong\n| death_cause = \n| body_discovered = [[Yau Tong]], Hong Kong\n| monuments = <!-- Memorial Building -->\n| residence = <!-- place of residence -->\n| nationality = [[Hongkonger]]\n| permanent_residency = <!-- Permanent residency -->\n| other_names = <!-- alias -->\n| ancestor = \n| ethnicity = <!-- ethnic -->\n| language = <!-- Language -->\n| education = \n| alma_mater = [[Hong Kong Design Institute]]\n| occupation = Student\n| known_for = <!-- Well-known reasons -->\n| height = 1.53m (5 ft 0 inches)\n| weight = <!-- weight -->\n| movement = [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|2019 Hong Kong protests]]\n| influenced = <!-- influences -->\n}}\nThe '''death of Chan Yin-lam''', a 15-year-old female, occurred on or shortly after 19 September 2019. Her naked corpse was found floating in the sea near [[Yau Tong]], Hong Kong on 22 September 2019. Following a preliminary autopsy, police asserted that no foul play was suspected, and that Chan had committed suicide.<ref name=\"Suicide\">{{Cite web|url=https://thestandnews.com/politics/15-%E6%AD%B2%E5%A5%B3%E7%94%9F%E9%99%B3%E5%BD%A5%E9%9C%96%E6%B5%AE%E5%B1%8D%E6%B5%B7%E9%9D%A2-%E8%AD%A6-%E7%84%A1%E5%9B%A0%E5%8F%8D%E4%BF%AE%E4%BE%8B%E5%85%AC%E7%9C%BE%E6%B4%BB%E5%8B%95%E8%A2%AB%E6%8D%95-%E5%88%9D%E6%AD%A5%E8%AA%BF%E6%9F%A5%E8%A7%A3%E5%89%96%E6%AD%BB%E5%9B%A0%E7%84%A1%E5%8F%AF%E7%96%91/|title=15 \u6b72\u5973\u751f\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u6d6e\u5c4d\u6d77\u9762 \u8b66\uff1a\u7121\u56e0\u53cd\u4fee\u4f8b\u516c\u773e\u6d3b\u52d5\u88ab\u6355 \u521d\u6b65\u8abf\u67e5\u89e3\u5256\u6b7b\u56e0\u7121\u53ef\u7591 &#124; \u7acb\u5834\u5831\u9053 &#124; \u7acb\u5834\u65b0\u805e|website=Stand News |language=zh|location=Hong Kong|access-date=4 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116085725/https://thestandnews.com/politics/15-%E6%AD%B2%E5%A5%B3%E7%94%9F%E9%99%B3%E5%BD%A5%E9%9C%96%E6%B5%AE%E5%B1%8D%E6%B5%B7%E9%9D%A2-%E8%AD%A6-%E7%84%A1%E5%9B%A0%E5%8F%8D%E4%BF%AE%E4%BE%8B%E5%85%AC%E7%9C%BE%E6%B4%BB%E5%8B%95%E8%A2%AB%E6%8D%95-%E5%88%9D%E6%AD%A5%E8%AA%BF%E6%9F%A5%E8%A7%A3%E5%89%96%E6%AD%BB%E5%9B%A0%E7%84%A1%E5%8F%AF%E7%96%91/|archive-date=16 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Her death was the subject of a [[conspiracy theory]] that alleged that the government murdered her for participating in the [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|2019 Hong Kong protests]].<ref name=\"Yahoo\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/fake-news-stoking-violence-anger-210000243.html|title=How Fake News and Rumors Are Stoking Division in Hong Kong|date=12 November 2019|accessdate=3 December 2019|publisher=[[Bloomberg News]]|via=[[Yahoo! News|Yahoo!]]|author1=Shelly Banjo|author2=Natalie Lung|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128003944/https://news.yahoo.com/fake-news-stoking-violence-anger-210000243.html|archive-date=28 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Victim == \nChan Yin-lam was 15 years old, and her parents were separated. With a \"complicated\" family background, she had a history of running away from home.<ref name=appledaily20785021/> Prior to her disappearance, she had been staying at a [[Women's shelter|girls' home]].<ref name=thestandard212706/>\n\nShe attended the Pok Oi Hospital Tang Pui King Memorial College, Hong Kong, and had, just a few days prior to her disappearance, started a course at the Youth College attached to the [[Vocational Training Council]] (VTC). She also worked a part-time job in the restaurant trade.<ref name=appledaily20785021/> Media reports indicate that Chan had won awards in inter-school swimming competitions.<ref name=scmp3032907/> Chan had received regular diving training and was once a member of the diving team.<ref name=Apple20785020>{{Cite web|title=\u5168\u88f8\u5973\u6d6e\u5c4d \u70ba15\u6b72\u6cf3\u5c07 \u66fe\u8d74\u53cd\u9001\u4e2d\u793a\u5a01|url=https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20191011/20785020|date=11 October 2019|accessdate=14 October 2019|work=Apple Daily |language=zh|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014131043/https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20191011/20785020|archive-date=14 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to her friends, she had attended protests, while police confirmed that Chan had not been arrested during the [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|2019 protests]].<ref name=scmp3032907/>\n\n== Disappearance and death ==\nOn 19 September at 14:15, Chan separated from friends at Mei Foo and sent a message to her friends stating she was going back home. It was her last message before her disappearance.<ref name=appledaily20785021>{{Cite web|url=https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20191011/20785021|title=\u597d\u53cb\uff1a\u4f62\u60f3\u91cd\u65b0\u51fa\u767c|work=Apple Daily |language=zh|accessdate=14 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014131045/https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20191011/20785021|archive-date=14 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Friends put out a missing person's brief after she failed to reappear;<ref name=Apple20785020/> her family called the police on 21 September.<ref name=\"hkej-191011-1\">{{cite news|url=https://www2.hkej.com/instantnews/current/article/2273802/\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u4e8b\u4ef6+\u8b66\u65b9\u6307\u7d93\u89e3\u5256\u7121\u53ef\u7591|title=\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u4e8b\u4ef6 \u8b66\u65b9\u6307\u7d93\u89e3\u5256\u7121\u53ef\u7591|date=11 October 2019}}</ref> According to surveillance footage from Youth College she attended, she left the campus barefoot and walked towards the waterfront near Tseung Kwan O on 19 September. She was reported missing two days later.<ref name=scmp3032907/>\n\nMTR confirmed that station cleaners had found her mobile phone and some stationery belonging to Chan on the ground near an exit of [[Tiu Keng Leng Station]], while the station staff have contacted Chan's family members in accordance with the phonebook of the mobile phone. Her family member picked up the lost property two days later.<ref name=hk01386420>{{cite news|url=https://www.hk01.com/\u793e\u6703\u65b0\u805e/386420/\u6cb9\u5858\u5973\u6d6e\u5c4d-\u6e2f\u9435\u8b49\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u8abf\u666f\u5dba\u7ad9\u66fe\u907a\u624b\u6a5f-\u5bb6\u5c6c\u5169\u65e5\u5f8c\u9818\u56de|title=\u3010\u6cb9\u5858\u5973\u6d6e\u5c4d\u3011\u6e2f\u9435\u8b49\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u8abf\u666f\u5dba\u7ad9\u66fe\u907a\u624b\u6a5f\u3000\u5bb6\u5c6c\u5169\u65e5\u5f8c\u9818\u56de|date=15 October 2019|work=\u9999\u6e2f01|access-date=20 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016003035/https://www.hk01.com/%E7%A4%BE%E6%9C%83%E6%96%B0%E8%81%9E/386420/%E6%B2%B9%E5%A1%98%E5%A5%B3%E6%B5%AE%E5%B1%8D-%E6%B8%AF%E9%90%B5%E8%AD%89%E9%99%B3%E5%BD%A5%E9%9C%96%E8%AA%BF%E6%99%AF%E5%B6%BA%E7%AB%99%E6%9B%BE%E9%81%BA%E6%89%8B%E6%A9%9F-%E5%AE%B6%E5%B1%AC%E5%85%A9%E6%97%A5%E5%BE%8C%E9%A0%98%E5%9B%9E|archive-date=16 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt 11&nbsp;am on 22 September, a man who was fishing saw a floating object with a human form 100m off the coast from [[Devil's Peak, Hong Kong|Devil's Peak]]. Police boats were dispatched, and it was found to be the naked corpse of a human female. Police initially reported that the victim was a female suspected of being between 25 and 30 years of age, 1.5m in height, medium build, with long blond hair.According to a preliminary autopsy, there were no lacerations or contusions on her body, and no sign of sexual assault. Her death was therefore considered \"not suspicious\" by the police. Her body was cremated several days later.<ref name=\"Suicide\"/>\n\n==Conspiracy theories and reactions==\n[[File:Cy photo 20191015 upload 29.jpg|thumb|right|A [[Lennon Wall]] at [[Hong Kong Design Institute]], the school Chan attended before her death.]]\nFollowing her death, conspiracy theories emerged on social media that alleged that the police and government officials murdered her for participating in the [[2019 Hong Kong protests]] and then covered-up her death. The Hong Kong police and government have denied these allegations.<ref name=\"Suicide\"/><ref name=\"Yahoo\"/>\n\n=== HKDI footage ===\nFueled by these conspiracy theories, students from Youth College and [[Hong Kong Design Institute]] (HKDI) [[Tiu King Leng]] campus where she was a student gathered to demand the release of the CCTV footage taken on the evening of 19 September, where Chan was last seen before her death.<ref name=\"Yahoo\"/> On 15 October, after a sit-in, campus management agreed to accede to the demands and released some relevant footage. Dissatisfied with partial footage, disgruntled students demanded complete and unedited footage, giving a 30-minute deadline. Upon expiry of the deadline, the students vandalised school premises, damaged surveillance cameras and set off a fire alarm. The VTC later suspended all classes on the Tiu Keng Leng campus of the HKDI, Youth College and other institutions between 15 and 17 October.<ref name=scmp3032907>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3032907/classes-suspended-hong-kong-design-institute-after-students|title=Classes suspended at Hong Kong Design Institute after students vandalise campus demanding surveillance footage of classmate found dead in sea|last=Lew|first=Linda|date=15 October 2019|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020054908/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3032907/classes-suspended-hong-kong-design-institute-after-students|archive-date=20 October 2019|accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=20191016hongkongfp>{{cite web|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/10/16/protesters-demand-cctv-footage-tiu-keng-leng-school-following-death-15-year-old-student/|title=Protesters demand CCTV footage from Tiu Keng Leng school following death of 15-year-old student|last=Tong|first=Elson|date=16 October 2019|work=[[Hong Kong Free Press]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191018010938/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/10/16/protesters-demand-cctv-footage-tiu-keng-leng-school-following-death-15-year-old-student/|archive-date=18 October 2019|accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> The VTC has since released additional CCTV clips after 200 students, amid class suspension, rallied inside the campus to support an online appeal for an indefinite class boycott.<ref name=scmp3033257>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education/article/3033257/15-year-old-hong-kong-girl-found-dead-sea-had-walked|title=15-year-old Hong Kong girl found dead at sea had walked barefoot through campus before leaving school grounds on day she was last seen, new footage shows|last=Choi|first=Martin|date=16 October 2019|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020054907/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education/article/3033257/15-year-old-hong-kong-girl-found-dead-sea-had-walked|archive-date=20 October 2019|accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> The 16 clips released showed Chan wandering around campus for more than an hour.<ref name=thestandard212706/>\n\nAfter the Design Institute had disclosed surveillance videos and the girl's mother had appealed for an end to the speculation of Chan's death, students continued to demand the release of integral footage from surveillance cameras for 29 and 30 October. Masked protesters accused the school of downplaying the situation; they continued to damage facilities and equipment on campus for two days, with the police ended up having to be called.<ref name=\"scmp3035605\" />\n\n=== Interview of Chan's mother ===\nIn an interview with TVB News on 17 October, Chan's mother Ho Pui-yee said that after looking at all the relevant CCTV footage, she was satisfied that her daughter's death was suicide.<ref name=thestandard212706>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/section-news.php?id=212706|title=Mother of tragedy girl asks for peace|website=The Standard}}</ref><ref name=scmp3033448>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3033448/mother-15-year-old-hong-kong-girl-found-dead-sea-says|title=Mother says Hong Kong girl, 15, found dead in sea 'took her own life'|date=17 October 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref> She said that although she was initially suspicious of the death of Chan, she said that her daughter was emotionally unstable, and she may well have had psychosis as demonstrated by auditory hallucination.<ref name=thestandard212706/><ref name=scmp3033448/><ref name=asiatimes>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/10/article/friends-not-convinced-girls-death-was-suicide/|title=Friends not convinced girl's death was suicide |website=Asia Times Online|access-date=27 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030094011/https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/10/article/friends-not-convinced-girls-death-was-suicide/|archive-date=30 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"MKUltra\">{{YouTube|id=TeHp6YoMkBw|title=\u9999\u6e2f\u4fdd\u885b\u6230\u4e4bMK Ultra\u9673\u5f65\u9716}}</ref> She said that her daughter once participated in distributing the leaflet of the protests in June, but had become disillusioned by July.<ref name=thestandard212706/><ref name=scmp3033448/> She added that she had been [[doxing|dox]]xed since her daughter's death, resulting in her being harrassed at work and telephoned at all hours.<ref name=scmp3033448/><ref name=tvb6038380295/> Ho pleaded to the general public to end the speculation and for her to be left alone.<ref name=thestandard212706/><ref name=scmp3035605>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education/article/3035605/hong-kong-design-institute-vandalised-second-straight-day|title=Design institute vandalised again after school chiefs fail to meet students|date=30 October 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref name=scmp3033448/><ref name=tvb6038380295>{{Cite web|url=http://news.tvb.com/local/5da84727e6038380295c27b2/\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u5abd\u5abd\u63a5\u53d7\u5c08\u8a2a\u6307\u76f8\u4fe1\u5973\u5152\u81ea\u6bba-\u5180\u8b20\u8a00\u76e1\u5feb\u505c\u6b62\u9084\u5979\u5011\u5be7\u975c|title=\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u5abd\u5abd\u63a5\u53d7\u5c08\u8a2a\u6307\u76f8\u4fe1\u5973\u5152\u81ea\u6bba \u5180\u8b20\u8a00\u76e1\u5feb\u505c\u6b62\u9084\u5979\u5011\u5be7\u975c|website=TVB News|access-date=12 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017121914/http://news.tvb.com/local/5da84727e6038380295c27b2/%25E9%2599%25B3%25E5%25BD%25A5%25E9%259C%2596%25E5%25AA%25BD%25E5%25AA%25BD%25E6%258E%25A5%25E5%258F%2597%25E5%25B0%2588%25E8%25A8%25AA%25E6%258C%2587%25E7%259B%25B8%25E4%25BF%25A1%25E5%25A5%25B3%25E5%2585%2592%25E8%2587%25AA%25E6%25AE%25BA-%25E5%2586%2580%25E8%25AC%25A0%25E8%25A8%2580%25E7%259B%25A1%25E5%25BF%25AB%25E5%2581%259C%25E6%25AD%25A2%25E9%2582%2584%25E5%25A5%25B9%25E5%2580%2591%25E5%25AF%25A7%25E9%259D%259C|archive-date=17 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHo's interview and the police's assertion that Chan had committed suicide were met with skepticism. A political activist who knows Chan's brother cast doubt on the assertion that Chan had committed suicide by drowning herself in the sea, citing the fact that Chan was an award-winning swimmer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/10/article/friends-not-convinced-girls-death-was-suicide/|title=Friends not convinced girl's death was suicide |website=Asia Times Online|access-date=3 February 2020}}</ref> Retired [[coroner]] Philip Beh commented that the circumstances of the discovery and cremation of Chan's body were suspicious: discoveries of fully naked bodies in the sea are generally treated as suspect and would require thorough investigations, yet Beh's opinion is that Chan's body was hastily cremated after a preliminary autopsy. Beh opined that police should release further information about the autopsy and a coroner's inquest should be undertaken to allay suspicions of police misconduct.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hk.appledaily.com/local/20191014/SMRVGN2YZC7J6ULDZZX6BVU6LI/|title=\u8cc7\u6df1\u6cd5\u91ab\u99ac\u5ba3\u7acb\uff1a\u9673\u5f65\u9716\u6d6e\u5c4d\u5168\u88f8\u6709\u53ef\u7591\u8b66\u61c9\u516c\u958b\u66f4\u591a\u8abf\u67e5\u8cc7\u6599|website=Apple Daily |language=zh|access-date=3 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hkcnews.com/article/24280/\u99ac\u5ba3\u7acb-\u6cd5\u91ab-\u9673\u5f65\u9716-24287/\u4efb\u6cd5\u91ab30\u5e74\u99ac\u5ba3\u7acb\uff1a\u59e6\u6bba\u6848\u4ee5\u5916\u751a\u5c11\u907a\u9ad4\u4e00\u7d72\u4e0d\u639b-\u5fc5\u9808\u5728\u6b7b\u56e0\u5ead\u89e3\u958b\u7591\u5718|title=\u4efb\u6cd5\u91ab30\u5e74\u99ac\u5ba3\u7acb\uff1a\u59e6\u6bba\u6848\u4ee5\u5916\u751a\u5c11\u907a\u9ad4\u4e00\u7d72\u4e0d\u639b \u5fc5\u9808\u5728\u6b7b\u56e0\u5ead\u89e3\u958b\u7591\u5718|website=\u773e\u65b0\u805e|language=zh|access-date=3 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Death of Chow Tsz-lok]]\n*[[Death of Luo Changqing]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019 Hong Kong protests|state=autocollapse}}\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n\n[[Category:2019 in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests]]\n[[Category:Suicides by drowning in China]]\n[[Category:Female suicides]]\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Death_of_Chan_Yin-lam"}
{"title_page": "Coney Island", "text_new": "{{other uses|Coney Island (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Coney Island\n| native_name             =\n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| settlement_type         = [[Neighborhoods of Brooklyn|Neighborhood of Brooklyn]]\n| image_skyline           = Coney Island beach and amusement parks (June 2016).jpg\n| imagesize               = 300px\n| image_alt               =\n| image_caption           = Coney Island beach, amusement parks, and high rises as seen from the pier in June 2016\n| image_flag              =\n| flag_alt                =\n| image_seal              =\n| seal_alt                =\n| image_shield            =\n| shield_alt              =\n| nickname=\"Playground of the World\"\n| motto                   =\n| image_map               = {{maplink|frame=y|plain=y|frame-align=center|zoom=12|type=shape|from=Neighbourhoods/New York City/Coney Island.map}}<!--{{maplink|frame=y|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-lat=40.705|frame-long=-73.975|zoom=9|type=point|coord={{coord|40.574|-73.978}}}}-->\n| map_alt                 =\n| map_caption             = Location in New York City<br>Note: red area overlaps with Sea Gate.\n| pushpin_map             = <!--USA New York City#USA New York#USA-->\n| pushpin_label_position  =\n| pushpin_map_alt         =\n| pushpin_map_caption     = <!--Location-->\n| coordinates             = {{coord|40.574|-73.978|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           =\n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|United States}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = {{flag|New York}}\n| subdivision_type2       = [[City]]\n| subdivision_name2       = {{flagicon image|Flag of New York City.svg}} [[New York City]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Borough (New York City)|Borough]]\n| subdivision_name3       = {{flagicon image|Flag of Borough of Brooklyn.png}} [[Brooklyn]]\n| subdivision_type4       = [[Community boards of Brooklyn|Community District]]\n| subdivision_name4       = [[Brooklyn Community Board 13|Brooklyn 13]]<ref name=\"NYCPlanning\">{{cite web |title=NYC Planning {{!}} Community Profiles|url=https://communityprofiles.planning.nyc.gov/brooklyn/13|website=communityprofiles.planning.nyc.gov|publisher=New York City Department of City Planning|accessdate=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| established_title       = Settled\n| established_date        = 17th century\n| founder                 = Dutch settlers\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_total_km2          = 1.790\n| population_footnotes    =\n| population_total        = 24,711\n| population_as_of        = 2010\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      =\n| population_note         =\n| timezone1 = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern]]\n| utc_offset1 = \u22125\n| timezone1_DST = [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n| utc_offset1_DST = \u22124\n| postal_code_type        = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code             = 11224\n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbering plan|Area code]]\n| area_code               = [[Area codes 718, 347, and 929|718, 347, 929]], and [[Area code 917|917]]\n}}\n\n'''Coney Island''' is a residential and commercial [[List of Brooklyn neighborhoods|neighborhood]] and entertainment area, located on a [[peninsula]] in the southwestern part of the [[borough (New York City)|borough]] of [[Brooklyn]] in [[New York City]]. The neighborhood is bounded by [[Manhattan Beach, Brooklyn|Manhattan Beach]] to its east, [[Lower New York Bay]] to the south and west, and [[Gravesend, Brooklyn|Gravesend]] to the north, and includes the subsections of [[Sea Gate, Brooklyn|Sea Gate]] to its west and [[Brighton Beach]] to its east. Coney Island was formerly the westernmost of the [[Outer Barrier]] islands on the southern shore of [[Long Island]], but in the early 20th century it became a peninsula, connected to the rest of Long Island by [[Land reclamation|land fill]].\n\nThe origin of Coney Island's name is disputed, but the area was originally part of the colonial town of Gravesend. By the mid-19th century it had become a [[seaside resort]], and by the late 19th century, [[amusement park]]s had also been built at the location. The attractions reached a historical peak during the first half of the 20th century. However, they declined in popularity after [[World War II]], and following years of neglect, several structures were torn down. Various redevelopment projects were proposed for Coney Island in the 1970s through the 2000s, though most of these were not carried out. The area was revitalized with the opening of [[MCU Park]] in 2001 and several amusement rides in the 2010s.\n\nConey Island has 31,965 residents as of the [[2010 United States Census]]. The neighborhood is ethnically diverse, and the neighborhood's poverty rate of 27% is slightly higher than that of the city as a whole.\n\nConey Island is part of [[Brooklyn Community Board 13|Brooklyn Community District 13]] and its primary [[ZIP Code]] is 11224.<ref name=\"NYCPlanning\" /> It is patrolled by the 60th Precinct of the [[New York City Police Department]].<ref name=\"NYPD 60th Precinct\" /> Fire services are provided by the [[New York City Fire Department]]'s Engine 245/Ladder 161/Battalion 43 and Engine 318/Ladder 166.<ref name=\"fdny-locs\" /> Politically, Coney Island is represented by the [[New York City Council]]'s 47th District.<ref>[http://www.nyc.gov/html/dc/downloads/pdf/brooklyn.pdf Current City Council Districts for Kings County], [[New York City]]. Accessed May 5, 2017.</ref> The area is well served by the [[New York City Subway]] and local bus routes, and contains several public elementary and middle schools.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:ConeyIslandAerial.jpg|left|thumb|250px|The Coney Island peninsula from the air]]\nThe Coney Island neighborhood is generally coextensive with the [[peninsula]] of the same name, located on the western end of [[Long Island]] lying to the west of the [[Outer Barrier]] islands along Long Island's southern shore. The peninsula is about {{convert|4|mi|km}} long and {{convert|0.5|mi|km}} wide. It extends into [[Lower New York Bay]] with [[Sheepshead Bay]] to its northeast, Gravesend Bay and [[Coney Island Creek]] to its northwest, and the main part of Brooklyn to its north. At its highest it is {{convert|7|feet|m}} above sea level. Coney Island was formerly an actual island, separated from greater Brooklyn by Coney Island Creek, and was the westernmost of the Outer Barrier islands. A large section of the creek was filled in the 1920s and 1930s, turning the island into a peninsula.<ref name=\"auto\" /> A narrower definition of the Coney Island neighborhood is given by the ''[[Encyclopedia of New York City]]'', which only considers the area west of Ocean Parkway (including Sea Gate and [[Nortons Point Light]]) to be part of that neighborhood.<ref>{{cite enc-nyc2|page=299}}</ref>\n\nThe perimeter of Coney Island features manmade structures designed to maintain its current shape. The beaches are currently not a natural feature; the sand that is naturally supposed to replenish Coney Island is cut off by the [[jetty]] at [[Breezy Point, Queens]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">[https://3dparks.wr.usgs.gov/nyc/parks/loc72.htm U.S. Geological Survey, Geology of National Parks, 3D and Photographic Tours, 72. Coney Island], [[United States Department of the Interior]]. Accessed December 15, 2016.</ref><ref name=NYC.gov-ResilientNY-Ch17 />{{rp|337}} Sand has been redeposited on the beaches via [[beach nourishment]] since the construction of [[Riegelmann Boardwalk]] in 1922\u20131923,<ref>{{cite conference|last=Dornhelm|first=Richard B.|title=The Coney Island Public Beach and Boardwalk Improvement of 1923|publisher=American Society of Civil Engineers | location=Reston, VA|date=September 25, 2003|isbn=978-0-7844-0682-3|doi=10.1061/40682(2003)6|page=}}</ref> and is held in place by around two dozen [[groyne]]s. A large sand-replenishing project along Coney Island and Brighton Beach took place in the 1990s.<ref name=NYC.gov-ResilientNY-Ch17 />{{rp|337}} Sheepshead Bay at the peninsula's northeast corner is, for the most part, enclosed in [[Bulkhead (barrier)|bulkheads]].<ref name=\"NYC.gov-ResilientNY-Ch17\">{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/sirr/downloads/pdf/Ch17_SouthernBrooklyn_FINAL_singles.pdf|title=A Stronger, More Resilient New York|chapter=Chapter 17, Southern Brooklyn|pages=335\u2013364|publisher=[[Government of New York City|City of New York]]|date=2013|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> Two major parks, Kaiser Park and Coney Island Creek Park, are located on the northwest side of the peninsula along Coney Island Creek.<ref name=\"NYC Parks Kaiser\" /><ref name=\"NYC Parks CIC\" />\n\n== Name ==\nThe original [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] inhabitants of the region, the [[Lenape]], called this area ''Narrioch''. This name has been attributed the meaning of \"''land without shadows''\"<ref name=\"Solomon 1999\" /> or \"''always in light''\"<ref>{{cite book |via=HathiTrust | url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/008511115 |title=Brooklyn before the bridge: American paintings from the Long Island Historical Society |publisher=Long Island Historical Society, Brooklyn Museum |year=1982 |page=54 | access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> describing how its south facing beaches always remained in sunlight. A second meaning attributed to ''Narrioch'' is \"''point''\" or \"''corner of land''\".<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=c5hky9f5PgoC | last=Pritchard | first=Evan | title=Native New Yorkers : the legacy of the Algonquin people of New York | publisher=Council Oak Books | location=San Francisco | year=2002 | isbn=978-1-57178-107-9 | oclc=46937559 | page=105}}</ref>\n\nThere is no clear historical consensus on how the island got the name \"Coney Island\".<ref name=Name /><ref name=\"Henin\" /><ref name=\"Solomon 1999\">{{cite book | last=Solomon |first=Steve | title=Coney Island | publisher=Top Hat Press | location=Baltimore, MD | year=1999 | isbn=978-0-912509-08-2 | oclc=42191804 | page=13}}</ref> A version of this name, ''Conyne Eylandt'', shows up in early 17th century Dutch maps.<ref name=\"hunter\">{{cite book |last1= Hunter |first1=Douglas|date=2009|title= Half Moon: Henry Hudson and the Voyage that Redrew the Map of the New World|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=kMykb1AbSHsC&pg=PA165|publisher= Bloomsbury Publishing USA|page=278|isbn=978-1-60819-098-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Schwartz | first=Seymour I. | last2=Ehrenberg | first2=Ralph E. | title=The mapping of America | publisher=H.N. Abrams | year=1980 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KCQYAQAAMAAJ | access-date=October 20, 2019 | page=108}}</ref> The most popular theory is the name came from the old spelling of the Dutch word for [[rabbit]], \"conyn\", derived from a purported large population of wild rabbits, giving it the name \"Rabbit Island\",<ref name=\"autogenerated51\">{{cite book |last= Sijs van der |first= Nicoline |authorlink= Nicoline van der Sijs |date=2009 |title= Cookies, Coleslaw, and Stoops: The Influence of Dutch on the North American Languages |page=51 |isbn= 978-9089641243}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web | url = http://international.loc.gov/intldl/awkbhtml/kb-1/kb-1-2-5.html | title = The Atlantic World: Dutch Place Names | website = The Dutch in America, 1609\u20131664 | publisher = The Library of Congress | access-date = May 10, 2016 }}</ref> with the name being [[Anglicisation|anglicized]] to ''Coney Island'' after the English took over the colony in 1664,<ref>*{{cite web|first=Robert|last=Morden|author-link=Robert Morden|title=A Map of ye English Empire in the Continent of America|date=1690|url=http://www.sunysb.edu/libmap/ch1.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060420012731/http://www.sunysb.edu/libmap/ch1.htm |archive-date=April 20, 2006 |postscript=&nbsp;(Coney Island is labelled \"Conney Isle\".)}}\n* Henry Popple, \"A Map of the British Empire in America\", Sheet 12, 1733. Coney Island is labeled \"Coney Island\".\n* [[Joseph Frederick Wallet DesBarres|Joseph DesBarre's]] chart of New York harbor in the 1779 work ''Atlantic Neptune'', as cited in {{cite book | last=Sanderson | first=Eric | title=Mannahatta : a natural history of New York City | publisher=Abrams | location=New York | year=2009 | isbn=978-0-8109-9633-5 | oclc=258332257 | page=47 }} In 1779 the island was a cluster of three low hummocks in the shallow \"East Bank\" flats at the eastern end of [[Gravesend Bay]].\n* John H. Eddy, \"Map Of The Country Thirty Miles Round the City of New York\", 1811. Coney Island is labeled \"Coney I.\"</ref> ''[[wikt:coney#English|coney]]'' being the corresponding English word.<ref name=\"autogenerated51\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated2\" /><ref name=\"Coney etymology\">{{cite web|title=''coney''|url=https://www.etymonline.com/search?q=coney|website=Online Etymology Dictionary|access-date=March 2, 2018}}</ref> It could also be a corruption of the name of the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] tribe, the Konoh or Konoi (the \"Bear Band\"), who once inhabited the island.<ref name=\"Name\">{{cite web | title=Coney Island |work=American Experience |publisher=PBS | date=February 4, 1991 | url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/films/coney/ | access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Henin\">Official Brooklyn Guide Book, Henin & Company, 1939, page 27</ref><ref name=\"Solomon 1999\" /> Other origins put forward include it was the surname of a family of Dutch settlers who lived there,<ref name=Name /> or that \"Conyne\" was a distortion of the name of [[Henry Hudson]]'s second mate on the [[Halve Maen]], [[John Colman]], who was slain by natives on the 1609 expedition and buried at a place they named Colman's Point, possibly coinciding with Coney Island.<ref name=hunter /><ref name=Name />\n\n== History ==\n=== Early settlement ===\n[[Giovanni da Verrazzano]] was the first European explorer to discover the island of Narrioch during his expeditions to the area in 1527 and 1529. He was subsequently followed by Henry Hudson.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|34}} The Dutch established the colony of [[New Amsterdam]] in present-day Coney Island in the early 17th century. The Native American population in the area dwindled as the Dutch settlement grew and the entire southwest section of present-day Brooklyn was purchased in 1645 from the Native Americans in exchange for a gun, a blanket, and a kettle.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pritchard|first=E.T.|title=Native New Yorkers: The Legacy of the Algonquin People of New York|publisher=Council Oak Books|year=2002|isbn=978-1-57178-107-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c5hky9f5PgoC|access-date=July 21, 2018|page=106}}</ref><ref name=\"Douglass\">{{cite news|last=Douglass|first=Harvey|date=March 23, 1933|title=Coney Island Scenes Shift, Never Change|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/59998009/|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com|access-date=March 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1644, a colonist named Guysbert Op Dyck was given a patent for 88 acres of land in the town of [[Gravesend, Brooklyn|Gravesend]], on the southwestern shore of Brooklyn. The patent included Conyne Island, an island just off the southwestern shore of the town of Gravesend, as well as Conyne Hook, a peninsula just east of the island. At the time, both were part of Gravesend.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|4}}<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=http://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52628845/|title=Passed in Review|last=Currie|first=George|date=August 10, 1936|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=July 21, 2018|page=14|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com}}</ref> East of Conyne Hook was the largest section of island called Gysbert's, Guysbert's, or Guisbert's Island (also called Johnson Island), containing most of the arable land and extending east through today's [[Brighton Beach]] and [[Manhattan Beach, Brooklyn|Manhattan Beach]].<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|34}}<ref name=\"Ierardi\">{{cite book|last=Ierardi|first=Eric|title=Gravesend, the home of Coney Island|publisher=Arcadia | location=Charleston, S.C|year=2001|isbn=978-0-7385-2361-3|oclc=51632931|page=46}}</ref><ref name=\"heartofconeyisland1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.heartofconeyisland.com/early-coney-island-history.html|title=Coney Island History \u2013 Early History|website=Heart of Coney Island}}</ref> This was officially the first official real estate transaction for the island.<ref name=\":1\" />\nOp Dyck never occupied his patent, and in 1661 he sold it off to Dick De Wolf. The land's new owner banned Gravesend residents from using Guisbert's Island and built a salt-works on the land, provoking outrage among Gravesend livestock herders. New Amsterdam was transferred to the English in 1664, and four years later, the English Governor created a new charter for Gravesend that excluded Coney Island. Subsequently, Guisbert's Island was divided into plots meted out to several dozen settlers. However, in 1685, the island became part of Gravesend again as a result of a new charter with the Native Americans.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|36}}\n\n[[File:Coney Island (Detail) Chart of the entrance of Hudson's River, from Sandy Hook to New York - with the banks, depths of water, sailing-marks, &ca (NYPL b14099970-1222740).png|thumb|center|600px|Detail of a 1776 nautical chart showing the collection of islands and shifting sand that eventually became present day Coney Island.]]\n\nAt the time of European settlement, the land that makes up the present-day Coney Island was divided across several separate islands. All of these islands were part of the [[outer barrier]] on the southern shore of Long Island, and their land areas and boundaries changed frequently.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|34}} Only the westernmost island was called Coney Island; it currently makes up part of [[Sea Gate, Brooklyn|Sea Gate]]. At the time, it was a 1.25-mile shifting [[Spit (landform)|sandspit]] with a detached island at its western end extending into Lower New York Bay.<ref name=\"hunter\" /> In a 1679\u20131680 journal, Jasper Danckaerts and Peter Sluyter noted that \"Conijnen Eylandt\" was fully separated from the rest of Brooklyn. The explorers observed that \"Nobody lives upon it, but it is used in winter for keeping cattle, horses, oxen, hogs and others.\"<ref name=\"hunter\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|36}}\n\nBy the early 18th century, the town of Gravesend was periodically granting seven-year-long leases to freeholders, who would then have the exclusive use of Coney Hook and Coney Island. In 1734, a road to Coney Hook was laid out.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|37}}  Thomas Stillwell, a prominent Gravesend resident who was the freeholder for Coney Island and Coney Hook at the time, proposed to build a ditch through Coney Hook so it would be easier for his cattle to graze. He convinced several friends in the nearby town of [[Jamaica, Queens|Jamaica]] to help him in this effort, telling them that the creation of such a ditch would allow them to ship goods from [[Jamaica Bay]] to [[New York Harbor]] without having to venture out into the ocean.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|37}} In 1750, the \"Jamaica Ditch\" was dug through Coney Hook from Brown's Creek in the west to Hubbard's Creek in the east.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x9YsAAAAYAAJ|title=A History of the Town of Gravesend, N.Y.|last=Stockwell|first=A.P.|last2=Stillwell|first2=W.H.|year=1884|page=|access-date=July 21, 2018}}</ref>{{Rp|34}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coneyislandhistory.org/collection/filter/Jamaica-Ditch|title=Jamaica Ditch|website=Coney Island History Project|access-date=July 21, 2018}}</ref> The creation of the canal turned Coney Hook into a detached {{Convert|0.5|mi|km|-long|adj=mid}} island called Pine Island, so named due to the woods on it.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|34}}\n\nEach island was separated by an [[inlet]] that could only be crossed at low tide. By the end of the 18th century, the ongoing shifting of sand along the barrier islands had closed up the inlets to the point that residents began filling them in and joining them as one island. Development of Coney Island was slow until the 19th century due to land disputes, the [[American Revolutionary War]], and the [[War of 1812]].<ref name=\"heartofconeyisland1\" /> Coney Island was so remote that [[Herman Melville]] wrote ''[[Moby-Dick]]'' on the island in 1849, and [[Henry Clay]] and [[Daniel Webster]] discussed the [[Missouri Compromise]] at the island the next year.<ref name=BuffaloNews-LostGlamour-1957 />\n\n=== Resort development ===\n[[File:Railroad Station, Coney Island, Brooklyn, ca. 1872-1887. (5832942813).jpg|thumb|left|Railroad station in Coney Island, Brooklyn, ca. 1872\u20131887]]\n\nIn 1824, the Gravesend and Coney Island Road and Bridge Company built the first bridge across Jamaica Ditch (by now known as Coney Island Creek), connecting the island with the mainland. The company also built a shell road across the island to the beaches.<ref name=\"heartofconeyisland1\" /><ref name=\"BDE-YellowedPages-1939\">{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52755417/|title=Yellowed Pages of Coney Island Register Reveal Visits of Many Great and Near-Great of Day|date=March 5, 1939|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=July 21, 2018|page=11|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com}}</ref> In 1829, the company also built the first hotel on the island: the Coney Island House, near present day Sea Gate.<ref name=\"Phalen2016\">{{cite book|last=Phalen|first=William|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Coney_Island.html?id=2HCQDAAAQBAJ|title=Coney Island : 150 years of rides, fires, floods, the rich, the poor and finally Robert Moses|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers | location=Jefferson, North Carolina|year=2016|isbn=978-0-7864-9816-1|oclc=933438460}}</ref>{{rp|8}}<ref name=\"PBS\">{{cite web|title=American Experience. Coney Island. People & Events|website=PBS|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/coney/peopleevents/pande07.html|access-date=November 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=BDE-YellowedPages-1939 />\n\nDue to Coney Island's proximity to [[Manhattan]] and other boroughs, and its simultaneous relative distance from the city of Brooklyn to provide the illusion of a proper vacation, it began attracting vacationers in the 1830s and 1840s, assisted by carriage roads and steamship service that reduced travel time from a formerly half-day journey to two hours.<ref name=\"Berman York 2003 p. 15\">{{cite book|last=Berman|first=J.S.|last2=Museum of the City of New York|title=Coney Island|publisher=Barnes and Noble Books|series=Portraits of America|year=2003|isbn=978-0-7607-3887-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a_paj4cavDwC&pg=PA15|access-date=November 13, 2015}}</ref>{{rp|15}} Most of the vacationers were wealthy and went by carriage. Inventor [[Samuel Colt]] built an observation tower on the peninsula in 1845, but he abandoned the project soon after.<ref name=\"PBS\" /> In 1847, the middle class started going to Coney Island upon the introduction of a ferry line to Norton's Point\u2014named after hotel owner [[Michael Norton (New York state senator)|Michael Norton]]\u2014at the western portion of the peninsula. Gang activity started as well, with one 1870s writer noting that going to Coney Island could result in losing money and even lives.<ref name=\"PBS\" /> The [[Brooklyn, Bath and Coney Island Railroad]] became the first railroad to reach Coney Island when it opened in 1864,<ref>*{{cite news|work=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|location=[[Brooklyn]], NY|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/50404324|title=Travel|date=June 9, 1864|page=1}}\n* {{cite news|work=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|location=[[Brooklyn]], NY|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/50404348|title=Another New Rail Road|date=June 9, 1864|page=2}}</ref><ref name=\"Our Brooklyn 1936\" /> and it was completed in 1867.<ref name=\"Cudahy 2009\" />{{rp|71}} Over the next 13 years, four more railroads to be built specifically to transport visitors to Coney Island.<ref name=\"Cross Walton 2005\" />{{rp|14}}\n\nIn 1868, [[William A. Engeman]] built a resort in the area.<ref name=\"Coney Island Hotels\" /> The resort was given the name \"[[Brighton Beach]]\" in 1878 by [[Henry C. Murphy]] and a group of businessmen, who chose to name as an allusion to the English resort city of [[Brighton]].<ref name=\"Citycyclopedia\">{{cite book|author=Weinstein, Stephen|editor1=Jackson, Kenneth T.|editor2=Keller, Lisa|editor3=Flood, Nancy |editor-link= Kenneth T. Jackson|edition=2nd|date=2000|chapter=Brighton Beach|title=The Encyclopedia of New York City|isbn=0-300-11465-6|location=New York, NY, and New Haven, CT, USA|publisher=The New York Historical Society and Yale University Press|pages=139\u2013140|url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0300182570 |access-date=November 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Our Brooklyn 1936\">{{cite web|title=Brighton Beach History|website=Our Brooklyn|publisher=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]|date=August 30, 1936|url=http://www.bklynlibrary.org/ourbrooklyn/brightonbeach/|access-date=July 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117015009/http://www.bklynlibrary.org/ourbrooklyn/brightonbeach/|archive-date=November 17, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> With the help of Gravesend's surveyor [[William Stillwell]], Engeman acquired all 39 lots for the relatively low cost of $20,000.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Real Brighton Beach|website=The New Yorker|date=March 29, 2010|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/03/29/the-real-brighton-beach|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Phalen2016 />{{rp|38}} This {{convert|460|by|210|ft|m|adj=on}} hotel, with rooms for up to 5,000 people nightly and meals for up to 20,000 people daily, was close to the then-rundown western Coney Island, so it was mostly the upper middle class that went to this hotel.<ref name=\"Williams\">{{cite journal|last=Williams|first=Keith|title=Brighton Beach: Old World mentality, New World reality|url=http://theweeklynabe.wordpress.com/2012/07/29/brighton-beach-brooklyn-history/|journal=The Weekly Nabe|access-date=July 29, 2012}}</ref> The {{convert|400|ft|m|adj=on}}, double-decker Brighton Beach Bathing Pavilion was also built nearby and opened in 1878, with the capacity for 1,200 bathers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Engeman's New Bathing Hotel|date=July 1, 1878|page=1|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com|url=http://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/50423388/|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Phalen2016 />{{rp|38}}<ref name=\"Our Brooklyn 1936\" /> \"Hotel Brighton\", also known as the \"Brighton Beach Hotel\", was situated on the beach at what is now the foot of [[Coney Island Avenue]].<ref name=\"Coney Island Hotels\">{{cite web|last=Stanton|first=Jeffrey|date=1997|title=Coney Island&nbsp;\u2014 Luxury Hotels|publisher=Coney Island History Site|url=http://www.westland.net/coneyisland/articles/luxuryhotels.htm|access-date=November 12, 2015}}</ref> The [[Brooklyn, Flatbush, and Coney Island Railway]], the predecessor to the [[New York City Subway]]'s present-day [[BMT Brighton Line|Brighton Line]], opened on July 2, 1878, and provided access to the hotel.<ref name=\"NYCS 2001\">{{cite web|last=Feinman|first=Mark S.|title=Early Rapid Transit in Brooklyn, 1878\u20131913|publisher=nycsubway.org|date=February 17, 2001|url=http://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/Early_Rapid_Transit_in_Brooklyn,_1878-1913|access-date=November 12, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Phalen2016 />{{rp|38}}<ref name=\"NYTImes-AnotherRR-Jul1878\">{{cite web|title=ANOTHER CONEY ISLAND RAILROAD.; OPENING OF THE BROOKLYN AND FLATBUSH LINE TO BRIGHTON BEACH.|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 2, 1878|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1878/07/02/archives/another-coney-island-railroad-opening-of-the-brooklyn-and-flatbush.html|access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSimultaneously, wealthy banker [[August Corbin]] was developing adjacent [[Manhattan Beach, Brooklyn|Manhattan Beach]] after being interested in the area during a trip to the beach to heal his sick son.<ref name=\"Coney Island Hotels\" /><ref name=\"Features 2013\">{{cite web|title=The Upper-Class Brooklyn Resorts of the Victorian Era|website=Curbed NY|date=June 27, 2013|url=http://ny.curbed.com/archives/2013/06/27/the_upperclass_brooklyn_resorts_of_the_victorian_era.php|access-date=November 12, 2015}}</ref> Corbin, who worked on [[Wall Street]] and had many [[railroad]] investments, built the [[New York and Manhattan Beach Railway]] for his two luxury shoreline hotels. These hotels were used by the wealthy upper class, who would not go to Brighton Beach because of its proximity to Coney Island.<ref name=\"Coney Island Hotels\" /> The 150-room Manhattan Beach Hotel\u2014which was designed by [[J. Pickering Putnam]] and contained restaurants, ballrooms, and shops\u2014was opened for business in July 1877 at a ceremony presided over by President [[Ulysses S. Grant]].<ref name=\"Features 2013\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Wilderness Made Prosperous By One Man's Vision and Daring|date=July 11, 1954|page=7|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/54414817/|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref> The similarly prodigal Oriental Hotel, which hosted rooms for wealthy families staying for extended periods, was opened in August 1880.<ref name=\"Features 2013\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Opening Reception at the Oriental Hotel|date=August 3, 1880|page=3|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/50504406/|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Andrew R. Culver]], president of the [[Prospect Park and Coney Island Railroad]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1906/07/13/archives/obituary-1-no-title.html|title=Obituary 1 -- No Title|date=July 13, 1906|publisher=|via=query.nytimes.com}}</ref> had built a steam railway to West Brighton, the [[Culver Line (surface)|Culver Line]], before Corbin and Engeman had even built their railroads. For 35 cents, one could ride the Prospect Park & Coney Island Railroad to the [[Culver Depot]] terminal at Surf Avenue.<ref name=\"Coney Island Hotels\" /> Across the street from the terminal, the {{convert|300|ft|m|adj=on}} Iron Tower (also known as the Centennial Observartory), bought from the [[1876 Philadelphia Exposition]], provided patrons with a bird's-eye view of the coast. The nearby \"Camera Obscura\" similarly used mirrors and lens to provide a panoramic view of the area.<ref name=\"Coney Island Hotels\" /><ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|22\u201323}} Coney Island became a major resort destination after the Civil War as excursion [[rail transport|railroads]] and the [[Coney Island & Brooklyn Railroad]] [[streetcar line]] reached the area in the 1860s and 1870s, followed by the [[Iron Steamboat Company]] ferry to Manhattan in 1881.<ref name=Phalen2016 />{{rp|29}}<ref name=\"Cudahy 2009\">{{cite book|last=Cudahy|first=B.J.|title=How We Got to Coney Island: The Development of Mass Transportation in Brooklyn and Kings County|publisher=Fordham University Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0-8232-2211-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FtUzg07N0wwC|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>{{rp|64}}\n\n[[File:Dreamland tower 1907.jpg|thumb|right|[[Dreamland (Coney Island, 1904)|Dreamland]] tower and lagoon in 1907]]\n\nThe 150-suite Cable Hotel was built nearby in 1875.<ref name=\"NYCS 2001\" /> Next to it, on a {{convert|12|acre|ha|adj=on}} piece of land leased by James Voorhies, [[maitre d']] Paul Bauer built the western peninsula's largest hotel, which opened in 1876.<ref name=\"Coney Island Hotels\" /> By the turn of the century, Victorian hotels, private bathhouses, and [[vaudeville]] theaters were a common sight on Coney island.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\">{{cite book|author1=Judith N. DeSena|author2=Timothy Shortell|title=The World in Brooklyn: Gentrification, Immigration, and Ethnic Politics in a Global City|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S-YNs4ih1FUC|year=2012|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-0-7391-6670-3|pages=147\u2013176}}</ref>{{rp|147}} The three resort areas\u2014Brighton Beach, Manhattan Beach and West Brighton\u2014competed with each other for clientele. By the early 1900s, West Brighton had gradually become the most popular destination, and as such, became associated with the lively amusement area of Coney Island.<ref name=\"heartofconeyisland\">{{cite web|access-date=November 19, 2016|publisher=heartofconeyisland.com|url=http://www.heartofconeyisland.com/west-brighton-coney-island-history.html|title=Coney Island History: How 'West Brighton' became Modern-day Coney Island|author=David A. Sullivan}}</ref><ref name=\"Cross Walton 2005\" />{{rp|14\u201315}}\n\nIn the 1890s, Norton's Point on the western side of Coney Island was developed into [[Sea Gate, Brooklyn|Sea Gate]], a [[gated community|gated]] summer community that catered mainly to the wealthy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/50387044/|title=Sea Gate and Sheepshead|date=August 6, 1899|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=July 21, 2018|page=16|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=QUEST FOR RURAL HOMES; Toilers of Greater New York to Gain by Long Island Rapid Transit. TWENTY MINUTES TO JAMAICA Pretty Suburban Villas Springing Up in Anticipation of the Proposed Atlantic Avenue Tunnel -Grass and Air for All.|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 16, 1897|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1897/05/16/archives/quest-for-rural-homes-toilers-of-greater-new-york-to-gain-by-long.html|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref> A private yacht carried visitors directly from [[the Battery (Manhattan)|the Battery]] at the southern tip of Manhattan Island. Notable tenants within the community included the [[Atlantic Yacht Club]], which built a [[colonial style]] house along the waterfront.<ref>{{cite web|author=J.B.T.|title=SEA GATE.|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=August 14, 1898|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1898/08/14/archives/sea-gate.html|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Amusement park era ===\n\nBetween about 1880 and [[World War II]], Coney Island was the largest amusement area in the United States, attracting several million visitors per year. Its development as an amusement area was concurrent with the erection of urban amusement parks elsewhere in the United States, which changed amusement from a passive to an active concept.<ref name=\"Kasson 2011\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pRC1mjAzFXsC|title=Amusing the Million: Coney Island at the Turn of the Century|last=Kasson|first=J.F.|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|year=2011|isbn=978-1-4299-5223-1}}</ref>{{Rp|7, 8}} Of these amusement areas, Coney Island was the largest. At its height, it contained three competing major amusement parks\u2014[[Luna Park (Coney Island, 1903)|Luna Park]], [[Dreamland (Coney Island, 1904)|Dreamland]], and [[Steeplechase Park]]\u2014as well as many independent amusements.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|147\u2013150}}<ref name=\"Parascandola 2014\" />{{rp|11}}<ref name=\"Kasson 2011\" />{{Rp|4}} The area was also the center of new technological events, with electric lights, roller coasters, and [[baby incubator]]s among the innovations at Coney Island in the 1900s.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|147}} By the first decade of the 20th century, Coney Island was seen as a top getaway and \"a symbol of Americans' increasing pride\".<ref name=\"Parascandola 2014\" />{{rp|21\u201322}}\n\n==== 19th century ====\n[[File:The first carousel and amusement ride at Coney Island was hand-carved and built by Danish carver, Charles I. D. Looff and installed at Mrs. Lucy Vanderveer's Bathing Pavilion in 1876.jpg|thumb|left|First Coney Island Charles Looff carousel]]\n\nBy the late 1870s, Coney Island's hotels had drawn people from many different social classes, and attractions were being built.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|30}} When the [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit]] Company electrified the steam railroads and connected Brooklyn to [[Manhattan]] via the [[Brooklyn Bridge]] at the beginning of the 20th century, Coney Island turned rapidly from a resort to an accessible location for day-trippers seeking to escape the summer heat in New York City's [[apartment building|tenements]].<ref name=\"NYCS 2001\" /><ref name=\"Matus, Paul\">{{cite web|author=Matus, Paul|work=The Third Rail Online|title=The New BMT Coney Island Terminal|url=http://thethirdrail.net/0305/stillwell4.html|access-date=August 29, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926235717/http://thethirdrail.net/0305/stillwell4.html|archivedate=September 26, 2007}}</ref> [[Charles I. D. Looff]], a [[Denmark|Danish]] [[wood carving|woodcarver]], built the first carousel and amusement ride at Coney Island in 1876, at Lucy Vandeveer's bath-house complex at West 6th Street and Surf Avenue. Looff personally hand-carved the designs into the carousel.<ref name=\"Westland Network 1997\">{{cite web|title=Coney \u2013 Carousel List|website=Westland Network|date=August 27, 1997|url=http://www.westland.net/coneyisland/articles/carousellist.htm|access-date=November 13, 2015}}</ref> Looff subsequently commissioned another carousel at Feltman's Ocean Pavilion in 1880.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|88}} Another early attraction was the Seaside Aquarium, which operated from 1877 to 1887 and included aquatic exhibits, aviaries, zoo attractions, and various sideshows.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|31}}<ref name=\"Cross Walton 2005\">{{cite book | last=Cross | first=G. | last2=Walton | first2=J.K. | title=The Playful Crowd: Pleasure Places in the Twentieth Century | publisher=Columbia University Press | year=2005 | isbn=978-0-231-50283-2 | url=https://archive.org/details/playfulcrowdplea0000cros | url-access=registration | page=[https://archive.org/details/playfulcrowdplea0000cros/page/15 15] | access-date=October 21, 2019 }}</ref>{{rp|15}} The earliest rides, including Looff's first carousel and the Seaside Aquarium, were located at the Centennial Observatory's site.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|32}} The first sideshows and fireworks displays came to Coney Island in 1883, and combined with constant musical performances, brought increased excitement to the area.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|34\u201337}}\n\nThe very first [[roller coaster]] at Coney Island was the [[Switchback Railway]], a gravity coaster installed by [[LaMarcus Adna Thompson]] at West 10th Street in 1884. Nearby was the [[Elephantine Colossus]], a seven-story building (including a [[brothel]]) in the shape of an elephant, which opened the following year.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|38\u201339}} Until its demolition in 1896, the elephant was the first sight to greet immigrants arriving in New York, who would see it before they saw the [[Statue of Liberty]].<ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|40\u201342}}<ref name=\"heartofconeyislandelephant\">{{cite web|access-date=November 19, 2016|work=www.heartofconeyisland.com|url=http://www.heartofconeyisland.com/elephant-hotel-coney-island-history.html|title=Coney Island History: The Elephant Hotel and Roller Coaster (1885\u20131896)|author=David A. Sullivan}}</ref> Next to be developed were horse-racing tracks, and by 1890, Coney Island had three tracks: [[Sheepshead Bay Race Track]], [[Brighton Beach Race Course]], and [[Gravesend Race Track]].<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|46}} However, crime and corruption in Coney Island were prevalent. The main leader of this corruption was John Y. McKane, who ran prizefighting rings behind the elephant until he was arrested and sentenced in 1894.<ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|48\u201351}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://brooklyneagle.com/articles/2012/03/01/on-this-day-in-history-march-1-brooklyns-answer-to-boss-tweed/|title=On This Day in History, March 1: Brooklyn's Answer to Boss Tweed|date=February 1, 2012|website=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=July 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe development of amusement rides in Coney Island intensified in the 1890s with the opening of amusement parks. The first such park was the [[Sea Lion Park]], which opened in 1895 and continued operating until 1902, and was the first amusement park to charge entry fees. The Sea Lion Park's opening spurred the construction of George C. Tilyou's [[Steeplechase Park]], which opened in 1897.<ref name=\"Parascandola 2014\" />{{rp|12}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Remembering Parks Past|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 7, 1989|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/07/07/arts/remembering-parks-past.html|access-date=January 20, 2019}}</ref> The Coney Island \"Funny Face\" logo, which is still extant, dates to the early days of Steeplechase Park.<ref>{{cite web | title=\"The Face of Steeplechase\" at the Coney Island History Project | website=Brooklyn Paper | date=May 30, 2014 | url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/37/22/24-steeplechase-face-2014-05-30-bk_37_22.html | access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:1879 Coney Island.jpg|thumb|center|800px|Map of Coney Island in 1879]]\n\n==== 20th century ====\n[[File:Night in Luna Park, Coney Island (1905).jpg|thumb|Luna Park, seen 1905]]\n[[File:Potthast-coney-island.jpg|thumb|''Coney Island'', c. 1914, by [[Edward Henry Potthast]]]]\n\nThe first decade of the 20th century saw two more large amusement parks. Luna Park opened in 1903 on the site of the old Sea Lion Park, which had closed the previous year.<ref>{{cite web | title=LUNA PARK FIRST NIGHT; Coney Island Visitors Dazzled by Electric City. Many Colored Illuminations and Canals -- A Midway of Nations and a Trip to the Moon Replace the Old-Time Recreations. | website=The New York Times | date=May 17, 1903 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1903/05/17/archives/luna-park-first-night-coney-island-visitors-dazzled-by-electric.html | access-date=October 21, 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|60\u201361}} The park's flagship was [[A Trip to the Moon (attraction)|A Trip to the Moon]], an attraction based off [[Jules Verne]]'s novel ''[[From the Earth to the Moon]]'', which had previously been located at Steeplechase Park.<ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|62}} The following year saw the opening of Dreamland, which reproduced many attractions at Luna Park, but at a grander scale, with a large central tower and one million electric lights.<ref>{{cite web | title=NEW CONEY DAZZLES ITS RECORD MULTITUDE; Luna Park and Dreamland the Centres of Great Crush. 250,000 PERSONS AT ISLAND Novel and Costly Shows, with the Frankfurter and Peanut as Reminders of By-Gone Days. | website=The New York Times | date=May 15, 1904 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1904/05/15/archives/new-coney-dazzles-its-record-multitude-luna-park-and-dreamland-the.html | access-date=October 21, 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|68\u201369}} Additionally, the City of New York made efforts to condemn all buildings and piers built south of Surf Avenue in an effort to reclaim the beach and create a boardwalk, though the local amusement community opposed the move.<ref>{{cite web|title=CONEY ISLAND BOARDWALK.; Much Opposition to the Bill for a Public Recreation Ground.|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=February 27, 1901|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1901/02/27/archives/coney-island-boardwalk-much-opposition-to-the-bill-for-a-public.html|access-date=May 16, 2018}}</ref> Eventually a settlement was reached where the beach did not begin until {{convert|1000|ft|m}} south of Surf Avenue, the territory marked by a city-owned boardwalk, while the city would demolish any structures that had been built over public streets, to reclaim beach access.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coney Island Realty Settlement.|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 24, 1904|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1904/07/24/archives/coney-island-realty-settlement.html|access-date=January 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1915, the [[BMT Sea Beach Line|Sea Beach Line]] was upgraded to a [[rapid transit|subway]] line, followed by the other former excursion roads, and the opening of the [[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue (New York City Subway)|Stillwell Avenue]] station in 1919 ushered in Coney Island's busiest era.<ref name=\"NYCS 2001\" /><ref name=\"Matus, Paul\" /> On the busiest summer days, over a million people would travel to Coney Island. This created tensions between longtime New York City residents and more recent immigrants who liked to patronize Coney Island.<ref name=\"Parascandola 2014\" />{{rp|23}} One of the entrepreneurs who took advantage of the increased visitor counts was [[Nathan Handwerker]], who in 1916 started selling hot dogs at Coney Island for a nickel each, and eventually expanded his enterprise into the [[Nathan's Famous]] hot dog chain.<ref name=BuffaloNews-LostGlamour-1957 /><ref name=\"Parascandola 2014\" />{{rp|22\u201323}}\n\nConey Island's development as an amusement area continued through the end of World War II. The opening of the [[Wonder Wheel]] in 1920; the [[Riegelmann Boardwalk]] in 1923; the [[Shore Theater]] in 1925; several roller coasters in the 1920s including the [[Tornado (Coney Island)|Tornado]], [[Thunderbolt (1925 roller coaster)|Thunderbolt]], and [[Coney Island Cyclone]]; and the [[Parachute Jump]] in 1941 contributed to the area's quality as an amusement destination. In particular, the Riegelmann Boardwalk enabled the crowds to be dispersed away from Surf Avenue, the main west-east avenue in the area.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|147}}<ref name=\"Parascandola 2014\">{{cite book|last=Parascandola|first=L.J.|title=A Coney Island Reader: Through Dizzy Gates of Illusion|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2014|isbn=978-0-231-53819-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NDMzBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA24|access-date=January 20, 2019|page=24}}</ref>{{rp|23\u201324}} Despite staff shortages during World War II, Coney Island retained its popularity and was frequented by [[military personnel]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1943/06/27/archives/coney-has-a-war-boom-there-are-priorities-shortages-and-the-dimout.html|title=CONEY HAS A WAR BOOM; There Are Priorities, Shortages and the Dimout, but the Subway Is Convenient|last=Lindheim|first=Burton|date=June 27, 1943|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 18, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the era was also marked by frequent fires, and those at the beginning of the 20th century were particularly destructive.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/07/14/archives/early-coney-fires-razed-large-areas-dreamland-was-burned-in-1911.html|title=EARLY CONEY FIRES RAZED LARGE AREAS Dreamland Was Burned in 1911 With Damage Estimated at More Than $5,000,000.; STEEPLECHASE FIRE IN 1907 Loss Kept Down to $1,500,000 When Wind Shifted -- In 1908 Flames Destroyed Two Hotels.|date=July 14, 1932|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 12, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Elmira Star-Gazette\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33793308/|title=$3,000,000 Fire Sweeps Over Coney Island|date=July 14, 1932|work=Elmira Star-Gazette|access-date=July 12, 2019|page=1|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> A 1907 fire at Steeplechase Park<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1907/07/29/archives/coney-swept-by-1500000-fire-steeplechase-park-and-blocks-of-flimsy.html|title=CONEY SWEPT BY $1,500,000 FIRE; Steeplechase Park and Blocks of Flimsy Bowery Buildings in Ruins. STARTS IN CAVE OF WINDS Eats Over 35 Acres of Wooden Structures; Checked at Stauch's Brick Hotel. ONE MAY DIE; DOZEN HURT Many Uninsured Business Men Ruined -- Tilyou,Chief Loser, Takes It Bravely -- Coney's Gayety Is Unchecked. CONEY SWEPT BY $1,500,000 FIRE|date=July 29, 1907|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=|title=Investigating Fire at Coney; No More Tinsel Buildings|date=July 29, 1907|work=Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=|pages=[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33760417/ 1], [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33760426/ 10]|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref>  resulted in the park having to be completely rebuilt.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1909/05/16/archives/the-lambs-gambol-brooklyn-amusements-greater-dreamland-opening.html|title=The Lambs' Gambol.; Brooklyn Amusements. Greater Dreamland, Opening Steeplechase Park.|date=May 16, 1909|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Dreamland burned down in 1911<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1911/06/04/archives/rang-two-nines-for-dreamland-fire-first-time-the-call-ever-was.html|title=RANG 'TWO NINES' FOR DREAMLAND FIRE; First Time the Call Ever Was Sounded for a Fire in Brooklyn Borough. WHAT THE SIGNAL MEANS Called Out 33 Companies and 250 Men -- Longest Run Was More Than Nine Miles -- Great Race to the Sea.|date=June 4, 1911|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 12, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and was never rebuilt.<ref name=\":13\" /> One of the largest conflagrations at Coney Island, which occurred in 1932,<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\"Elmira Star-Gazette\" /> left at least a thousand people homeless.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/07/14/archives/1000-are-made-homeless-one-of-resorts-worst-fires-razes-section-of.html|title=1,000 ARE MADE HOMELESS; One of Resort's Worst Fires Razes Section of Boardwalk. BLAZE STARTS IN RUBBISH Burns District Between 21st and 24th Streets -- Shift in 40-Mile Wind Saves Large Area. FLAMES VISIBLE FOR MILES 500 Receive First-Aid -- Police Rush Help to the Destitute -- Manhattan Sends Apparatus. $5,000,000 FIRE SWEEPS CONEY|date=July 14, 1932|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 12, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe 20th century also saw the filling-in of a portion of the {{convert|3|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[Coney Island Creek]], thereby connecting Coney Island to the rest of Brooklyn. In the previous decades, there had been plans to dredge and straighten the creek as a [[ship canal]], which were later abandoned. By 1924, local land owners and the city had filled a portion of the creek.<ref name=NYC.gov-ResilientNY-Ch17 />{{rp|337}}<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://hiddenwatersblog.wordpress.com/2016/03/04/photo-of-the-week-9/|title=Photo of the Week|date=March 4, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> A major section of the creek was further filled in to allow construction of the [[Belt Parkway]] in the 1930s, and the western and eastern ends of the island became peninsulas. More fill was added in 1962 during the construction of the [[Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/06/nyregion/thecity/06grav.html/partner/rssnyt|title=The Ghost Ships of Coney Island Creek|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 6, 2006|access-date=June 11, 2014|author=JONAH OWEN LAMB}}</ref>\n\n=== Residential development and decline ===\n==== Robert Moses era ====\n[[File:Coney Island (ca. 1940s).ogv|thumb|thumbtime=44|alt=Coney Island, circa 1940|Coney Island, circa 1940]]\n[[File:Brooklyn Museum - Coney Island Bathers - Irving Underhill.jpg|thumb|Bathers in Coney Island by Irving Underhill, in the [[Brooklyn Museum]] collection]]\n\nIn 1937, New York City parks commissioner [[Robert Moses]] published a report about the possible redevelopment of Coney Island, which would have entailed the addition of parking lots and reconstruction of part of the boardwalk.<ref name=\"Beaches-Improvement-1937\">{{cite book|title=Improvement of Coney Island, Rockaway and South Beaches|last=Moses|first=Robert|via=Internet Archive|date=1937|url=https://archive.org/stream/improvementofcon00newy/improvementofcon00newy_djvu.txt|access-date=July 26, 2018}}</ref> The city purchased a {{convert|400|ft|m|-wide|adj=mid}} strip of land along the shoreline, which would allow the boardwalk to be moved {{convert|300|ft|m}} inland.<ref name=\"NYTimes-RevisedPlan-1939\">{{cite web|title=Mayor Ready to Remodel Coney, Asks Moses for Revised Plan; Indicates He Favors Reconstruction of Resort on Broader Scale Than 1937 Proposal-- Says Demand for Recreation Has Changed Mayor for Broad Plan Mayor's Letter to Moses Held Up by Lack of Funds|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=June 25, 1939|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1939/06/25/archives/mayor-ready-to-remodel-coney-asks-moses-for-revised-plan-indicates.html|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref> At this point, Coney Island was so crowded on summer weekends that Moses observed that a coffin would provide more space per person.<ref name=\"BuffaloNews-LostGlamour-1957\">{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Evening%2520News%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Evening%2520News%25201957%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Evening%2520News%25201957%2520-%25203502.pdf|title=Coney Isle Fishing For Way to Regain Its Lost Glamour|first=Edith Kermit|last=Roosevelt|work=Buffalo Evening News|date=June 1, 1957|access-date=July 26, 2018|via=fultonhistory.com}}</ref> Though ride construction was delayed due to material shortages caused by the onset of [[World War II]], two new rides were constructed in 1946 at the end of the war.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/05/05/archives/face-lifted-coney-awaits-old-gang-amusement-owners-put-paint-on-the.html|title=FACE LIFTED, CONEY AWAITS OLD GANG; Amusement Owners Put Paint on the Rides and Trot Out a Few New Super-Thrillers|date=May 5, 1946|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1944, [[Luna Park (Coney Island, 1903)|Luna Park]] was severely damaged by a fire.<ref>{{cite web|title=HALF OF LUNA PARK DESTROYED BY FIRE AS 750,000 WATCH; Flames Sweep Over 8-Acre Area and Cause $500,000 Loss in 1 1/2-Hour Battle|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=August 13, 1944|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1944/08/13/archives/half-of-luna-park-destroyed-by-fire-as-750000-watch-flames-sweep.html|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> Two years later, it was closed permanently and sold to a company who wanted to tear down the park's remnants and build [[Quonset hut]]s for military veterans and their families.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coney's OId Luna Park Will Yield To New Homes for 625 GI Families; LUNA PARK TO BOW TO HOMES FOR GI'S|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=August 18, 1946|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/08/18/archives/coneys-oid-luna-park-will-yield-to-new-homes-for-625-gi-families.html|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> Moses asked the city to transfer Luna Park's land along the Coney Island waterfront to the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation|Parks Department]], a request that was granted in 1949.<ref>{{cite web|title=NEW PARKING LOTS PLANNED BY MOSES; 25-Cent Fee Would Be Charged for Facilities at Coney Island and Rockaway Beach|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=August 18, 1949|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1949/08/18/archives/new-parking-lots-planned-by-moses-25cent-fee-would-be-charged-for.html|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> Moses then had the land rezoned for residential use, with plans to demolish \"about a third\" of attractions along Surf Avenue, one block north of the beach, and replace these with housing.<ref name=NYTimes-ConeyGimmicks-1949 /> Moses moved the boardwalk back from the beach several yards, demolishing many structures, including the city's municipal bath house, as well as several blocks of amusements.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|149}} He claimed that fewer amusement-seekers were going to Coney Island every year, because they preferred places where they could bathe outdoors, such as [[Jones Beach State Park]] on Long Island, rather than the \"mechanical gadget\" attractions of Coney Island.<ref name=\"NYTimes-ConeyGimmicks-1949\">{{cite web|title=PUBLIC SEEN TIRING OF CONEY GIMMICKS; Moses Says People Are Turning to Places Like Jones Beach as Against 'Gadget' Resorts LONG BEACH 'A WARNING' Commissioner Advises Jersey Group Not to Commercialize Sandy Hook Project|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=October 6, 1949|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1949/10/06/archives/public-seen-tiring-of-coney-gimmicks-moses-says-people-are-turning.html|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> Moses also announced that the Steeplechase Pier would be closed for a year so it could be renovated.<ref>{{cite web|title=STEEPLECHASE PIER PLAN; Closing in Summer Slated for $190,000 Rebuilding|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=April 7, 1949|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1949/04/07/archives/steeplechase-pier-plan-closing-in-summer-slated-for-190000.html|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, Moses proposed that most of the peninsula be rezoned for various uses, claiming that it would be an \"upgrade\" over the various business and unrestricted zones that existed at the time. Steeplechase Park would be allowed to remain open, but much of the shorefront amusements and concessions would be replaced by residential developments.<ref>{{cite web|title=Moses Asks Coney Island Rezoning To 'Upgrade' It as Residential Area; REZONING SOUGHT FOR CONEY ISLAND|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=April 2, 1953|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1953/04/02/archives/moses-asks-coney-island-rezoning-to-upgrade-it-as-residential-area.html|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref><ref name=BDE-Greatest-Aquarium-1954 /> After many complaints from the public and from concession operators, the Estimate Board reinstated the area between West 22nd and West Eighth Streets as an amusement-only zone, with the zone extending {{convert|200|to|400|ft|m}} inland from the shoreline.<ref>{{cite web|title=AMUSEMENT AREA IN CONEY EXEMPT; Estimate Board Votes Exclusion From Rezoning of a Section North of the Boardwalk|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=June 12, 1953|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1953/06/12/archives/amusement-area-in-coney-exempt-estimate-board-votes-exclusion-from.html|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=That Hot Dog Flavor To Remain at Coney|first=Clarence|last=Greenbaum|page=1|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com|date=June 12, 1953|url=http://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53706179/|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref> Moses's subsequent proposal to extend the Coney Island boardwalk east to Manhattan Beach was denied in 1955.<ref>{{cite web|title=CONEY EXTENSION DENIED TO MOSES; Estimate Board Rejects His Plan to Join Boardwalk With Manhattan Beach RESIDENTS PROTEST IT Their Willingness to Pay for Restoring Own Esplanade Spurs Unanimous Vote|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=September 23, 1955|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/09/23/archives/coney-extension-denied-to-moses-estimate-board-rejects-his-plan-to.html|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref> A proposal to make the Quonset hut development into a permanent housing structure was also rejected.<ref>{{cite web|title=PLANNERS OPPOSE HOUSING AT BEACH; Reject Proposal for Municipal Operation of Ex-G. I. Units -- Ask Quick Shift to Park WEIGH REZONING FOR TV N.B.C. Ties Favorable Vote on Flatbush Studio to Location of Its Color Operations|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 28, 1953|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1953/05/28/archives/planners-oppose-housing-at-beach-reject-proposal-for-municipal.html|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA new building for the [[New York Aquarium]] was approved for construction in the neighborhood in 1953.<ref name=\"Caro 1974\">{{Cite Power Broker}}</ref>{{rp|687}}<ref>{{cite web|title=PLAN OF AQUARIUM AT CONEY APPROVED; Estimate Board Appropriates $450,000 for First Stage -- Work Starts in Spring|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=October 23, 1953|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1953/10/23/archives/plan-of-aquarium-at-coney-approved-estimate-board-appropriates.html|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref> Construction started on the aquarium in 1954.<ref name=\"BDE-Greatest-Aquarium-1954\">{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/54529888/|title=Break Ground for World's Greatest Aquarium at Coney Island|first=Al|last=Salerno|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|date=October 24, 1954|pages=1, 21|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com}}</ref> The development of the new New York Aquarium was expected to revitalize Coney Island.<ref name=Billboard-19550129 /><ref name=BDE-Greatest-Aquarium-1954 /> By 1955, the area still included four children's amusement areas, five roller coasters, several [[flat ride|flat]] and [[dark ride]]s, and various other attractions such as the Wonder Wheel.<ref name=\"Billboard-19550129\">{{cite book|title=Coney Girds for '55; Aquarium Progressing|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UxkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA63|language=en|date=January 29, 1955|access-date=July 22, 2018|page=63}}</ref> The New York Aquarium's new site opened in June 1957.<ref name=\"NYParks-Aquarium-History\">{{cite web|title=History of the New York Aquarium : NYC Parks|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|date=May 31, 1934|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/about/history/zoos/ny-aquarium|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> At this point, there were still several dozen rides on Coney Island.<ref name=BuffaloNews-LostGlamour-1957 />\n\n==== Fred Trump era ====\nDuring the summers of 1964 and 1965, there was a large decrease in the number of visitors to Coney Island because of the [[1964 New York World's Fair|1964/1965 World's Fair]] at [[Flushing Meadows\u2013Corona Park]] in Queens.<ref name=\"Phillips 1966\" /> Crime increases, insufficient parking facilities, bad weather, and the post-World War II automotive boom were also cited as contributing factors in the visitor decrease. During the summer of 1964, concessionaires saw their lowest profits in a quarter-century. Ride operators reported that they had 30% to 90% fewer visitors in 1964 compared to the previous year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coney Island Slump Grows Worse; Decline in Business Since the War Years Has Been Steady|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 2, 1964|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/07/02/archives/coney-island-slump-grows-worse-decline-in-business-since-the-war.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1964, Coney Island's last remaining large amusement park, [[Steeplechase Park]], was closed and demolished.<ref name=\"NYT2005\">{{cite web | last=Chan | first=Sewell | title=Leaps of Imagination for the Parachute Jump | website=The New York Times | date=July 21, 2005 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/21/arts/design/leaps-of-imagination-for-the-parachute-jump.html | access-date=July 6, 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|172}} The surrounding blocks were filled with amusement rides and concessions that were closed or about to close.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|172}} The rides at Steeplechase Park were auctioned off, and the property was sold to developer [[Fred Trump]], who in 1965 announced that he wanted to build luxury apartments on the old Steeplechase property.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steeplechase Park Planned as the Site Of Housing Project|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 1, 1965|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/07/01/archives/steeplechase-park-planned-as-the-site-of-housing-project.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> At the time, residential developments on Coney Island in general were being built at a rapid rate. The peninsula, which had 34,000 residents in 1961, was expected to have more than double that number by the end of 1964. Many of the new residents moved into middle-income [[co-operative housing]] developments such as [[Trump Village]], [[Warbasse Houses]], and [[Luna Park Apartments]]; these replaced what ''The New York Times'' described as \"a rundown sprawl of rickety houses\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Kaufman|first=Michael T.|title=Housing and Amusements Give Coney Island a Dual Place in the Sun|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=March 19, 1964|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/03/19/housing-and-amusements-give-coney-island-a-dual-place-in-the-sun.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> Developers were spending millions of dollars on new housing developments, and by 1966, the peninsula housed almost 100,000 people.<ref name=\"Phillips 1966\">{{cite web|last=Phillips|first=McCandlish|title=Return of Coney Island; Amusement Area, Badly Hurt Last Year, Is Attempting to Win Back Customers|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=April 13, 1966|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/04/13/archives/return-of-coney-island-amusement-area-badly-hurt-last-year-is.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nTrump destroyed Steeplechase Park's Pavilion of Fun during a highly publicized ceremony in September 1966.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|172}}<ref>{{cite web|title=6 Bikinied Beauties Attend Demolishing Of Coney Landmark|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=September 22, 1966|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/09/22/archives/6-bikinied-beauties-attend-demolishing-of-coney-landmark.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> In its stead, Trump proposed building a {{convert|160|ft|m|adj=mid|-high}} enclosed dome with recreational facilities and a convention center, a plan which was supported by Brooklyn borough president [[Abe Stark]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A 160-Foot-High Pleasure Dome Is Proposed for Coney Island; A DOME PROPOSED FOR CONEY ISLAND|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 24, 1966|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/07/24/archives/a-160foothigh-pleasure-dome-is-proposed-for-coney-island-a-dome.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> That summer, developers tried to revitalize the Coney Island boardwalk as an amusement area.<ref name=\"Phillips 1966\" /> In October 1966, the city announced its plans to acquire the {{convert|125|acre|ha}} of the former Steeplechase Park,<ref>{{cite web|last=Fowle|first=Farnsworth|title=City Wants Site of Steeplechase For Seafront Coney Island Park; Planning Board Sets Oct. 19 Hearing to Bar Area for High-Rise Homes|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=October 5, 1966|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/10/05/archives/city-wants-site-of-steeplechase-for-seafront-coney-island-park.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> a move that many residents supported but that Trump considered to be \"wasteful\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Roberts|first=Steven V.|title=A PARK IS BACKED FOR CONEY ISLAND; Developer Who Bought Site Calls Plan Wasteful|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=October 20, 1966|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/10/20/archives/a-park-is-backed-for-coney-island-developer-who-bought-site-calls.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> In January 1968, New York City parks commissioner [[August Heckscher II]] proposed that the New York state government build an \"open-space\" state park on the Steeplechase site,<ref>{{cite web|last=Clark|first=Alfred E.|title=State Is Urged to Build a Park At Coney Island's Steeplechase|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=January 6, 1968|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1968/01/06/archives/state-is-urged-to-build-a-park-at-coney-islands-steeplechase.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> and that May, the New York City Board of Estimate voted in favor of funding to buy the land from Trump.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|title=PARK USAGE VOTED FOR STEEPLECHASE; City to Seek $2-Million Aid to Buy Coney Island Tract|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 23, 1968|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1968/05/23/archives/park-usage-voted-for-steeplechase-city-to-seek-2million-aid-to-buy.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":19\">{{cite news|url=|title=Coney Island stages a comeback|last=Glave|first=Judie|date=September 2, 1990|work=The Journal-News|access-date=|location=White Plains, NY|pages=[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34116222/ 68], [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34116227/ 69], [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34116234/ 70]|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> Condemnation of the site started in 1969.<ref name=\"Fowler 1979\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/06/03/archives/15year-dispute-over-lease-for-coney-island-steeplechase-continues.html|title=15\u2010Year Dispute Over Lease for Coney Island Steeplechase Continues|last=Fowler|first=Glenn|date=June 3, 1979|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref> The city ultimately purchased the proposed park's site for $4 million, with a stipulation blocking Trump from developing the site as apartments.<ref name=\"Carmody 1985\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28804609/|title=A plan to bring back Coney Island|last=Mirabella|first=Alan|date=June 2, 1985|work=New York Daily News|access-date=February 24, 2019|page=311|via=Newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref>\n\nTrump filed a series of court cases related to the proposed residential rezoning, and ultimately won a $1.3 million judgment.<ref name=\"Fowler 1979\" /> The Steeplechase Park site laid empty for several years. Trump started [[lease|subleasing]] the property to [[Norman Kaufman]], who ran a small collection of fairground amusements called \"Steeplechase Park\" on part of the site.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|172}}<ref name=\"Fowler 1979\" /> The city also leased the boardwalk and parking lot sites at extremely low rates, which resulted in a $1 million loss of revenue over the following seven years. Since the city wanted to build the state park on the site of Kaufman's Steeplechase Park, it attempted to evict him by refusing to grant a lease extension.<ref name=\"Chambers 1977\" />\n\n==== Late-1970s attempts at restoration ====\n[[File:ABANDONED \"GIANT SLIDE\" AT CONEY ISLAND MARKS DECLINE OF AREA'S RECREATIONAL USE - NARA - 547902.jpg|thumb|right|A 1973 photo of an abandoned \"Giant Slide\" that had been set up for a few years on the old Steeplechase site]]\n\nThe 1970s brought along further renewal plans, such as proposals to construct public housing. However, it was beset by social issues such as high crime and a drug epidemic.<ref name=\":19\" /> By 1975, the city was considering demolishing the [[Coney Island Cyclone]] in favor of an extension of the adjacent New York Aquarium.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|153}} The proposed demolition was controversial,<ref>{{cite web|title=Aquarium Urges Razing Of Coney Island Cyclone|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 27, 1975|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/05/27/archives/aquarium-urges-razing-of-coney-island-cyclone.html|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref> and after a refurbishment by [[Astroland]], the Cyclone reopened for the summer 1975 season.<ref>{{cite book|last=Futrell|first=J.|title=Amusement Parks of New York|publisher=Stackpole Books|series=Amusement Parks Series|year=2006|isbn=978-0-8117-3262-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MKOkQoVeGWAC&pg=PA66|access-date=September 15, 2018|page=66}}</ref> The abandoned Parachute Jump was left in situ, and the New York City Board of Estimate planned to tear down the structure.<ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|174}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Parachute Jump at Coney Island Loses Chance of Landmark Status|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=October 21, 1977|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/10/21/archives/parachute-jump-at-coney-island-loses-chance-of-landmark-status.html|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref> In the meanwhile, Coney Island was still affected by a perception of crime and deterioration of old rides, but by the mid-1970s, middle-class families started returning to Coney Island following the implementation of a unified admission ticket to Coney Island's amusement areas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34018580/|title=Coney Island: battered but unbowed, it still amuses|date=April 9, 1976|work=New York Daily News|access-date=July 18, 2019|page=53|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref>\n\nThe city continued to pursue litigation over the site occupied by Norman Kaufman, but for over a decade, was unsuccessful.<ref name=\"Fowler 1979\" /> It had no plan for the proposed state park, and in 1975 the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development]] nearly withdrew a proposed grant of $2 million to fund the proposed park.<ref name=\"Chambers 1977\">{{cite web|last=Chambers|first=Marcia|title=New York, After 10 Years, Finds Plan to Create a Coney Island Park Is Unsuccessful|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=April 3, 1977|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/04/03/archives/new-york-after-10-years-finds-plan-to-create-a-coney-island-park-is.html|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref> The city ultimately accepted the grant, though different city agencies still disagreed over whether to return the funds.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chambers|first=Marcia|title=City, in a Shift, Says Coney I. Park Should Become Amusement Area|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=June 16, 1977|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/06/16/archives/city-in-a-shift-says-coney-i-park-should-become-amusement-area.html|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref> Kaufman continued to operate the site until the end of summer 1980. The following June, the city paid Kaufman a million dollars for the rides, effectively evicting him, even though the amusements were estimated to be worth much less.<ref name=\"NYTimes-TalkofConeyIsland-1981\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 1979, the state announced that it would be conducting a report on the feasibility of legalizing gambling in New York State, Mayor [[Ed Koch]] proposed that the state open casinos in New York City to revitalize the area's economy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lynn|first=Frank|title=Koch Urges City Be Considered As a Site for Gambling Casinos|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=April 6, 1979|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/04/06/archives/koch-urges-city-be-considered-as-a-site-for-gambling-casinos-panel.html|access-date=September 16, 2018}}</ref> Residents and politicians supported the idea of building casinos at Coney Island, which they felt would alleviate its poverty, crime, and property vacancy rates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28712821/|title=Casinos seen as a Coney lifesaver|last=Fitzgerald|first=Owen|date=June 21, 1979|work=New York Daily News|access-date=February 21, 2019|page=652|via=Newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> However, there was substantial controversy over the plans to place a gambling site in Coney Island.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/08/14/archives/opinions-mixed-on-casino-plan-in-coney-island-prospect-of-gambling.html|title=Opinions Mixed On Casino Plan In Coney Island|last=Basler|first=Barbara|date=August 14, 1979|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref> The state's interest in legalizing gambling had subsided by 1981, and the New York state legislature failed to take action on such proposal.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28713218/|title=Effort renewed for rides park|last=Fitzgerald|first=Owen|date=November 17, 1982|work=New York Daily News|access-date=February 21, 2019|page=110|via=Newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes-TalkofConeyIsland-1981\">{{cite web|last=Campbell|first=Colin|title=BELEAGUERED CONEY ISLANDERS RALLY WITH SENSE OF AFFECTION; The Talk of Coney Island|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=August 29, 1981|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/08/29/nyregion/beleaguered-coney-islanders-rally-with-sense-affection-talk-coney-island.html|access-date=September 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn an effort to reduce crime, the city also began demolishing abandoned bungalows on Coney Island.<ref name=\":19\" /> By 1982, the area was filled with vacant lots, though several residential developments were being planned for Coney Island.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/02/25/nyregion/about-new-york-a-ray-of-hope-gleams-in-coney-island.html|title=About New York; a Ray of Hope Gleams in Coney Island|last=Quindlen|first=Anna|date=February 25, 1982|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 22, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Having finally acquired Kaufman's rides, the New York City government began advertising for developers to redevelop the former amusement park area that November.<ref name=\":2\" /> The Mermaid-Neptune Development Corporation constructed three residential developments at the neighborhood's western edge, with a combined total of 430 units. These developments were completed through the mid-1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/06/10/realestate/postings-housing-reprieve.html|title=POSTINGS; HOUSING REPRIEVE|date=June 10, 1984|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=February 22, 2019}}</ref> Even so, the area still suffered from drug-related killings and other crimes, especially west of West 20th Street. Former amusement structures such as the Parachute Jump lay unused, and prostitutes roamed around the neighborhood at night.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/08/20/nyregion/the-talk-of-coney-island-at-coney-i-symbols-of-heyday-fading-away.html|title=The Talk of Coney Island; at Coney I., Symbols of Heyday Fading Away|last=Chira|first=Susan|date=August 20, 1983|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 22, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> Through the 1980s, prostitution and drug use in Coney Island increased, as did the area's murder and felony crime rate.<ref>{{cite web|last=Freedman|first=Samuel G.|title=CONEY I.: SYMBOL OF FUN IS NOW ONE OF DESPAIR|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 29, 1986|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/05/29/nyregion/coney-i-symbol-of-fun-is-now-one-of-despair.html|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US}}</ref> By the late 1980s, deadly shootings were common, particularly in the low-income housing developments inside Coney Island.<ref>{{cite web|last=Williams|first=Winston|title=THE TALK OF CONEY ISLAND; Faded Funland: Fears and Hopes|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 18, 1988|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/07/18/nyregion/the-talk-of-coney-island-faded-funland-fears-and-hopes.html|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref> Commercial activity also decreased, and by 1990, storefronts on Mermaid Avenue had decreased by 90%, from over 400 stores before the urban renewal to 39 stores afterward.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\n=== Revival ===\n==== Bullard deal, Sportsplex, and KeySpan Park ====\n[[File:CI BUG apts fr W12 jeh.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.25|Co-ops on Coney Island]]\nIn the mid-1980s, restaurant mogul [[Horace Bullard]] proposed rebuilding Steeplechase Park.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|150}}<ref name=\":3\" /> On the site bounded by West 15th and 19th Streets between Surf Avenue and the boardwalk, Bullard wanted to build a $55 million amusement park based on the originals. The city agreed, and the project was approved in 1985.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|150}}<ref name=\"Carmody 1985\">{{cite web|last=Carmody|first=Deirdre|title=REBORN STEEPLECHASE PARK PLANNED AT CONEY I.|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=August 5, 1985|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/08/05/nyregion/reborn-steeplechase-park-planned-at-coney-i.html|access-date=September 16, 2018}}</ref> Bullard planned to open the park by mid-1986 to coincide with the [[Statue of Liberty]]'s centennial.<ref name=\"Carmody 1985\" /> However, the project was delayed while the New York City Planning Commission compiled an environmental impact report.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|last=Rangel|first=Jesus|title=CONEY I. OPENING SEASON WITH HOPE|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=March 29, 1986|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/03/29/nyregion/coney-i-opening-season-with-hope.html|access-date=September 16, 2018}}</ref> By early 1987, the cost of the amusement park nearly doubled, to $100 million.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/06/05/nyregion/broad-redevelopment-is-urged-for-coney-island.html|title=Broad Redevelopment Is Urged for Coney Island|last=Rangel|first=Jesus|date=June 5, 1987|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nConcurrently, in December 1986, the New York State Urban Development Corporation formally proposed a 17,000-seat minor-league baseball stadium north of the boardwalk between West 19th and West 22nd Streets as well as 15,000-seat indoor arena north of the Abe Stark Rink. Negotiations were ongoing with the [[New York Mets|Mets]] and [[New York Yankees|Yankees]] to ensure their support for the minor-league stadium.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rangel|first=Jesus|title=STATE PROPOSES BASEBALL STADIUM FOR CONEY I.|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=December 5, 1986|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/12/05/nyregion/state-proposes-baseball-stadium-for-coney-i.html|access-date=September 16, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{cite news|url=|title=The Business of Bringing Baseball Back to Brooklyn|last=Arena|first=Salvatore|date=April 26, 1987|work=New York Daily News|access-date=|pages=[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28807554/ 1], [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28807722/ 8\u20139]|via=Newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> State senator [[Thomas Bartosiewics]] attempted to block Bullard's plan, as he was part of a foundation that had promised another developer, Sportsplex, the right to build an amateur sports arena on the site.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":11\" /> Construction was held up for another four years, and by 1989, Bullard and the city were ready to sign a contract that would allow the developer to construct a 60-ride amusement park on a {{Convert|25|acre|ha|abbr=|adj=on}} waterfront strip, which would be completed by 2002.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/08/09/business/real-estate-coney-island-development-deal-gaining.html|title=Real Estate; Coney Island Development Deal Gaining|last=Kennedy|first=Shawn G.|date=August 9, 1989|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Other proposals for the area included a $7.9 million restoration of the boardwalk, as well as a new high-school and college sports stadium.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nSome of Coney Island's iconic rides were designated as official city landmarks during the late 1980s.<ref name=\"BrooklynEagle-CILandmarks-2016\" /> In 1988, the Cyclone roller coaster was made a New York City designated landmark.<ref name=\"NYTimes-Cyclone-1988\">{{cite web|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|title=Coney I. Thriller Becomes Landmark|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 13, 1988|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/07/13/nyregion/coney-i-thriller-becomes-landmark.html|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref> This was followed by the Parachute Jump and the Wonder Wheel in 1989.<ref name=\"NYTimes-PJ-1989\">{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2010/02/15/coney-island-parachute-jump-no-climbing-allowed/|title=Coney Island Parachute Jump \u2013 No climbing allowed!|last=Maniscalco|first=Joe|date=February 15, 2010|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BrooklynEagle-CILandmarks-2016\">{{Cite web|url=https://brooklyneagle.com/articles/2016/05/11/coney-island-landmarks-present-and-we-hope-future/|title=Coney Island landmarks, present and (we hope) future|date=May 11, 2016|website=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|language=en-US|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref> The neighborhood's high crime rate had reversed slightly by the 1990s. However, Coney Island's relative isolation from the rest of New York City, along with its ethnic diversity, deprived the area of significant political power, and to a greater extent money.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wolff|first=Craig|title=Coney Island on the Edge; A Region's Venerable Magic Is Buffeted by Modern Times|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 25, 1994|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/05/25/nyregion/coney-island-on-the-edge-a-region-s-venerable-magic-is-buffeted-by-modern-times.html|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Rudy Giuliani]] took office as New York City mayor of New York in 1994, he negated the Bullard deal by approving the construction of a minor-league baseball stadium on the site allotted for Steeplechase Park.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|150}} Giuliani had wanted to build Sportsplex in order to improve sports facilities in the area, and to create a professional baseball team in Brooklyn.<ref>{{cite web|last=Farrell|first=Bill|title=Baseball Pitch Back in Sportsplex Mix Rally for Coney Venue|website=NY Daily News|date=January 21, 1998|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/boroughs/baseball-pitch-back-sportsplex-mix-rally-coney-venue-article-1.788295|access-date=November 13, 2015}}</ref> By the late 1990s, some $67 million had been secured for the development of Sportsplex.<ref name=\":6\" /> In 1997, developer [[Bruce Ratner]] proposed constructing a $100 million entertainment complex between West 9th and West 15th Streets, with a \"virtual-reality amusement park\" as well as a [[Multiplex (movie theater)|movie theater multiplex]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/21/nyregion/with-times-square-reborn-attention-turns-to-coney-island.html|title=With Times Square Reborn, Attention Turns to Coney Island|last=Martin|first=Douglas|date=July 21, 1997|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Concurrently, a four-phase, 873-unit housing development in Coney Island was completed in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rozhon|first=Tracie|title=Coney Island Housing Project Complete|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=November 22, 1996|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/11/22/business/coney-island-housing-project-complete.html|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Giuliani canceled Sportsplex and the entertainment complex, and instead unveiled another plan where only the parking lot would be built. The Sports Foundation had prepared another proposal that would allow a scaled-down Sportsplex to be built next to the minor-league baseball stadium.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite news|last=Martin|first=Douglas|title=Back to the Drawing Board in Coney Island|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=November 23, 1998|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/23/nyregion/back-to-the-drawing-board-in-coney-island.html|access-date=November 13, 2015}}</ref> The minor league team was called the Brooklyn Cyclones, though naming rights to the stadium were sold to [[Keyspan Energy]]. Bullard, now no longer rebuilding Steeplechase Park, had wanted to restore the Thunderbolt as part of a scaled-down amusement park, but it was demolished instead.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|150}} In 2000, the city approved the $31 million project to construct [[MCU Park|Keyspan Park]] using the funds from the canceled Sportsplex,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/12/nyregion/deal-gives-coney-island-a-ballpark-and-a-team-that-some-didn-t-want.html|title=Deal Gives Coney Island a Ballpark, and a Team That Some Didn't Want|last=Barnes|first=Julian E.|date=April 12, 2000|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and the minor-league baseball stadium opened the following year.<ref name=\":15\">{{cite web|last=Vecsey|first=George|title=Sports of The Times; Summer Rite Returns To Borough of Churches|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=June 26, 2001|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/06/26/sports/sports-of-the-times-summer-rite-returns-to-borough-of-churches.html|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref> Other major projects at the time included the reconstruction of Coney Island's sewers and the refurbishment of the Stillwell Avenue subway station,<ref name=\":6\" /> the latter of which was completed in 2005.<ref name=\"Chan\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/28/nyregion/and-now-for-the-good-news-from-the-subway-system.html|title=And Now for the Good News From the Subway System|last=Chan|first=Sewell|date=May 28, 2005|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Thor Equities ownership and rezoning proposals ====\n[[File:Astroland Coney Island by David Shankbone.JPG|thumb|left|The Wonder Wheel and Astroland Park from a Coney Island beach]]\n\nIn 2003, Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] took an interest in revitalizing Coney Island as a possible site for the [[New York City bid for the 2012 Summer Olympics|New York City bid]] of the [[2012 Summer Olympics bids|2012 Summer Olympics]]. A plan was developed by the [[Astella Development Corporation]]. When the city lost the bid for the Olympics, revitalization plans were passed on to the Coney Island Development Corporation (CIDC), which came up with a plan to restore the resort.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nycedc.com/press-release/mayor-bloomberg-announces-strategic-plan-future-coney-island|title=Mayor Bloomberg Announces Strategic Plan For Future of Coney Island|last=|first=|date=September 14, 2005|work=NYCEDC|access-date=July 21, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Shortly before the CIDC's plans were to be publicly released, a development company named [[Thor Equities]] purchased all of Bullard's {{convert|168000|ft2|m2|adj=on}} western property for $13 million, later selling the property to [[Taconic Investment Partners]] for over $90 million.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|158}} Taconic now had {{convert|100|acre|ha}}, on which it planned to build 2,000 apartment units.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|158\u2013159}}<ref name=\"Fung 2009\">{{cite web|last=Fung|first=Amanda|title=Coney Island keeper|website=Crain's New York Business|date=June 28, 2009|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20090628/SMALLBIZ/306289868/coney-island-keeper|access-date=November 14, 2015}}</ref> Thor then went about using much of its $77 million profit to purchase property on Stillwell Avenue for well over market value, and offered to buy out every piece of property inside the traditional amusement area.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|158\u2013159}}\n\nIn September 2005, Thor's founder, [[Joe Sitt]], unveiled his new plans for a large [[Bellagio (resort)|Bellagio]]-style hotel resort with a [[timeshare]] development, surrounded by rides and amusements. The CIDC report suggested adding year-round commercial and amusement area, and recommended that property north of Surf Avenue and west of Abe Stark Rink could be rezoned for other uses, including residential.<ref name=\":0\" /> Sitt, a resident of the area, spent more than $100 million to buy land in Coney Island.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/04/nyregion/04coney.html|title=Down by the Boardwalk, a $1 Billion Revival Plan|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|date=July 4, 2006|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Astroland]] owner Carol Hill Albert, whose husband's family had owned the park since 1962, sold the site to Thor in November 2006. Two months later, Thor released renderings for a $1.5 billion amusement park, entertainment complex, and indoor water park called Coney Island Park.<ref>{{cite web | title=A $1.5 Billion Vision For Coney Island | website=The New York Sun | url=https://www.nysun.com/new-york/15-billion-vision-for-coney-island/43372/ | access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite web | title=Plans Coming Together For Coney Island Amusement Park Expansion | website=ny1.com | date=November 14, 2006 | url=http://www.ny1.com/ny1/content/index.jsp?stid=9&aid=64315 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071008063611/http://www.ny1.com/ny1/content/index.jsp?stid=9&aid=64315 | archive-date=October 8, 2007 | url-status=dead | access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the DCP started circulating a rezoning plan that would cover {{Convert|47|acre|ha|abbr=}} of Coney Island. The city would spend $120 million to redevelop {{Convert|15|acre|ha|abbr=}} into an amusement park surrounded by around 5,000 new housing units.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/home.html|title=New York City Department of City Planning&nbsp;\u2014 Amanda M. Burden, Director|publisher=Nyc.gov|date=|access-date=August 13, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/09/nyregion/09coney.html|title=City Offers Coney Island Plan That Conflicts With a Developer's|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|date=November 9, 2007|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Aquarium was also planning a renovation in conjunction with the rezoning.<ref name=\":7\" /> The city's and Sitt's proposals directly conflicted: Sitt wanted to build housing inside the amusement park, while the city's rezoning would create a special amusement district where residential development was forbidden.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/17/nyregion/17coney.html|title=City and Developer Spar Over Coney Island Visions|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|date=February 16, 2009|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In April 2008, because of objections from land owners, residents, and developers, the city revised its rezoning proposal. Only 9 acres would be used as an amusement park, while private owners and developers could build on the rest of the land as long as they followed the DCP's general master plan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/17/nyregion/17coney.html|title=City's Coney Island Design Revised to Break Deadlock|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|date=April 17, 2008|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> While the city negotiated with Thor, Sitt evicted several amusement operators on his land, including Astroland, in the expectation that he would soon be able to redevelop it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/11/nyregion/11coney.html|title=City and Developer at Odds Over Future of Coney Island|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|date=April 10, 2009|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 26, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>[[File:COneyIsland1506.jpg|thumb|right|Senior housing on Coney Island]]The DCP certified the rezoning plan in January 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/html/luproc/ulpro.shtml|title=Uniform Land Use Review Procedure (ULURP)&nbsp;\u2013 New York City Department of City Planning|publisher=Nyc.gov|access-date=August 13, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120719144905/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/html/luproc/ulpro.shtml|archivedate=July 19, 2012}}</ref> which allowed the city to create a {{Convert|9.4|acre|ha|abbr=|adj=on}} amusement district.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/12/nyregion/12coney.html|title=New York to Buy 7 Acres in Coney Island, Hoping for Revival|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|date=November 11, 2009|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> At the time, Thor Equities said it hoped to complete the project by 2011.<ref>{{cite news | last=Santos | first=Fernanda | title=Coney Island's Astroland Closes, Maybe for Good | work=The New York Times | date=September 10, 2007 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/10/nyregion/10coney.html | access-date=October 20, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In June 2009, the city's planning commission approved the construction of 4,500 units of housing, including 900 affordable units, and promised to preserve affordable housing already in the neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web | last=Edroso | first=Roy | title=New York \u2013 Runnin' Scared \u2013 Planning Commission Approves Unloved Coney Plan | website=blogs.villagevoice.com | date=July 3, 2009 | url=http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/archives/2009/06/planning_commis.php | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090703160349/http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/archives/2009/06/planning_commis.php | archive-date=July 3, 2009 | url-status=dead | access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" /> Subsequently, the city government paid Sitt $95.6 million for {{Convert|7|acre|ha|abbr=}} of land.<ref name=\":10\" /> The nonprofit civic group, [[Municipal Art Society]], wanted the city-operated park to be larger, though the city was reluctant to spend so much money.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n==== Progress on expansion ====\nThe Zipper and Spider on West 12th Street were closed permanently and dismantled in September 2007 after its owner lost his lease.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ride Over for Coney Classics|first=Rich|last=Calder|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/09052007/news/regionalnews/ride_over_for_coney_classics.htm|newspaper=New York Post|date=September 5, 2007|access-date=September 5, 2007}}</ref> The same year, plans to restore Coney Island's historic [[B&B Carousell]] were revealed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/13/nyregion/13carousel.html|title=Plans Afoot to Restore Coney Island Carousel for New Spin on the Boardwalk|last=McGeehan|first=Patrick|date=September 13, 2007|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> After Astroland closed in 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ireport.com/ir-topic-stories.jspa?topicId=22385|title=Coney Island amusement park closing: News & Videos about Coney Island amusement park closing|publisher=CNN|work=Ireport.com|access-date=March 17, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081230203827/http://www.ireport.com/ir-topic-stories.jspa?topicId=22385|archive-date=December 30, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> it was replaced by a new [[Dreamland (Coney Island, 2009)|Dreamland]] in 2009<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn/dreamland-amusement-park-place-astroland-coney-island-article-1.362110|title=Dreamland amusement park to take place of Astroland at Coney Island|last=Sederstrom|first=Jotham|date=April 8, 2009|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref> and by a new [[Luna Park (Coney Island, 2010)|Luna Park]] in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/33/23/all_coneypreview_2010_06_04_bk.html|title=It's Saturday \u2014 and a new day dawns at Coney Island|last=Donahue|first=Courtney|date=June 4, 2010|website=Brooklyn Paper|language=en|access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/gonna-new-coney-island-baby-19-rides-added-luna-park-article-1.198180|title=It's gonna be a new Coney Island, baby! 19 rides added to Luna Park|last=Durkin|first=Erin|date=February 20, 2010|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref> In April 2011, the first new roller coasters to be built at Coney Island in eighty years were opened as part of efforts to reverse the decline of the amusement area.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-rollercoasters-idUSTRE73K57P20110421|title=Coney Island gets first new roller coasters in 80 years|date=April 21, 2011|work=Reuters|access-date=July 22, 2019|language=en}}</ref> The B&B Carousell reopened in 2013 at Luna Park.<ref name=\"Foderaro 2013\" /> The [[Thunderbolt (2014 roller coaster)|Thunderbolt]] steel roller coaster, named after the original wooden coaster on the site, was opened in June 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn/coney-island-new-thunderbolt-roller-coaster-officially-opens-article-1.1830380|title=Coney Island's new Thunderbolt roller coaster officially opens|date=June 14, 2014|work=NY Daily News|access-date=June 29, 2014|author=Brown, Stephen R.}}</ref> Furthermore, a live performance venue, the [[Ford Amphitheater at Coney Island]], opened on the boardwalk in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pix11.com/2016/06/29/massive-entertainment-amphitheater-opens-on-iconic-coney-island-boardwalk/|title=Massive entertainment amphitheater opens on iconic Coney Island Boardwalk|date=June 29, 2016|website=WPIX 11 New York|language=en|access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, [[Hurricane Sandy]] caused major damage to the Coney Island amusement parks, the Aquarium, and businesses. However, the [[Nathan's Hot Dog Eating Contest]] was held the following summer, as usual.<ref>{{cite web | title=Nathan's Famous to Reopen in Spring 2013 after Hurricane Sandy | website=Brooklyn Paper | date=December 7, 2012 | url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/35/48/all_nathansrecovery_2012_12_07_bk.html | access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> Luna Park at Coney Island reopened as scheduled on March 24, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Despite Sandy's Wrath, Coney Island's Luna Park To Reopen On Schedule Sunday|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2013/03/22/despite-sandys-wrath-coney-islands-luna-park-to-reopen-on-schedule-sunday/|publisher=CBS News New York|access-date=March 22, 2013}}</ref> Rebuilding of the aquarium started in early 2013, and a major expansion of the aquarium opened in summer 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/06/inside-ocean-wonders-sharks-at-the-new-york-aquarium.html|title=What to Know About the New York Aquarium's New Shark Building|last=Schneider|first=Katy|date=June 28, 2018|website=Daily Intelligencer|access-date=June 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/28/arts/design/new-york-aquarium-sharks-sandy.html|title=Coney Island's Newest Wonder: Sharkitecture!|last=Hodgson|first=Sam|date=June 28, 2018|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=July 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Coney Island Brooklyn Jul 2019 03.jpg|thumb|Reconstruction of [[Shore Theater]] into hotel, seen in 2019]]\n\nIn August 2018, the NYCEDC and NYC Parks announced that Luna Park would be expanded between West 15th and West 16th Streets, next to the Thunderbolt.<ref>{{cite web|title=Log flume ride, zip lines coming to Coney Island|website=am New York|date=August 23, 2018|url=https://www.amny.com/news/coney-island-luna-park-expansion-1.20626460|access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Chung 2018\">{{cite web|last=Chung|first=Jen|title=Coney Island's Luna Park Is Getting Log Flume Ride, A Ropes Course, And More!|website=Gothamist|date=August 23, 2018|url=http://gothamist.com/2018/08/23/luna_park_expanding_coney_island.php|access-date=August 24, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823223421/http://gothamist.com/2018/08/23/luna_park_expanding_coney_island.php | archive-date=August 23, 2018 | url-status=dead}}</ref> There would be a public plaza and an [[amusement arcade]] within the newly expanded amusement area.<ref name=\"Chung 2018\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=City Unveils Plans For New Water Park, Arcade On Coney Island|website=CBS New York|date=August 23, 2018|url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2018/08/23/city-unveils-plans-for-new-water-park-arcade-on-coney-island/|access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref> The same month, it was also announced that a 50-room [[boutique hotel]] was being planned for Coney Island within the former [[Shore Theater]] on Surf and Stillwell Avenues.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ramirez|first=Jeanine|title=Coney Island could see first new hotel in over 50 years|website=Spectrum News NY1 &#124; New York City|date=August 21, 2018|url=http://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2018/08/21/coney-island-could-see-first-new-hotel-in-over-50-years|access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Franklin|first=Sydney|title=Shore Theater on Coney Island will be converted into a boutique hotel|website=Archpaper.com|date=August 21, 2018|url=https://archpaper.com/2018/08/shore-theater-coney-island-hotel/|access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref> The city also expressed its intent to demolish the Abe Stark Rink and redevelop the site, as per the 2009 rezoning, though residents wanted NYC Parks to retain control over the site rather than sell it off to a private developer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Locals demand beloved Coney ice rink remain under Parks Department control|website=Brooklyn Daily|date=August 31, 2018|url=https://www.brooklyndaily.com/stories/2018/35/bn-abe-stark-demolition-2018-08-31-bk.html|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe addition of new amusements coincided with the development of over 2,000 new residential units on empty lots, through the early 2020s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/12/28/coney-island-sees-a-budding-real-estate-boom-after-years-of-decline.html|title=Coney Island, home to hot dogs and the Cyclone roller coaster, sees a budding real estate boom|last=Bukszpan|first=Daniel|date=December 30, 2018|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2018/11/04/wave-of-residential-construction-in-coney-island-to-attract-new-residents-|title=A Wave of New Housing is Being Built in Coney Island|website=www.ny1.com|language=en|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref> These included a 1,000-unit mega-development and a 40-story, 522-unit residential tower that would be the tallest in southern Brooklyn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brooklyneagle.com/articles/2018/08/23/sea-breeze-tower-to-rise-above-coney-island/|title=Sea Breeze Tower to rise above Coney Island|date=August 23, 2018|website=Brooklyn Eagle|language=en-US|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ny.curbed.com/2018/1/4/16850666/coney-island-surf-avenue-megaproject|title=Massive Coney Island development to have 1,000 apartments, retail|last=Warerkar|first=Tanay|date=January 4, 2018|website=Curbed NY|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Amusement parks and attractions ==\n{{anchor|Amusement parks|Theme parks|Amusement}}\nConey Island has two amusement parks, [[Luna Park (Coney Island, 2010)|Luna Park]] and [[Deno's Wonder Wheel Amusement Park]], as well as several rides that are not incorporated into either amusement park. These are owned and managed by several different companies and operate independently of each other. Coney Island also has several other visitor attractions such as [[skee ball|skeeball]] and ball tossing, as well as a [[sideshow]], that contains shooting, throwing, and tossing skills. The area hosts renowned events as well. Coney Island's amusement area is one of a few in the United States that is not mostly owned by any one entity.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|153}}\n\n=== Rides ===\n==== Current rides ====\n{{For|a more detailed list of rides operating in Coney Island amusement parks|Luna Park (Coney Island, 2010)#Attractions|Deno's Wonder Wheel Amusement Park#Attractions}}\nConey Island contains three rides with landmark status. One is a [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission|New York City designated landmark]], another is [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Brooklyn|listed]] in the [[National Register of Historic Places]] (NRHP), and a third is both a city landmark and a NRHP-listed landmark.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\"cyclone-nycl\" /><ref>{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Wonder Wheel]], built in 1918 and opened in 1920, is a steel [[Ferris wheel]] with both stationary cars and rocking cars that slide along a track.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amny.com/lifestyle/wonder-wheel-photos-1.10691209|title=The Wonder Wheel at Coney celebrates its 95th summer season|last=Salazar|first=Cristian|date=July 30, 2015|website=am New York|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> It holds 144 riders, stands {{convert|150|ft|m|abbr=on}} tall, weighs over {{convert|200|ST|LT t|sp=us}}, and is located at Deno's Wonder Wheel Amusement Park.<ref name=\"Denson 2011\" />{{rp|47}} The Wonder Wheel was made a city landmark in 1989.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1708.pdf|title=The Wonder Wheel|date=May 23, 1989|publisher=New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>{{Rp|1}}\n\nThe [[B&B Carousell]] {{sic}} (as spelled by the frame's builder, [[William F. Mangels]]) is Coney Island's last traditional [[carousel]], near the old entrance to [[Luna Park (Coney Island, 1903)|Luna Park]]. The carousel was built circa 1906\u20131909 with a traditional roll-operated [[fairground organ]]. It was relocated multiple times, most recently to Luna Park's Steeplechase Plaza in 2013,<ref name=\"Foderaro 2013\">{{cite web|last=Foderaro|first=Lisa W.|title=B&B Carousell Horses Return Home to Coney Island|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 24, 2013|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/26/nyregion/bb-carousell-horses-return-home-to-coney-island.html|access-date=July 28, 2018}}</ref> and listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coney Island's B&B Carousell placed on National Register of Historic Places|website=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|date=July 28, 2018|url=http://www.brooklyneagle.com/articles/2016/3/8/coney-island%E2%80%99s-bb-carousell-placed-national-register-historic-places|access-date=July 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=B&B Carousell designated national historic place, up for federal preservation money \u2022 Brooklyn Daily|website=Brooklyn Daily|date=March 11, 2016|url=https://www.brooklyndaily.com/stories/2016/11/bn-b-and-b-carousell-on-historic-register-2016-03-11-bk.html|access-date=July 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Coney Island Cyclone]], built in 1927, is one of the United States's oldest [[wooden roller coaster]]s still in operation. The Cyclone includes an {{convert|85|ft|m|abbr=on}}, 58-degree drop. It is owned by the City of New York, and is operated by [[Luna Park (Coney Island, 2010)|Luna Park]] under a franchise agreement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/04/nyregion/04critic.html|work=The New York Times|title=Thrilling Reminder of Old Coney Island|first=Ariel|last=Kaminer|date=April 2, 2010}}</ref> The Cyclone was made a city landmark in 1988<ref name=\"cyclone-nycl\">{{Cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1636.pdf|title=The Cyclone|date=July 12, 1988|publisher=New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>{{Rp|1}}<ref name=\"NYTimes-Cyclone-1988\" /> and was listed on the NRHP in 1991.<ref>{{NRISref|2013a|dateform=mdy|access-date=February 26, 2019|refnum=91000907|name=Cyclone Roller Coaster}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n| align = center\n| direction = horizontal\n| total_width = 800\n| image1 = Coney-island-cyclone-usgs-photo.jpg\n| caption1 =  [[Coney Island Cyclone]]\n| image2 = WonderWheelNewYork.jpg\n| caption2 = [[Wonder Wheel]]\n| image3 = Thunderbolt 2014-08-11 view from west.JPG\n| caption3 = [[Thunderbolt (2014 roller coaster)|Thunderbolt]]\n| image4 = Coney Carousel 006.JPG\n| caption4 = [[B&B Carousell]]\n}}\n\nThere are also multiple other rides in Coney Island. In March 2014, construction started on the new [[Thunderbolt (2014 roller coaster)|Thunderbolt]], a [[steel roller coaster]] that was manufactured by [[Zamperla]] at a cost of $10 million. The ride features {{Convert|2000|ft|m}} of track, a height of {{Convert|125|ft|m}}, and a top speed of {{Convert|65|mph}}, as well as four [[Roller coaster inversions|inversions]].<ref name=\"RCDB2\">{{cite RCDB|coaster_name=Thunderbolt|location=Luna Park|rcdb_number=8788|access-date=November 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://brooklyn.news12.com/news/luna-park-breaks-ground-on-new-roller-coaster-the-thunderbolt-on-coney-island-1.7344601|title=Luna Park breaks ground on new roller coaster, the Thunderbolt, on Coney Island \u2013 News 12 Brooklyn|date=March 10, 2014|publisher=Brooklyn.news12.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140311180202/http://brooklyn.news12.com/news/luna-park-breaks-ground-on-new-roller-coaster-the-thunderbolt-on-coney-island-1.7344601|archivedate=March 11, 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=June 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=New Roller Coaster Promises Coney Island a Return of Thrills | website=The New York Times | date=March 11, 2014 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/11/nyregion/new-roller-coaster-promises-coney-island-a-return-of-thrills.html | access-date=October 22, 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2014/03/10/coney-islands-luna-park-to-get-new-roller-coaster/|title=Coney Island's Luna Park To Get New Roller Coaster \u00ab CBS New York|date=March 10, 2014|publisher=Newyork.cbslocal.com|access-date=June 4, 2014}}</ref> The Thunderbolt opened in June 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn/coney-island-new-thunderbolt-roller-coaster-officially-opens-article-1.1830380|title=Coney Island's new Thunderbolt roller coaster officially opens|work=NY Daily News|date=June 14, 2014|access-date=June 29, 2014|author=Brown, Stephen R.}}</ref>\n\nThere are also multiple [[bumper car]] rides in Coney Island, all operated separately. {{As of|2019||df=|since=}}, these include an attraction in Deno's Wonder Wheel Park,<ref name=\"denos-map\">{{cite web|url=https://www.denoswonderwheel.com/s/0302-Denos-WW-Park-map-2018compressed.pdf|title=Park Map|website=DENO'S WONDER WHEEL|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> as well as Eldorado Auto Skooter on Surf Avenue. Historically, the earliest bumper car rides were located in Coney Island.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/experience/america/theme-parks/2019/02/21/bumper-cars-history/2843129002/|title=Bumper cars: A crash course on the classic amusement park ride|date=February 21, 2019|website=USA TODAY|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> Furthermore, two traditional [[dark ride]] [[Haunted attraction (simulated)|haunted houses]] operate at Coney Island: [[Spook-a-Rama]] at Deno's,<ref name=\"denos-map\" /> and [[Ghost Hole]] on West 12th Street adjacent to Deno's.<ref name=\"fun-guide\">{{cite web|url=http://coneyislandfunguide.com/fun-map-of-coney-island/|title=Fun Map of Coney Island|date=December 5, 2013|website=Coney Island Fun Guide|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Former rides ====\n[[File:ThunderboltConeyIsland1995.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The original [[Thunderbolt (1925 roller coaster)|Thunderbolt]] in 1995]]\n\nConey Island has had three major amusement parks in its past\u2014[[Steeplechase Park]] (1897\u20131964), [[Luna Park (Coney Island, 1903)|Luna Park]] (1903\u20131944), and [[Dreamland (Coney Island, 1904)|Dreamland]] (1904\u20131911)\u2014as well as several standalone attractions.<ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|74}}<ref>{{cite web | title=Steeplechase, Luna Park, and Dreamland \u2013 BKM TECH | website=Brooklyn Museum | date=January 16, 2008 | url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/community/blogosphere/2008/01/16/steeplechase-luna-park-and-dreamland/ | access-date=July 17, 2019}}</ref> In addition, [[Astroland]] operated at the site of the current Luna Park from 1962 to 2008,<ref>{{cite web | title=Astroland is truly dead | website=Brooklyn Paper | date=September 5, 2008 | url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/31/36/31_36_mm_astroland.html | access-date=October 19, 2019}}</ref> while a second [[Dreamland (Coney Island, 2009)|Dreamland]] only operated for the 2009 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn/nightmare-dreamland-rent-woes-shut-coney-island-park-owner-vows-court-battle-article-1.396209|title=Nightmare at Dreamland: Rent woes shut Coney Island park as owner vows court battle|last=Durkin|first=Erin|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/32/35/32_35_mm_dreamland_is_dead.html|title=IT'S OVER! Coney's Dreamland will be closed for the rest of the summer|last=McLaughlin|first=Mike|website=Brooklyn Paper|language=en|access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the rides in Coney Island's former amusement parks, there were also several dozen roller coasters that are now defunct.<ref>{{cite web|title=Roller Coasters|website=Coney Island|date=June 2, 2004|url=https://www.westland.net/coneyisland/articles/coasterlist.htm|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> The Comet, next to the Cyclone's current site, was built in 1921 and destroyed in 1945.<ref name=\"Denson 2011\" />{{rp|46}} Another coaster, the Oriental Scenic Railway, was created by [[LaMarcus Adna Thompson]] in 1887,<ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|98\u201399}}<ref name=\"Denson 2011\" />{{rp|41}} and was demolished in 1955 to be replaced with a \"hot rod\" amusement ride.<ref name=\"Billboard-19550129\" /> The [[steeplechase roller coaster]], created by Steeplechase Park operator George C. Tilyou in 1897, consisted of people riding wooden horses around the park on a steel track.<ref name=\"Ierardi\" /> The original wooden [[Thunderbolt (1925 roller coaster)|Thunderbolt]] coaster, located between West 15th and West 16th Streets, was constructed in 1925, closed in 1983, and torn down in 2000 during the construction of nearby Keyspan Park.<ref>{{cite RCDB|coaster_name=Thunderbolt|location=Coney Island \u2013 George Moran|rcdb_number=423|access-date=November 16, 2013}}</ref><ref name=endofln>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=iopOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vR4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5735%2C906219 |work=Spartanburg Herald-Journal |location=South Carolina |agency=Associated Press |title=End of the line |date=November 19, 2000 |page=10A}}</ref> Nearby was [[Tornado (Coney Island)|Tornado]], a wooden coaster constructed in&nbsp;1926,<ref name=\"Parascandola 2014\" />{{rp|24}}<ref>{{cite RCDB|coaster_name=Tornado|location=Coney Island \u2013 Independent Vendor 5|rcdb_number=5690|access-date=November 16, 2013}}</ref> and destroyed by arson in&nbsp;1977.<ref>{{cite web|title=3 Women Killed in Brooklyn Fires|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=December 11, 1977|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/12/11/archives/3-women-killed-in-brooklyn-fires.html|access-date=January 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nConey Island also contains one defunct ride that is still standing, the [[Parachute Jump]]. Originally built as the [[Life Savers]] Parachute Jump at the [[1939 New York World's Fair]], this was the first ride of its kind. Patrons were hoisted {{convert|262|ft|m|abbr=on}} in the air before being allowed to drop using guy-wired parachutes. The Parachute Jump was closed in the 1960s, but was officially preserved,<ref name=\"NYT2005\" /> having been listed on the NRHP in 1980<ref>{{NRISref|2013a|dateform=mdy|access-date=February 26, 2019|refnum=80002645|name=Parachute Jump}}</ref> and made a city landmark in 1989.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1638.pdf|title=The Parachute Jump|date=May 23, 1989|publisher=New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>{{rp|1}}<ref name=\"NYTimes-PJ-1989\" />\n\n=== Beaches ===\n[[File:Coney Island beach (June 2016).jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1|The beach at Coney Island in June 2016, with the [[Marine Parkway\u2013Gil Hodges Memorial Bridge]] visible on the horizon]]\nThere is a broad public sand beach that starts at Sea Gate at West 37th Street, through the central Coney Island area and [[Brighton Beach]], to the beginning of the community of [[Manhattan Beach, Brooklyn|Manhattan Beach]], a distance of approximately {{convert|2.7|mi|km|abbr=on}}. The beach is continuous and is served for its entire length by the broad [[Riegelmann Boardwalk]]. Numerous amusements, as well as the aquarium and a variety of food shops and arcades, are directly accessible from the landward side of the boardwalk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/coney-island-beach-and-boardwalk/highlights/204|title=Coney Island Beach & Boardwalk Highlights|date=June 26, 1939|website=Coney Island : NYC Parks|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"La Rocco 2004\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tx-3l1hZfPQC&pg=PA137|title=Going Coastal New York City|last=La Rocco|first=Barbara|publisher=Going Coastal|year=2004|isbn=978-0-9729803-0-2|page=137|language=et|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> The boardwalk in Manhattan Beach, located within Manhattan Beach Park, is not connected with the Riegelmann Boardwalk.<ref name=\":20\">{{cite web | title=Manhattan Beach Park : NYC Parks | website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation | date=June 26, 1939 | url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/manhattan-beach-park | access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe beaches in Coney Island used to be private until 1923, when the city bought all the land on the waterfront and created the Riegelmann Boardwalk and Beach.<ref>{{cite web|title=Secrets of Coney Island|website=am New York|date=August 23, 2018|url=https://www.amny.com/secrets-of-new-york/secrets-of-coney-island-1.10182810|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> Today, only the sand beach inside Sea Gate is private; it is accessible solely to residents of that community.<ref name=\"La Rocco 2004\" />\n\nThe public beaches are maintained on a regular basis by the city. Because sand no longer naturally deposits on the beach, it is replenished in regular [[beach nourishment]] projects using [[Dredging|dredged]] sand.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> The public beaches are open and free to use, though the boardwalk is closed during nights from 1 to 5 a.m.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/coney-island-beach-and-boardwalk/facilities/beaches|title=Coney Island Beach & Boardwalk Beaches : NYC Parks|date=June 26, 1939|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref> The beach area is divided into several sections by rock [[groyne]]s that were built in the 1920s to prevent erosion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/2583.pdf|title=Coney Island (Riegelmann) Boardwalk|date=May 15, 2018|website=nyc.gov|publisher=New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref>{{Rp|15}}\n\nThere are several clubs that host activities on Coney Island's beach. The [[Coney Island Polar Bear Club]] consists of a group of people who swim at Coney Island throughout the winter months. Their most popular event is an annual swim on [[New Year's Day]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amny.com/secrets-of-new-york/coney-island-polar-bear-club-forging-into-the-icy-atlantic-ocean-for-decades-1.11255114|title=The Coney Island Polar Bear Club, braving the icy Atlantic|date=December 31, 2018|website=am New York|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Denson 2011\">{{cite book|last=Denson|first=Charles|title=Coney Island and Astroland|publisher=Arcadia Pub.|series=Images of America Series|year=2011|isbn=978-0-7385-7428-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CVNG35jlce8C&pg=PA50|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>{{rp|50}} The beach also serves as the training grounds for the Coney Island Brighton Beach Open Water Swimmers, a group dedicated to promoting [[open water swimming]], which hosts several open water swim races each year.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stein|first=Mara Lemos|title=Brooklyn's Swimming Mecca|website=Wall Street Journal|date=November 24, 2011|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204452104577055950095852414|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mooney|first=Jake|title=On a Beach in Brooklyn, an Empty Lifeguard's Chair|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 10, 2009|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/10/nyregion/thecity/10disp.html|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Coney island board walk.jpg|900px|The boardwalk around sunset}}\n\n=== Public parks ===\nThere are several public parks in Coney Island, operated by the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]. Parks within the main Coney Island neighborhood include:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/maps/|title=Maps : NYC Parks|date=June 26, 1939|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|access-date=June 12, 2019}}</ref>\n* The [[Abe Stark#Legacy|Abe Stark]] Skating Rink, located on the south side of Surf Avenue between West 19th and West 20th Streets, adjacent to the boardwalk. It opened in 1970.<ref>{{cite web|title=Abe Stark Skating Rink Highlights : NYC Parks|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/abe-stark-skating-rink/history|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref>\n* Coney Island Creek Park, located along the south shore of Coney Island Creek. Opened in 1984, it is composed mostly of plants.<ref name=\"NYC Parks CIC\">{{cite web|title=Coney Island Creek Park : NYC Parks|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/coney-island-creek-park/history|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref>\n* Leon S. Kaiser Park, located on the northern side of Neptune Avenue between West 24th and West 32nd Streets, and contains playgrounds, athletic facilities, fitness equipment, and open spaces for barbecuing.<ref name=\"NYC Parks Kaiser\">{{cite web|title=Kaiser Park : NYC Parks|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|date=October 16, 2004|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/leon-s-kaiser-park|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref>\n* Poseidon Playground, located along the beach between West 25th and West 27th Streets, and contains water spray showers, playgrounds, and handball courts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Poseidon Playground : NYC Parks|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/poseidon-playground/history|access-date=July 28, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Steeplechase Park#Current status|Steeplechase Park]], located along the beach between West 16th and West 19th Streets. It contains a public plaza with seating, as well as [[MCU Park]], a [[minor league baseball]] stadium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/steeplechase-park|title=Steeplechase Park : NYC Parks|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|access-date=July 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* Surf Playground, located on the south side of Surf Avenue between West 25th and West 27th Streets, just north of Poseidon Playground. It contains basketball courts, playgrounds, and water spray showers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Surf Playground Highlights|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|date=May 15, 1923|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/surf-playground/history|access-date=July 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Other attractions ===\nThe [[New York Aquarium]] opened in 1957 on the former site of the Dreamland amusement park.<ref name=NYParks-Aquarium-History /> It is located on 602 Surf Avenue between West 5th and West 10th Streets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nyaquarium.com/visitor-info/getting-here|title=Getting Here|date=January 2, 2019|website=New York Aquarium|language=en|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> {{As of|2018}}, the New York Aquarium consists of five exhibits: Aquatheater; Conservation Hall; Sea Cliffs; Sharks, Rays & Turtles; and Ocean Wonders: Sharks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nyaquarium.com/exhibits |title=Exhibits|publisher=New York Aquarium|accessdate=September 22, 2019}}</ref> The original [[Bathysphere]], a deep-sea submersible that made historic journeys underwater in the 1930s, is on display at the aquarium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aps.org/publications/apsnews/201808/history.cfm|title=This Month in Physics History|last=Poffenberger|first=Leah|date=August\u2013September 2018|website=American Physical Society|access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nKeySpan Park, located on the former site of Steeplechase Park, opened in 2001.<ref name=\":15\" /> It hosts the [[Brooklyn Cyclones]] minor league baseball team.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HIxPgnmtQlcC&pg=PA135|title=Brooklyn!, 3rd Edition: The Ultimate Guide to New York's Most Happening Borough|last=Freudenheim|first=E.|last2=Wiener|first2=A.|publisher=St. Martin's Press|year=2004|isbn=978-0-312-32331-8|page=135|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> In 2010, it was renamed after the [[Municipal Credit Union]] (MCU), the city's largest credit union, in an eleven-year naming rights deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/33/6/33_06_sb_keyspan_is_dead.html|title=Lights Out at Keyspan Park as Naming Rights Deal Ends|last=Brown|first=Stephen|date=January 29, 2010|newspaper=[[The Brooklyn Paper]]|accessdate=January 31, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/ny_local/brooklyn/2010/02/04/2010-02-04_brooklyn_cyclones_keyspan_park_renamed_mcu_park.html|title=Brooklyn Cyclones' KeySpan Park Renamed MCU Park|last=Epstein|first=Victor|date=February 4, 2010|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|accessdate=February 4, 2010|last2=Yaniv|first2=Oren|location=New York}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, the [[Ford Amphitheater at Coney Island]] opened on the boardwalk to the west of MCU Park, hosting several live musical acts as well as other events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2016/03/14/coney-island-ampitheater.html|title=NY1 Exclusive: A Look at the New Coney Island Amphitheater|publisher=Ny1.com|date=March 14, 2016|access-date=September 17, 2016}}</ref> It was constructed at the location of the [[Childs Restaurants (Coney Island Boardwalk location)|Childs Restaurant]], which was originally constructed in 1923 and was renovated when the amphitheater was being constructed. The rooftop part of the restaurant reopened in July 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theconeyislandblog.com/?p=902|title=UPDATED: Construction Begins on Controversial Seaside Amphitheater &#124;|publisher=Theconeyislandblog.com|date=|access-date=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe nonprofit organization [[Coney Island USA]] also operates the Coney Island Museum, a collection of memorabilia that chronicles the history of the neighborhood. The museum opened in 1980, and is located at 1208 Surf Avenue near the intersection with West 12th Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thevillager.com/2014/06/coney-island-museum-returns-to-form/|title=Coney Island Museum returns to form|date=June 19, 2014|website=The Villager|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> It charges a $5 admission fee per adult.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coneyisland.com/programs/coney-island-museum|title=Coney Island USA|website=Coney Island Museum|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nycgo.com/museums-galleries/coney-island-museum|title=Coney Island Museum \u2013 Museums & Galleries|website=NYCgo.com|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> Another nonprofit founded in 2004, the Coney Island History Project, operates a space near the Wonder Wheel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nycgo.com/museums-galleries/coney-island-history-project2|title=Coney Island History Project \u2013 Museums & Galleries|website=NYCgo.com|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Events ===\n{{multiple image\n|align=right\n|direction=horizontal\n|total_width=350\n|image1=Nathan's Coney Island July 2007.jpg\n|alt1=Nathan's Famous hot dog restaurant on the Coney Island boardwalk\n|caption1=[[Nathan's Famous]]\n|image2=Freak bar.jpg\n|alt2=The Freak Bar, a Coney Island bar with a Freakshow/Sideshow theme\n|caption2=The Freak Bar\n}}\n\nConey Island USA sponsors various seasonal acts every year. In April, the organization hosts the Noisefest and the Congress of Curious Peoples. This is followed in May or June by the [[Coney Island Mermaid Parade]], which takes place on Surf Avenue and the boardwalk, and features [[Float (parade)|floats]] and performances. During August or September, Coney Island USA produces the Beard and Moustache Competition; Tattoo and Motorcycle Festival; and Coney Island Film Festival. The organization then hosts the Creepshow at the Freakshow, an interactive [[Halloween]]-themed event, in October.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coneyisland.com/programs/special-events|title=Special Events|website=Coney Island USA|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe annual Cosme 5K Charity Run/Walk, supported by the Coney Island Sports Foundation, takes place on the Riegelmann Boardwalk toward the end of June.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/31/29/sports_brooklyn_sportsrunnerspou07142008.html|title=Runners pound the b'walk \u2013 Cosme 5K Charity Run brings athletes to the shore|date=January 1, 2019|website=Brooklyn Paper|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA major national [[volleyball]] tournament hosted by the [[Association of Volleyball Professionals]] (AVP), which is typically hosted on the [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]] of the U.S., was held in Coney Island starting in 2006. The AVP built a 4,000-seat stadium and twelve outer courts next to the boardwalk for the event.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coney Island on the Ball \u2013 Beach volleyball is hitting New York ... & the boardwalk is the place to be|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/nydn-features/coney-island-ball-beach-volleyball-hitting-new-york-boardwalk-place-article-1.634345|website=NY Daily News|access-date = January 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/12/nyregion/thecity/on-a-gritty-shore-california-dreaming.html|title=On a Gritty Shore, California Dreaming|last=Mooney|first=Jake|date=February 12, 2006|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 26, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The tournament returned to Coney Island from 2007 through 2009, but was not hosted at Coney Island in 2010 due to a lack of money.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2010/05/07/spiked-pro-volleyball-tourney-to-skip-coney-island-this-summer/|title=Spiked! Pro volleyball tourney to skip Coney Island this summer|last=Maniscalco|first=Joe|date=May 7, 2010|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> When AVP tournaments resumed in Brooklyn in 2015, they were hosted at [[Brooklyn Bridge Park]] instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/38/30/dtg-park-vs-coney-volleyball-2015-07-24-bk.html|title=Beach bums! Pro volleyball shuns Coney, serves up in Brooklyn Bridge Park|date=July 24, 2015|website=Brooklyn Paper|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the [[Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus]] performed in Coney Island for the first time since 1956. The event, titled ''The Coney Island Boom-A-Ring'', was housed in tents that were located between the boardwalk and Surf Avenue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2009/10/13/coney-island-boom-a-ring-return-in-the-works/|title=Coney Island Boom-A-Ring return in the works|last=Maniscalco|first=Joe|date=October 13, 2009|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/33/23/sg_circus_2010_bk.html|title=Ringling's 'Illuscination' opens on June 17|last=Glass|first=Claire|date=June 4, 2010|website=Brooklyn Paper|language=en|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> The following year, they returned to the same location with ''The Coney Island Illuscination''.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\nStarting in May 2015, Thor Equities unveiled Coney Art Walls, a public art wall project curated by former [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles]] director [[Jeffrey Deitch]] and Thor CEO Joe Sitt. Located at 3050 Stillwell Avenue, the project featured work from more than 30 artists.<ref name=\"auto\" /> Since then, the exhibition has been held every year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/41/25/sci-coney-art-walls-2018-06-22-bk.html|title=Walls of sound: Coney Art Walls host concerts, food, and art|date=June 22, 2018|website=Brooklyn Paper|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brownstoner.com/brooklyn-life/coney-art-walls-brooklyn-jeffrey-deitch-lee-quinones/|title=Coney Art Walls Returns to Brooklyn on May 25|last=Hubert|first=Craig|date=May 24, 2018|website=Brownstoner|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n{{wide image|Coney Island panorama (June 2016) 2.jpg|1500px|3={{center|Panorama of Coney Island waterfront as seen from the pier in June 2016}}}}\n\n== Demographics ==\n[[File:W15 CI volunteers arrive Sandy jeh.jpg|thumb|Volunteers arrive to clear the boardwalk after [[Hurricane Sandy]].]]\nBased on data from the [[2010 United States Census]], the combined population of Coney Island and Sea Gate was 31,965, a decrease of 2,302 (6.7%) from the 34,267 counted in [[2000 United States Census|2000]]. Covering an area of {{convert|851.49|acres}}, the neighborhood had a population density of {{convert|37.5|PD/acre|PD/sqmi PD/sqkm}}.<ref name=\"PLP5\">[http://www1.nyc.gov/assets/planning/download/pdf/data-maps/nyc-population/census2010/t_pl_p5_nta.pdf Table PL-P5 NTA: Total Population and Persons Per Acre \u2013 New York City Neighborhood Tabulation Areas*, 2010], Population Division \u2013 [[New York City]] Department of City Planning, February 2012. Accessed June 15, 2016.</ref>\n\nThe racial makeup of the neighborhood was 32.2% (10,307) [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 30.9% (9,880) [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 8.7% (2,793) [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.2% (78) [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.0% (4) [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.2% (67) from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.5% (467) from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 26.2% (8,369) of the population.<ref name=\"PLP3A\">[http://www1.nyc.gov/assets/planning/download/pdf/data-maps/nyc-population/census2010/t_pl_p3a_nta.pdf Table PL-P3A NTA: Total Population by Mutually Exclusive Race and Hispanic Origin \u2013 New York City Neighborhood Tabulation Areas*, 2010], Population Division \u2013 [[New York City Department of City Planning]], March 29, 2011. Accessed June 14, 2016.</ref> 82% of the population were [[high school]] graduates and 40% had a [[bachelor's degree]] or higher.<ref name=\"PLP3A\" /><ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|2}}\n\nThe entirety of Community Board 13 had 106,459 inhabitants as of [[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene|NYC Health]]'s 2018 Community Health Profile, with an average life expectancy of 80.4 years.<ref name=\"CHP2018\">{{Cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/data/2018chp-bk13.pdf|title=CONEY ISLAND (Including Brighton Beach, Coney Island, Gravesend, Homecrest, Sea Gate and West Brighton)|last=|first=|date=2018|website=nyc.gov|publisher=NYC Health|access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>{{Rp|2, 20}} This is lower than the median life expectancy of 81.2 for all New York City neighborhoods.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/tcny/community-health-assessment-plan.pdf|title=2016-2018 Community Health Assessment and Community Health Improvement Plan: Take Care New York 2020|last=|first=|date=2016|website=[[government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene]]|access-date=September 8, 2017}}</ref>{{Rp|53 (PDF p. 84)}}<ref>{{cite web | title=New Yorkers are living longer, happier and healthier lives | website=New York Post | date=June 4, 2017 | url=https://nypost.com/2017/06/04/new-yorkers-are-living-longer-happier-and-healthier-lives/ | access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> Most inhabitants are adults, with 25% between the ages of 25\u201344, 27% between 45\u201364, and 22% who are at least 65 years old. The ratio of young and college-aged residents was lower, at 19% and 8% respectively.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|2}} Coney Island's elderly population, as a share of the area's total population, is higher than in other New York City neighborhoods.<ref name=\":14\" />{{rp|6}}\n\nAs of 2016, the median [[household income]] in Community District 13 was $39,213.<ref>{{cite web|title=Census profile: NYC-Brooklyn Community District 13--Brighton Beach & Coney Island PUMA, NY|website=Census Reporter|date=July 22, 2018|url=https://censusreporter.org/profiles/79500US3604018-nyc-brooklyn-community-district-13-brighton-beach-coney-island-puma-ny|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> In 2018, an estimated 24% of Coney Island residents lived in poverty, compared to 21% in all of Brooklyn and 20% in all of New York City. One in eight residents (11%) were unemployed, compared to 9% in the rest of both Brooklyn and New York City. Rent burden, or the percentage of residents who have difficulty paying their rent, is 55% in Coney Island, slightly higher than the citywide and boroughwide rates of 52% and 51% respectively. Based on this calculation, {{as of|2018|lc=y}}, Coney Island is not considered to be [[gentrification|gentrifying]].<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|7}}\n\n== Police and crime ==\nConey Island is patrolled by the [[New York City Police Department|NYPD]]'s 60th Precinct, located at 2950 West Eighth Street.<ref name=\"NYPD 60th Precinct\">{{Cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/nypd/bureaus/patrol/precincts/60th-precinct.page|title=NYPD \u2013 60th Precinct|last=|first=|date=|website=www.nyc.gov|publisher=[[New York City Police Department]]|access-date=October 3, 2016}}</ref> Transit District 34 is located at 1243 Surf Avenue, within the [[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue (New York City Subway)|Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue]] subway station.<ref>{{cite web|title=Transit District 34 \u2013 NYPD|website=Welcome to NYC.gov|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/nypd/bureaus/transit-housing/transit-district-34.page|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe 60th Precinct ranked 34th safest out of 69 patrol areas for per-capita crime in 2010. Between 1993 and 2010, major crimes decreased by 72%, including a 76% decrease in robberies, 71% decrease in felony assaults, and 67% decrease in shootings.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnainfo.com/crime-safety-report/brooklyn/coney-island/|title=Coney Island \u2013 DNAinfo.com Crime and Safety Report|website=www.dnainfo.com|access-date=October 6, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723034345/https://www.dnainfo.com/crime-safety-report/brooklyn/coney-island/|archive-date=July 23, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> With a non-fatal assault rate of 51 per 100,000 people, Coney Island's rate of violent crimes per capita is less than that of the city as a whole. The incarceration rate of 168 per 100,000 people is about the same of that of the city as a whole.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|8}} The 60th Precinct has a lower crime rate than in the 1990s, with crimes across all categories having decreased by 84.6% between 1990 and 2017. The precinct saw 0 murders, 20 rapes, 1138 robberies, 232 felony assaults, 89 burglaries, 422 grand larcenies, and 46 grand larcenies auto in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/nypd/downloads/pdf/crime_statistics/cs-en-us-060pct.pdf|title=60th Precinct CompStat Report|date=|website=www.nyc.gov|publisher=[[New York City Police Department]]|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Fire safety ==\n[[File:CI Engine 318 jeh.jpg|thumb|Engine Co. 318/Ladder Co. 166]]\nThe [[New York City Fire Department]] (FDNY) operates two [[firehouse]]s in the area:<ref name=\"fdny-locs\">{{Cite FDNY locations}}</ref>\n* Engine Co. 318/Ladder Co. 166, located at 2510 Neptune Avenue.<ref>{{cite web|title=Engine Company 318/Ladder Company 166|website=FDNYtrucks.com|url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e318.htm|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref> It contains the [[Coney Island Fire Station Pumping Station]], [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Brooklyn|listed]] on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3186|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration:Coney Island Fire Station Pumping Station|date=August 1980|accessdate=February 20, 2011 |author1=Michael S. May |author2=Carol Clark |author3=Anne B. Covell |publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]}} ''See also:'' {{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3293|title=Accompanying four photos}}</ref>\n* Engine Co. 245/Ladder Co. 161/Battalion 43, located at 2929 West 8th Street.<ref>{{cite web|title=Engine Company 245/Ladder Company 161/Battalion 43|website=FDNYtrucks.com|url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e245.htm|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[New York City Fire Department Bureau of EMS|FDNY EMS]] Station 43 is on the grounds of Coney Island Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nychealthandhospitals.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Coney_Island_Hospital_Environmental_Assessment.pdf|title=Environmental Assessment HHC Coney Island Hospital New Critical Services Structure New York City, Kings County, New York|date=July 2015|publisher=[[United States Department of Homeland Security]]; [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]]|website=[[NYC Health + Hospitals|nychealthandhospitals.org]]|access-date=March 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Health ==\n[[File:CIH @ Shore & Ocean Pkwys jeh.jpg|thumb|left|Coney Island Hospital]]\nPreterm and teenage births are slightly more common in Coney Island than in other places citywide. In Coney Island, there were 95 preterm births per 1,000 live births (compared to 87 per 1,000 citywide), and 20.2 teenage births per 1,000 live births (compared to 19.3 per 1,000 citywide), slightly higher than in the median neighborhood.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|11}} Coney Island has a high population of residents who are [[Health insurance coverage in the United States|uninsured]], or who receive healthcare through [[Medicaid]].<ref name=\":14\">[http://www.health.ny.gov/health_care/medicaid/redesign/dsrip/pps_applications/docs/maimonides_medical_center/3.8_maimonides_cna.pdf New York City Health Provider Partnership Brooklyn Community Needs Assessment: Final Report], [[New York Academy of Medicine]] (October 3, 2014).</ref> In 2018, this population of uninsured residents was estimated to be 14%, which is higher than the citywide rate of 12%.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|14}}\n\nThe concentration of [[particulates|fine particulate matter]], the deadliest type of [[air pollution|air pollutant]], in Coney Island is {{convert|0.0067|mg/m3|oz/ft3}}, lower than the citywide and boroughwide averages.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|9}} Nineteen percent of Coney Island residents are [[Smoking|smokers]], which is higher the city average of 14% of residents being smokers.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|13}} In Coney Island, 28% of residents are [[Obesity|obese]], 15% are [[Diabetes mellitus|diabetic]], and 31% have [[hypertension|high blood pressure]]\u2014higher than the citywide averages of 24%, 11%, and 28% respectively.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|16}} In addition, 18% of children are obese, compared to the citywide average of 20%.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|12}}\n\nNinety-two percent of residents eat some fruits and vegetables every day, which is slightly higher than the city's average of 87%. In 2018, 70% of residents described their health as \"good,\" \"very good,\" or \"excellent,\" lower than the city's average of 78%.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|13}} For every supermarket in Coney Island, there are 21 [[convenience store|bodegas]].<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|10}}\n\nThe primary hospital in the neighborhood is [[Coney Island Hospital]].<ref name=\":14\" />{{rp|6}}\n\n== Post offices and ZIP codes ==\nConey Island's primary [[ZIP Code]] is 11224,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zipmap.net/zips/11224.htm|title=Zip Code 11224, Brooklyn, New York Zip Code Boundary Map (NY)|website=United States Zip Code Boundary Map (USA)|access-date=March 10, 2019}}</ref> though the small portions located east of West 1st Street and Ocean Parkway are located in ZIP Code 11235.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zipmap.net/zips/11235.htm|title=Zip Code 11235, Brooklyn, New York Zip Code Boundary Map (NY)|website=United States Zip Code Boundary Map (USA)|access-date=March 10, 2019}}</ref> There are two [[United States Post Office]] branches in Coney Island. The Coney Island Station is located at 2727 Mermaid Avenue,<ref>{{cite web|title=USPS Locations|url=https://tools.usps.com/go/POLocatorDetailsAction!input.action?&radius=20&locationType=po&locationTypeQ=po&locationID=1358925| accessdate = June 20, 2018}}</ref> and the Neptune Station is located at 532 Neptune Avenue.<ref>{{cite web|title=USPS Locations|url=https://tools.usps.com/go/POLocatorDetailsAction!input.action?&radius=20&locationType=po&locationTypeQ=po&locationID=374586| accessdate = June 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nConey Island generally has a similar ratio of college-educated residents to the rest of the city. While 45% of residents age 25 and older have a college education or higher, 18% have less than a high school education and 37% are high school graduates or have some college education. By contrast, 40% of Brooklynites and 38% of city residents have a college education or higher.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|6}} The percentage of Coney Island students excelling in math has been increasing, though reading achievement has declined; math achievement rose from 53 percent in 2000 to 72 percent in 2011, but reading achievement fell from 57 to 55 percent within the same time period.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=http://furmancenter.org/files/sotc/BK_13_11.pdf|title=Coney Island \u2013 BK 13|last=|first=|date=2011|website=|publisher=[[Furman Center for Real Estate and Urban Policy]]|access-date=October 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nConey Island's rate of elementary school student absenteeism is higher than the rest of New York City. In Coney Island, 26% of elementary school students missed twenty or more days per [[school year]], compared to the citywide average of 20% of students.<ref name=\":21\" />{{Rp|24 (PDF p. 55)}}<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|7}}\n\n=== Elementary, middle, and high schools ===\n[[File:Abraham Lincoln High School.jpg|thumb|Abraham Lincoln High School]]\nConey Island is served by the [[New York City Department of Education]], and students in the neighborhood are automatically \"zoned\" into the nearest public schools. The zoned schools for the main portion of Coney Island include:\n* PS 90 Edna Cohen School (grades K-5)<ref>Tartar, Andre. \"[http://nymag.com/daily/intel/2012/08/teacher-exodus-at-troubled-coney-island-school.html Teacher Exodus at Coney Island School Where Principal Banned \u2018God Bless the USA\u2019].\" ''[[New York Magazine]]''. August 19, 2012. Retrieved on October 17, 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=P.S. 90 Edna Cohen School|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K090|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* PS 100 Coney Island School (grades K-5)<ref>{{cite web|title=P.S. 100 The Coney Island School|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K100|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Scharfenberg1\">{{cite web | last=Scharfenberg | first=David | title=Safety Belts On? Renewal Has Its Hazards | website=The New York Times | date=November 19, 2006 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/19/realestate/19livi.html | access-date=July 6, 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* PS 188 The Michael E. Berdy School (grades K-4)<ref>{{cite web|title=P.S. 188 Michael E. Berdy|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K188|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* PS/IS 288 The Shirley Tanyhill School (grades PK-8)<ref>{{cite web|title=P.S. 288 The Shirley Tanyhill|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K288|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* IS 303 Herbert S. Eisenberg (grades 6-8)<ref name=Scharfenberg1 /><ref name=\"Hughes2\">{{cite web | last=Hughes | first=C. J. | title=Waterfront Living That Doesn't Break the Bank | website=The New York Times | date=April 30, 2010 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/02/realestate/02living.html | access-date=July 6, 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=I.S. 303 Herbert S. Eisenberg|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K303|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* PS 329 (grades PK-5)<ref>{{cite web|title=P.S. 329 Surfside|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K329|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIS 239, the [[Mark Twain School for the Gifted and Talented]] (6\u20138), is a [[magnet school]] for gifted students, and it accepts students from around the city.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mark Twain I.S. 239 for the Gifted & Talented|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K239|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref> In 2006, David Scharfenberg of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said, \"Coney Island's elementary schools are a mixed lot, with only some exceeding citywide averages on the state's testing regimen.\"<ref name=Scharfenberg1 />\n\nAll New York City high school students can go to any high school in the city. There are two public high schools in Coney Island: [[Abraham Lincoln High School (Brooklyn)|Abraham Lincoln High School]]<ref name=Scharfenberg1 /><ref>{{cite web|title=Abraham Lincoln High School|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K410|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref> and [[Rachel Carson High School for Coastal Studies]].<ref name=\"Lucadamo\">\"[http://articles.nydailynews.com/2006-05-03/local/18332169_1_teachers-students-troubled-school Teachers Boycott Hs To Protest An Arrest].\" ''[[New York Daily News]]''. May 3, 2007. Retrieved on October 11, 2012.</ref>\n\n=== Public library ===\n[[File:CI BPL 1901 Mermaid Av jeh.jpg|thumb|Coney Island library branch]]\nThe [[Brooklyn Public Library]] (BPL)'s Coney Island branch is located at 1901 Mermaid Avenue, near the intersection with West 19th Street. It opened in 1911 as an unmanned deposit station. Ten years later, it moved to the former ''[[Coney Island Times]]'' offices and became fully staffed. In 1954 another branch was built. According to BPL's website, the library was referred to as \"the first-ever library built on stilts over the Atlantic Ocean.\" The branch was rebuilt in 2013 after being damaged in Hurricane Sandy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bklynlibrary.org/locations/coney-island/history|title=Coney Island Library|last=|first=|date=August 19, 2011|website=Brooklyn Public Library|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Transportation ==\n[[File:Coney IslandStillwell.JPG|thumb|left|[[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue station]]]]\nConey Island is served by four [[New York City Subway]] stations.<ref>{{NYCS const|map}}</ref><ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\">{{cite NYCS map|neighborhood|Coney Island}}</ref> The [[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue station]], the terminal of the {{NYCS trains|Stillwell}}, is one of the largest elevated rapid transit stations in the world, with eight tracks serving four platforms.<ref name=\"MTA-Stillwell-2014\" /> The entire station, built in 1917\u20131920 as a replacement for the former surface-level [[Culver Depot]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thethirdrail.net./0305/stillwell4.html|title=The New BMT Coney Island Terminal|last=Matus|first=Paul|date=May 2003|website=thethirdrail.net|page=4|access-date=August 15, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303172251/http://thethirdrail.net/0305/stillwell4.html|archive-date=March 3, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> was rebuilt in 2001\u20132004.<ref name=\"Chan\" /><ref name=\"MTA-Stillwell-2014\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/news/2014/05/20/stillwell-terminal-remains-sparkling-jewel-decade-after-full-rehabilitation|title=Stillwell Terminal Remains a Sparkling Jewel a Decade after Full Rehabilitation|last=|first=|date=May 20, 2014|website=www.mta.info|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|access-date=August 15, 2016}}</ref> The other subway stations within Coney Island are {{stn|West Eighth Street\u2013New York Aquarium}}, served by the {{NYCS trains|West 8th|time=nolink}}; {{stn|Neptune Avenue}}, served by the {{NYCS trains|Culver IND south|time=nolink}}; and {{stn|Ocean Parkway}}, served by the {{NYCS trains|Brighton south|time=nolink}}.<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n\nA [[Bus station|bus terminal]] beneath the Stillwell Avenue station serves the {{NYC bus link|B68}} to [[Prospect Park (Brooklyn)|Prospect Park]], the {{NYC bus link|B74}} to Sea Gate, the {{NYC bus link|B64}} to [[Bay Ridge, Brooklyn|Bay Ridge]], and the {{NYC bus link|B82}} to [[Starrett City, Brooklyn|Starrett City]]. Additionally, the {{NYC bus link|B36}} runs from Sea Gate to [[Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn|Sheepshead Bay]]. The {{NYC bus link|X28|X38|prose=y}} provide express bus service to Manhattan.<ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n\nThe three main west-east arteries in the neighborhood are Neptune Avenue, Mermaid Avenue, and Surf Avenue from north to south. Neptune Avenue becomes Emmons Avenue at Sheepshead Bay, while Surf Avenue becomes [[Ocean Parkway (Brooklyn)|Ocean Parkway]] and then runs north toward Prospect Park. The north-south cross streets in Coney Island are numbered, with \"West\" prepended to their numbers. The street numbers run from West 1st Street at Coney Island's eastern border to West 37th Street at the western border, adjacent to Sea Gate.<ref>{{Google maps|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Coney+Island,+Brooklyn,+NY/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x89c24448979d75cb:0x54745adc3c8f1179?sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjk652izLDcAhVhiOAKHVPCClYQ8gEI9QEwFg|title=Coney Island, Brooklyn, NY|access-date=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nConey Island contains several [[Cycling in New York City|bicycle paths]]. The Ocean Parkway bicycle path terminates in the neighborhood, while the [[Shore Parkway]] bike path (part of the [[Brooklyn Waterfront Greenway]]) runs east along [[Jamaica Bay]] and west and north along New York Harbor. On-street bike lanes are marked in Neptune Avenue and other streets in Coney Island. In addition, the Riegelmann Boardwalk is open to cyclists during the daytime, though bicycling hours are restricted during summers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bicycle Maps|website=NYC.gov|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/bikemap-2018.pdf|publisher=[[New York City Department of Transportation]]|date=2018|access-date=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe western part of Coney Island is expected to be served by [[NYC Ferry]]'s Coney Island route beginning in 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amny.com/transit/nyc-ferry-routes-1.25782023|title=NYC Ferry is adding 2 new routes|date=January 10, 2019|website=am New York|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ny.curbed.com/2019/1/10/18177078/nyc-ferry-transportation-staten-island-coney-island|title=NYC Ferry will launch service to Staten Island, Coney Island|last=Plitt|first=Amy|date=January 10, 2019|website=Curbed NY|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NYC Ferry Expansion 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ferry.nyc/nycferry-2020-2021-service-route-expansion/|title=2020-2021 Expansion|website=New York City Ferry Service|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n{{Main|Coney Island in popular culture}}\nConey Island has been featured in many novels, films, television shows, cartoons, and theatrical plays.<ref name=\"Immerso2002\">{{cite book|last=Immerso|first=Michael|title=Coney Island: the people's playground|publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=2002|edition=illustrated|isbn=978-0-8135-3138-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i4POVzmwY9cC}}</ref>{{rp|176}}<ref name=\"Rabinovitz 2004\">{{cite book|last=Rabinovitz|first=Lauren|title=American cinema's transitional era: audiences, institutions, practices|editor=Charlie Keil, Shelley Stamp|publisher=University of California Press|year=2004|edition=illustrated|chapter=The Coney Island Comedies|isbn=978-0-520-24027-8|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cB2MfzmdwYkC&pg=RA1-PA171#v=onepage&q=&f=false}}</ref> This is linked to its iconic status as a vacation destination.<ref>{{cite book | last=Frank | first=R.J. | author2=Wadsworth Atheneum Museum of Art | author3=San Diego Museum of Art | author4=Brooklyn Museum | author5=McNay Art Museum | title=Coney Island: Visions of an American Dreamland, 1861\u20132008 | publisher=Wadsworth Atheneum Museum of Art | year=2015 | isbn=978-0-300-18990-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pt22oQEACAAJ | access-date=February 28, 2019 | page=}}</ref> Various [[slapstick]] comedies and films have been set at Coney Island or allude to it. There have also been several television documentaries about the area's history.<ref name=\"Rabinovitz 2004\" />{{rp|137\u2013142}}<ref>{{cite web | title=Movie Shot at Coney Island List | website=Westland | date=July 10, 2006 | url=https://www.westland.net/coneyisland/articles/movielist.htm | access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* [[Rem Koolhaas]], ''[[Delirious New York: A Retroactive Manifesto for Manhattan]]'' (Academy Editions, London, 1978; republished, The Monacelli Press, 1994&nbsp;\u2014 a large part of the book focuses on Coney Island amusement parks)\n* John F. Kasson, ''Amusing The Million: Coney Island at the Turn of the Century'' (Hill and Wang, New York, 1978; Distributed in Canada by Douglas and McIntyre Ltd.)\n* Charles Denson, ''Coney Island: Lost and Found (Ten Speed Press, 2002)\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/coney Coney Island], a 1991 documentary film by [[Ric Burns]] for [[American Experience]]\n* {{Cite book|publisher=E. Leypoldt |location = New York|title=Percy's Pocket dictionary of Coney Island|author=Townsend Percy |date = 1880|oclc=5926329|ol = 6906857M}}\n* {{Cite book|publisher=Austin Publishing Co. |location = New York|title=The tourists companion and guide to Coney Island, Fort Hamilton, Bath Beach, Sheepshead Bay, Rockaway Beach and Far Rockaway|author=J. Perkins Tracy |date = 1887|ol = 23411073M}}\n{{refend}}\n\n=== Further reading ===\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* [http://www.heartofconeyisland.com/ The Comprehensive History of Coney Island] at Heart of Coney Island\n* Coney Island [http://www.westland.net/coneyisland/histart.htm History Articles]\n* [http://www.indypendent.org/?p=449 Bland as Sand: Developers Stalk Coney Island], The Indypendent\n* [http://www.indypendent.org/?p=450 Gritty and Trashy... That\u2019s Why I Love It], The Indypendent\n* Bruce, Jeannette. [https://archive.is/20130102055107/http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1080222/index.htm \"Where The Fun Was,\"]''Sports Illustrated'', August 28, 1967\n* Coney Island [http://www.coneyislandhistory.org/ History Project]\n* {{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Coney Island |volume=6 |page=897 |short=1}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikivoyage|Brooklyn/Coney Island and Brighton Beach}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|Coney Island, Brooklyn}}\n* [http://cityinenvironment.blogspot.com/2013/03/evolution-coney-island.html City in Environment \u2013 Evolution Coney Island]\n* [http://newyork.thecityatlas.org/lifestyle/future-southern-brooklyn-including-coney-island/ The future of Southern Brooklyn, including Coney Island \u2013 newyork.thecityatlas.org]\n\n{{Coney Island}}\n{{Brooklyn}}\n{{Portal bar|New York (state)|New York City}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Coney Island| ]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Barrier islands of New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Islands of Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Former islands of New York City]]\n[[Category:Seaside resorts in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Islands of New York City]]\n[[Category:Dutch place names in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Coney Island (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Coney Island\n| native_name             =\n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| settlement_type         = [[Neighborhoods of Brooklyn|Neighborhood of Brooklyn]]\n| image_skyline           = Coney Island beach and amusement parks (June 2016).jpg\n| imagesize               = 300px\n| image_alt               =\n| image_caption           = Coney Island beach, amusement parks, and high rises as seen from the pier in June 2016\n| image_flag              =\n| flag_alt                =\n| image_seal              =\n| seal_alt                =\n| image_shield            =\n| shield_alt              =\n| nickname=\"Playground of the World\"\n| motto                   =\n| image_map               = {{maplink|frame=y|plain=y|frame-align=center|zoom=12|type=shape|from=Neighbourhoods/New York City/Coney Island.map}}<!--{{maplink|frame=y|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-lat=40.705|frame-long=-73.975|zoom=9|type=point|coord={{coord|40.574|-73.978}}}}-->\n| map_alt                 =\n| map_caption             = Location in New York City<br>Note: red area overlaps with Sea Gate.\n| pushpin_map             = <!--USA New York City#USA New York#USA-->\n| pushpin_label_position  =\n| pushpin_map_alt         =\n| pushpin_map_caption     = <!--Location-->\n| coordinates             = {{coord|40.574|-73.978|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           =\n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|United States}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = {{flag|New York}}\n| subdivision_type2       = [[City]]\n| subdivision_name2       = {{flagicon image|Flag of New York City.svg}} [[New York City]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Borough (New York City)|Borough]]\n| subdivision_name3       = {{flagicon image|Flag of Borough of Brooklyn.png}} [[Brooklyn]]\n| subdivision_type4       = [[Community boards of Brooklyn|Community District]]\n| subdivision_name4       = [[Brooklyn Community Board 13|Brooklyn 13]]<ref name=\"NYCPlanning\">{{cite web |title=NYC Planning {{!}} Community Profiles|url=https://communityprofiles.planning.nyc.gov/brooklyn/13|website=communityprofiles.planning.nyc.gov|publisher=New York City Department of City Planning|accessdate=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| established_title       = Settled\n| established_date        = 17th century\n| founder                 = Dutch settlers\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_total_km2          = 1.790\n| population_footnotes    =\n| population_total        = 24,711\n| population_as_of        = 2010\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      =\n| population_note         =\n| timezone1 = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern]]\n| utc_offset1 = \u22125\n| timezone1_DST = [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n| utc_offset1_DST = \u22124\n| postal_code_type        = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code             = 11224\n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbering plan|Area code]]\n| area_code               = [[Area codes 718, 347, and 929|718, 347, 929]], and [[Area code 917|917]]\n}}\n\n'''Coney Island''' is a residential and commercial [[List of Brooklyn neighborhoods|neighborhood]] and entertainment area, located on a [[peninsula]] in the southwestern part of the [[borough (New York City)|borough]] of [[Brooklyn]] in [[New York City]]. The neighborhood is bounded by [[Manhattan Beach, Brooklyn|Manhattan Beach]] to its east, [[Lower New York Bay]] to the south and west, and [[Gravesend, Brooklyn|Gravesend]] to the north, and includes the subsections of [[Sea Gate, Brooklyn|Sea Gate]] to its west and [[Brighton Beach]] to its east. Coney Island was formerly the westernmost of the [[Outer Barrier]] islands on the southern shore of [[Long Island]], but in the early 20th century it became a peninsula, connected to the rest of Long Island by [[Land reclamation|land fill]].\n\nThe origin of Coney Island's name is disputed, but the area was originally part of the colonial town of Gravesend. By the mid-19th century it had become a [[seaside resort]], and by the late 19th century, [[amusement park]]s had also been built at the location. The attractions reached a historical peak during the first half of the 20th century. However, they declined in popularity after [[World War II]], and following years of neglect, several structures were torn down. Various redevelopment projects were proposed for Coney Island in the 1970s through the 2000s, though most of these were not carried out. The area was revitalized with the opening of [[MCU Park]] in 2001 and several amusement rides in the 2010s.\n\nConey Island has 31,965 residents as of the [[2010 United States Census]]. The neighborhood is ethnically diverse, and the neighborhood's poverty rate of 27% is slightly higher than that of the city as a whole.\n\nConey Island is part of [[Brooklyn Community Board 13|Brooklyn Community District 13]] and its primary [[ZIP Code]] is 11224.<ref name=\"NYCPlanning\" /> It is patrolled by the 60th Precinct of the [[New York City Police Department]].<ref name=\"NYPD 60th Precinct\" /> Fire services are provided by the [[New York City Fire Department]]'s Engine 245/Ladder 161/Battalion 43 and Engine 318/Ladder 166.<ref name=\"fdny-locs\" /> Politically, Coney Island is represented by the [[New York City Council]]'s 47th District.<ref>[http://www.nyc.gov/html/dc/downloads/pdf/brooklyn.pdf Current City Council Districts for Kings County], [[New York City]]. Accessed May 5, 2017.</ref> The area is well served by the [[New York City Subway]] and local bus routes, and contains several public elementary and middle schools.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:ConeyIslandAerial.jpg|left|thumb|250px|The Coney Island peninsula from the air]]\nThe Coney Island neighborhood is generally coextensive with the [[peninsula]] of the same name, located on the western end of [[Long Island]] lying to the west of the [[Outer Barrier]] islands along Long Island's southern shore. The peninsula is about {{convert|4|mi|km}} long and {{convert|0.5|mi|km}} wide. It extends into [[Lower New York Bay]] with [[Sheepshead Bay]] to its northeast, Gravesend Bay and [[Coney Island Creek]] to its northwest, and the main part of Brooklyn to its north. At its highest it is {{convert|7|feet|m}} above sea level. Coney Island was formerly an actual island, separated from greater Brooklyn by Coney Island Creek, and was the westernmost of the Outer Barrier islands. A large section of the creek was filled in the 1920s and 1930s, turning the island into a peninsula.<ref name=\"auto\" /> A narrower definition of the Coney Island neighborhood is given by the ''[[Encyclopedia of New York City]]'', which only considers the area west of Ocean Parkway (including Sea Gate and [[Nortons Point Light]]) to be part of that neighborhood.<ref>{{cite enc-nyc2|page=299}}</ref>\n\nThe perimeter of Coney Island features manmade structures designed to maintain its current shape. The beaches are currently not a natural feature; the sand that is naturally supposed to replenish Coney Island is cut off by the [[jetty]] at [[Breezy Point, Queens]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">[https://3dparks.wr.usgs.gov/nyc/parks/loc72.htm U.S. Geological Survey, Geology of National Parks, 3D and Photographic Tours, 72. Coney Island], [[United States Department of the Interior]]. Accessed December 15, 2016.</ref><ref name=NYC.gov-ResilientNY-Ch17 />{{rp|337}} Sand has been redeposited on the beaches via [[beach nourishment]] since the construction of [[Riegelmann Boardwalk]] in 1922\u20131923,<ref>{{cite conference|last=Dornhelm|first=Richard B.|title=The Coney Island Public Beach and Boardwalk Improvement of 1923|publisher=American Society of Civil Engineers | location=Reston, VA|date=September 25, 2003|isbn=978-0-7844-0682-3|doi=10.1061/40682(2003)6|page=}}</ref> and is held in place by around two dozen [[groyne]]s. A large sand-replenishing project along Coney Island and Brighton Beach took place in the 1990s.<ref name=NYC.gov-ResilientNY-Ch17 />{{rp|337}} Sheepshead Bay at the peninsula's northeast corner is, for the most part, enclosed in [[Bulkhead (barrier)|bulkheads]].<ref name=\"NYC.gov-ResilientNY-Ch17\">{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/sirr/downloads/pdf/Ch17_SouthernBrooklyn_FINAL_singles.pdf|title=A Stronger, More Resilient New York|chapter=Chapter 17, Southern Brooklyn|pages=335\u2013364|publisher=[[Government of New York City|City of New York]]|date=2013|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> Two major parks, Kaiser Park and Coney Island Creek Park, are located on the northwest side of the peninsula along Coney Island Creek.<ref name=\"NYC Parks Kaiser\" /><ref name=\"NYC Parks CIC\" />\n\n== Name ==\nThe original [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] inhabitants of the region, the [[Lenape]], called this area ''Narrioch''. This name has been attributed the meaning of \"''land without shadows''\"<ref name=\"Solomon 1999\" /> or \"''always in light''\"<ref>{{cite book |via=HathiTrust | url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/008511115 |title=Brooklyn before the bridge: American paintings from the Long Island Historical Society |publisher=Long Island Historical Society, Brooklyn Museum |year=1982 |page=54 | access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> describing how its south facing beaches always remained in sunlight. A second meaning attributed to ''Narrioch'' is \"''point''\" or \"''corner of land''\".<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=c5hky9f5PgoC | last=Pritchard | first=Evan | title=Native New Yorkers : the legacy of the Algonquin people of New York | publisher=Council Oak Books | location=San Francisco | year=2002 | isbn=978-1-57178-107-9 | oclc=46937559 | page=105}}</ref>\n\nThere is no clear historical consensus on how the island got the name \"Coney Island\".<ref name=Name /><ref name=\"Henin\" /><ref name=\"Solomon 1999\">{{cite book | last=Solomon |first=Steve | title=Coney Island | publisher=Top Hat Press | location=Baltimore, MD | year=1999 | isbn=978-0-912509-08-2 | oclc=42191804 | page=13}}</ref> A version of this name, ''Conyne Eylandt'', shows up in early 17th century Dutch maps.<ref name=\"hunter\">{{cite book |last1= Hunter |first1=Douglas|date=2009|title= Half Moon: Henry Hudson and the Voyage that Redrew the Map of the New World|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=kMykb1AbSHsC&pg=PA165|publisher= Bloomsbury Publishing USA|page=278|isbn=978-1-60819-098-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Schwartz | first=Seymour I. | last2=Ehrenberg | first2=Ralph E. | title=The mapping of America | publisher=H.N. Abrams | year=1980 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KCQYAQAAMAAJ | access-date=October 20, 2019 | page=108}}</ref> The most popular theory is the name came from the old spelling of the Dutch word for [[rabbit]], \"conyn\", derived from a purported large population of wild rabbits, giving it the name \"Rabbit Island\",<ref name=\"autogenerated51\">{{cite book |last= Sijs van der |first= Nicoline |authorlink= Nicoline van der Sijs |date=2009 |title= Cookies, Coleslaw, and Stoops: The Influence of Dutch on the North American Languages |page=51 |isbn= 978-9089641243}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web | url = http://international.loc.gov/intldl/awkbhtml/kb-1/kb-1-2-5.html | title = The Atlantic World: Dutch Place Names | website = The Dutch in America, 1609\u20131664 | publisher = The Library of Congress | access-date = May 10, 2016 }}</ref> with the name being [[Anglicisation|anglicized]] to ''Coney Island'' after the English took over the colony in 1664,<ref>*{{cite web|first=Robert|last=Morden|author-link=Robert Morden|title=A Map of ye English Empire in the Continent of America|date=1690|url=http://www.sunysb.edu/libmap/ch1.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060420012731/http://www.sunysb.edu/libmap/ch1.htm |archive-date=April 20, 2006 |postscript=&nbsp;(Coney Island is labelled \"Conney Isle\".)}}\n* Henry Popple, \"A Map of the British Empire in America\", Sheet 12, 1733. Coney Island is labeled \"Coney Island\".\n* [[Joseph Frederick Wallet DesBarres|Joseph DesBarre's]] chart of New York harbor in the 1779 work ''Atlantic Neptune'', as cited in {{cite book | last=Sanderson | first=Eric | title=Mannahatta : a natural history of New York City | publisher=Abrams | location=New York | year=2009 | isbn=978-0-8109-9633-5 | oclc=258332257 | page=47 }} In 1779 the island was a cluster of three low hummocks in the shallow \"East Bank\" flats at the eastern end of [[Gravesend Bay]].\n* John H. Eddy, \"Map Of The Country Thirty Miles Round the City of New York\", 1811. Coney Island is labeled \"Coney I.\"</ref> ''[[wikt:coney#English|coney]]'' being the corresponding English word.<ref name=\"autogenerated51\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated2\" /><ref name=\"Coney etymology\">{{cite web|title=''coney''|url=https://www.etymonline.com/search?q=coney|website=Online Etymology Dictionary|access-date=March 2, 2018}}</ref> It could also be a corruption of the name of the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] tribe, the Konoh or Konoi (the \"Bear Band\"), who once inhabited the island.<ref name=\"Name\">{{cite web | title=Coney Island |work=American Experience |publisher=PBS | date=February 4, 1991 | url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/films/coney/ | access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Henin\">Official Brooklyn Guide Book, Henin & Company, 1939, page 27</ref><ref name=\"Solomon 1999\" /> Other origins put forward include it was the surname of a family of Dutch settlers who lived there,<ref name=Name /> or that \"Conyne\" was a distortion of the name of [[Henry Hudson]]'s second mate on the [[Halve Maen]], [[John Colman]], who was slain by natives on the 1609 expedition and buried at a place they named Colman's Point, possibly coinciding with Coney Island,<ref name=hunter /><ref name=Name />\n\n== History ==\n=== Early settlement ===\n[[Giovanni da Verrazzano]] was the first European explorer to discover the island of Narrioch during his expeditions to the area in 1527 and 1529. He was subsequently followed by Henry Hudson.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|34}} The Dutch established the colony of [[New Amsterdam]] in present-day Coney Island in the early 17th century. The Native American population in the area dwindled as the Dutch settlement grew and the entire southwest section of present-day Brooklyn was purchased in 1645 from the Native Americans in exchange for a gun, a blanket, and a kettle.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pritchard|first=E.T.|title=Native New Yorkers: The Legacy of the Algonquin People of New York|publisher=Council Oak Books|year=2002|isbn=978-1-57178-107-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c5hky9f5PgoC|access-date=July 21, 2018|page=106}}</ref><ref name=\"Douglass\">{{cite news|last=Douglass|first=Harvey|date=March 23, 1933|title=Coney Island Scenes Shift, Never Change|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/59998009/|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com|access-date=March 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1644, a colonist named Guysbert Op Dyck was given a patent for 88 acres of land in the town of [[Gravesend, Brooklyn|Gravesend]], on the southwestern shore of Brooklyn. The patent included Conyne Island, an island just off the southwestern shore of the town of Gravesend, as well as Conyne Hook, a peninsula just east of the island. At the time, both were part of Gravesend.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|4}}<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=http://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52628845/|title=Passed in Review|last=Currie|first=George|date=August 10, 1936|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=July 21, 2018|page=14|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com}}</ref> East of Conyne Hook was the largest section of island called Gysbert's, Guysbert's, or Guisbert's Island (also called Johnson Island), containing most of the arable land and extending east through today's [[Brighton Beach]] and [[Manhattan Beach, Brooklyn|Manhattan Beach]].<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|34}}<ref name=\"Ierardi\">{{cite book|last=Ierardi|first=Eric|title=Gravesend, the home of Coney Island|publisher=Arcadia | location=Charleston, S.C|year=2001|isbn=978-0-7385-2361-3|oclc=51632931|page=46}}</ref><ref name=\"heartofconeyisland1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.heartofconeyisland.com/early-coney-island-history.html|title=Coney Island History \u2013 Early History|website=Heart of Coney Island}}</ref> This was officially the first official real estate transaction for the island.<ref name=\":1\" />\nOp Dyck never occupied his patent, and in 1661 he sold it off to Dick De Wolf. The land's new owner banned Gravesend residents from using Guisbert's Island and built a salt-works on the land, provoking outrage among Gravesend livestock herders. New Amsterdam was transferred to the English in 1664, and four years later, the English Governor created a new charter for Gravesend that excluded Coney Island. Subsequently, Guisbert's Island was divided into plots meted out to several dozen settlers. However, in 1685, the island became part of Gravesend again as a result of a new charter with the Native Americans.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|36}}\n\n[[File:Coney Island (Detail) Chart of the entrance of Hudson's River, from Sandy Hook to New York - with the banks, depths of water, sailing-marks, &ca (NYPL b14099970-1222740).png|thumb|center|600px|Detail of a 1776 nautical chart showing the collection of islands and shifting sand that eventually became present day Coney Island.]]\n\nAt the time of European settlement, the land that makes up the present-day Coney Island was divided across several separate islands. All of these islands were part of the [[outer barrier]] on the southern shore of Long Island, and their land areas and boundaries changed frequently.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|34}} Only the westernmost island was called Coney Island; it currently makes up part of [[Sea Gate, Brooklyn|Sea Gate]]. At the time, it was a 1.25-mile shifting [[Spit (landform)|sandspit]] with a detached island at its western end extending into Lower New York Bay.<ref name=\"hunter\" /> In a 1679\u20131680 journal, Jasper Danckaerts and Peter Sluyter noted that \"Conijnen Eylandt\" was fully separated from the rest of Brooklyn. The explorers observed that \"Nobody lives upon it, but it is used in winter for keeping cattle, horses, oxen, hogs and others.\"<ref name=\"hunter\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|36}}\n\nBy the early 18th century, the town of Gravesend was periodically granting seven-year-long leases to freeholders, who would then have the exclusive use of Coney Hook and Coney Island. In 1734, a road to Coney Hook was laid out.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|37}}  Thomas Stillwell, a prominent Gravesend resident who was the freeholder for Coney Island and Coney Hook at the time, proposed to build a ditch through Coney Hook so it would be easier for his cattle to graze. He convinced several friends in the nearby town of [[Jamaica, Queens|Jamaica]] to help him in this effort, telling them that the creation of such a ditch would allow them to ship goods from [[Jamaica Bay]] to [[New York Harbor]] without having to venture out into the ocean.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|37}} In 1750, the \"Jamaica Ditch\" was dug through Coney Hook from Brown's Creek in the west to Hubbard's Creek in the east.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x9YsAAAAYAAJ|title=A History of the Town of Gravesend, N.Y.|last=Stockwell|first=A.P.|last2=Stillwell|first2=W.H.|year=1884|page=|access-date=July 21, 2018}}</ref>{{Rp|34}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coneyislandhistory.org/collection/filter/Jamaica-Ditch|title=Jamaica Ditch|website=Coney Island History Project|access-date=July 21, 2018}}</ref> The creation of the canal turned Coney Hook into a detached {{Convert|0.5|mi|km|-long|adj=mid}} island called Pine Island, so named due to the woods on it.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />{{Rp|34}}\n\nEach island was separated by an [[inlet]] that could only be crossed at low tide. By the end of the 18th century, the ongoing shifting of sand along the barrier islands had closed up the inlets to the point that residents began filling them in and joining them as one island. Development of Coney Island was slow until the 19th century due to land disputes, the [[American Revolutionary War]], and the [[War of 1812]].<ref name=\"heartofconeyisland1\" /> Coney Island was so remote that [[Herman Melville]] wrote ''[[Moby-Dick]]'' on the island in 1849, and [[Henry Clay]] and [[Daniel Webster]] discussed the [[Missouri Compromise]] at the island the next year.<ref name=BuffaloNews-LostGlamour-1957 />\n\n=== Resort development ===\n[[File:Railroad Station, Coney Island, Brooklyn, ca. 1872-1887. (5832942813).jpg|thumb|left|Railroad station in Coney Island, Brooklyn, ca. 1872\u20131887]]\n\nIn 1824, the Gravesend and Coney Island Road and Bridge Company built the first bridge across Jamaica Ditch (by now known as Coney Island Creek), connecting the island with the mainland. The company also built a shell road across the island to the beaches.<ref name=\"heartofconeyisland1\" /><ref name=\"BDE-YellowedPages-1939\">{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52755417/|title=Yellowed Pages of Coney Island Register Reveal Visits of Many Great and Near-Great of Day|date=March 5, 1939|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=July 21, 2018|page=11|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com}}</ref> In 1829, the company also built the first hotel on the island: the Coney Island House, near present day Sea Gate.<ref name=\"Phalen2016\">{{cite book|last=Phalen|first=William|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Coney_Island.html?id=2HCQDAAAQBAJ|title=Coney Island : 150 years of rides, fires, floods, the rich, the poor and finally Robert Moses|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers | location=Jefferson, North Carolina|year=2016|isbn=978-0-7864-9816-1|oclc=933438460}}</ref>{{rp|8}}<ref name=\"PBS\">{{cite web|title=American Experience. Coney Island. People & Events|website=PBS|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/coney/peopleevents/pande07.html|access-date=November 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=BDE-YellowedPages-1939 />\n\nDue to Coney Island's proximity to [[Manhattan]] and other boroughs, and its simultaneous relative distance from the city of Brooklyn to provide the illusion of a proper vacation, it began attracting vacationers in the 1830s and 1840s, assisted by carriage roads and steamship service that reduced travel time from a formerly half-day journey to two hours.<ref name=\"Berman York 2003 p. 15\">{{cite book|last=Berman|first=J.S.|last2=Museum of the City of New York|title=Coney Island|publisher=Barnes and Noble Books|series=Portraits of America|year=2003|isbn=978-0-7607-3887-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a_paj4cavDwC&pg=PA15|access-date=November 13, 2015}}</ref>{{rp|15}} Most of the vacationers were wealthy and went by carriage. Inventor [[Samuel Colt]] built an observation tower on the peninsula in 1845, but he abandoned the project soon after.<ref name=\"PBS\" /> In 1847, the middle class started going to Coney Island upon the introduction of a ferry line to Norton's Point\u2014named after hotel owner [[Michael Norton (New York state senator)|Michael Norton]]\u2014at the western portion of the peninsula. Gang activity started as well, with one 1870s writer noting that going to Coney Island could result in losing money and even lives.<ref name=\"PBS\" /> The [[Brooklyn, Bath and Coney Island Railroad]] became the first railroad to reach Coney Island when it opened in 1864,<ref>*{{cite news|work=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|location=[[Brooklyn]], NY|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/50404324|title=Travel|date=June 9, 1864|page=1}}\n* {{cite news|work=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|location=[[Brooklyn]], NY|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/50404348|title=Another New Rail Road|date=June 9, 1864|page=2}}</ref><ref name=\"Our Brooklyn 1936\" /> and it was completed in 1867.<ref name=\"Cudahy 2009\" />{{rp|71}} Over the next 13 years, four more railroads to be built specifically to transport visitors to Coney Island.<ref name=\"Cross Walton 2005\" />{{rp|14}}\n\nIn 1868, [[William A. Engeman]] built a resort in the area.<ref name=\"Coney Island Hotels\" /> The resort was given the name \"[[Brighton Beach]]\" in 1878 by [[Henry C. Murphy]] and a group of businessmen, who chose to name as an allusion to the English resort city of [[Brighton]].<ref name=\"Citycyclopedia\">{{cite book|author=Weinstein, Stephen|editor1=Jackson, Kenneth T.|editor2=Keller, Lisa|editor3=Flood, Nancy |editor-link= Kenneth T. Jackson|edition=2nd|date=2000|chapter=Brighton Beach|title=The Encyclopedia of New York City|isbn=0-300-11465-6|location=New York, NY, and New Haven, CT, USA|publisher=The New York Historical Society and Yale University Press|pages=139\u2013140|url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0300182570 |access-date=November 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Our Brooklyn 1936\">{{cite web|title=Brighton Beach History|website=Our Brooklyn|publisher=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]|date=August 30, 1936|url=http://www.bklynlibrary.org/ourbrooklyn/brightonbeach/|access-date=July 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117015009/http://www.bklynlibrary.org/ourbrooklyn/brightonbeach/|archive-date=November 17, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> With the help of Gravesend's surveyor [[William Stillwell]], Engeman acquired all 39 lots for the relatively low cost of $20,000.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Real Brighton Beach|website=The New Yorker|date=March 29, 2010|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/03/29/the-real-brighton-beach|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Phalen2016 />{{rp|38}} This {{convert|460|by|210|ft|m|adj=on}} hotel, with rooms for up to 5,000 people nightly and meals for up to 20,000 people daily, was close to the then-rundown western Coney Island, so it was mostly the upper middle class that went to this hotel.<ref name=\"Williams\">{{cite journal|last=Williams|first=Keith|title=Brighton Beach: Old World mentality, New World reality|url=http://theweeklynabe.wordpress.com/2012/07/29/brighton-beach-brooklyn-history/|journal=The Weekly Nabe|access-date=July 29, 2012}}</ref> The {{convert|400|ft|m|adj=on}}, double-decker Brighton Beach Bathing Pavilion was also built nearby and opened in 1878, with the capacity for 1,200 bathers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Engeman's New Bathing Hotel|date=July 1, 1878|page=1|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com|url=http://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/50423388/|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Phalen2016 />{{rp|38}}<ref name=\"Our Brooklyn 1936\" /> \"Hotel Brighton\", also known as the \"Brighton Beach Hotel\", was situated on the beach at what is now the foot of [[Coney Island Avenue]].<ref name=\"Coney Island Hotels\">{{cite web|last=Stanton|first=Jeffrey|date=1997|title=Coney Island&nbsp;\u2014 Luxury Hotels|publisher=Coney Island History Site|url=http://www.westland.net/coneyisland/articles/luxuryhotels.htm|access-date=November 12, 2015}}</ref> The [[Brooklyn, Flatbush, and Coney Island Railway]], the predecessor to the [[New York City Subway]]'s present-day [[BMT Brighton Line|Brighton Line]], opened on July 2, 1878, and provided access to the hotel.<ref name=\"NYCS 2001\">{{cite web|last=Feinman|first=Mark S.|title=Early Rapid Transit in Brooklyn, 1878\u20131913|publisher=nycsubway.org|date=February 17, 2001|url=http://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/Early_Rapid_Transit_in_Brooklyn,_1878-1913|access-date=November 12, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Phalen2016 />{{rp|38}}<ref name=\"NYTImes-AnotherRR-Jul1878\">{{cite web|title=ANOTHER CONEY ISLAND RAILROAD.; OPENING OF THE BROOKLYN AND FLATBUSH LINE TO BRIGHTON BEACH.|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 2, 1878|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1878/07/02/archives/another-coney-island-railroad-opening-of-the-brooklyn-and-flatbush.html|access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSimultaneously, wealthy banker [[August Corbin]] was developing adjacent [[Manhattan Beach, Brooklyn|Manhattan Beach]] after being interested in the area during a trip to the beach to heal his sick son.<ref name=\"Coney Island Hotels\" /><ref name=\"Features 2013\">{{cite web|title=The Upper-Class Brooklyn Resorts of the Victorian Era|website=Curbed NY|date=June 27, 2013|url=http://ny.curbed.com/archives/2013/06/27/the_upperclass_brooklyn_resorts_of_the_victorian_era.php|access-date=November 12, 2015}}</ref> Corbin, who worked on [[Wall Street]] and had many [[railroad]] investments, built the [[New York and Manhattan Beach Railway]] for his two luxury shoreline hotels. These hotels were used by the wealthy upper class, who would not go to Brighton Beach because of its proximity to Coney Island.<ref name=\"Coney Island Hotels\" /> The 150-room Manhattan Beach Hotel\u2014which was designed by [[J. Pickering Putnam]] and contained restaurants, ballrooms, and shops\u2014was opened for business in July 1877 at a ceremony presided over by President [[Ulysses S. Grant]].<ref name=\"Features 2013\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Wilderness Made Prosperous By One Man's Vision and Daring|date=July 11, 1954|page=7|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/54414817/|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref> The similarly prodigal Oriental Hotel, which hosted rooms for wealthy families staying for extended periods, was opened in August 1880.<ref name=\"Features 2013\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Opening Reception at the Oriental Hotel|date=August 3, 1880|page=3|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/50504406/|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Andrew R. Culver]], president of the [[Prospect Park and Coney Island Railroad]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1906/07/13/archives/obituary-1-no-title.html|title=Obituary 1 -- No Title|date=July 13, 1906|publisher=|via=query.nytimes.com}}</ref> had built a steam railway to West Brighton, the [[Culver Line (surface)|Culver Line]], before Corbin and Engeman had even built their railroads. For 35 cents, one could ride the Prospect Park & Coney Island Railroad to the [[Culver Depot]] terminal at Surf Avenue.<ref name=\"Coney Island Hotels\" /> Across the street from the terminal, the {{convert|300|ft|m|adj=on}} Iron Tower (also known as the Centennial Observartory), bought from the [[1876 Philadelphia Exposition]], provided patrons with a bird's-eye view of the coast. The nearby \"Camera Obscura\" similarly used mirrors and lens to provide a panoramic view of the area.<ref name=\"Coney Island Hotels\" /><ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|22\u201323}} Coney Island became a major resort destination after the Civil War as excursion [[rail transport|railroads]] and the [[Coney Island & Brooklyn Railroad]] [[streetcar line]] reached the area in the 1860s and 1870s, followed by the [[Iron Steamboat Company]] ferry to Manhattan in 1881.<ref name=Phalen2016 />{{rp|29}}<ref name=\"Cudahy 2009\">{{cite book|last=Cudahy|first=B.J.|title=How We Got to Coney Island: The Development of Mass Transportation in Brooklyn and Kings County|publisher=Fordham University Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0-8232-2211-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FtUzg07N0wwC|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>{{rp|64}}\n\n[[File:Dreamland tower 1907.jpg|thumb|right|[[Dreamland (Coney Island, 1904)|Dreamland]] tower and lagoon in 1907]]\n\nThe 150-suite Cable Hotel was built nearby in 1875.<ref name=\"NYCS 2001\" /> Next to it, on a {{convert|12|acre|ha|adj=on}} piece of land leased by James Voorhies, [[maitre d']] Paul Bauer built the western peninsula's largest hotel, which opened in 1876.<ref name=\"Coney Island Hotels\" /> By the turn of the century, Victorian hotels, private bathhouses, and [[vaudeville]] theaters were a common sight on Coney island.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\">{{cite book|author1=Judith N. DeSena|author2=Timothy Shortell|title=The World in Brooklyn: Gentrification, Immigration, and Ethnic Politics in a Global City|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S-YNs4ih1FUC|year=2012|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-0-7391-6670-3|pages=147\u2013176}}</ref>{{rp|147}} The three resort areas\u2014Brighton Beach, Manhattan Beach and West Brighton\u2014competed with each other for clientele. By the early 1900s, West Brighton had gradually become the most popular destination, and as such, became associated with the lively amusement area of Coney Island.<ref name=\"heartofconeyisland\">{{cite web|access-date=November 19, 2016|publisher=heartofconeyisland.com|url=http://www.heartofconeyisland.com/west-brighton-coney-island-history.html|title=Coney Island History: How 'West Brighton' became Modern-day Coney Island|author=David A. Sullivan}}</ref><ref name=\"Cross Walton 2005\" />{{rp|14\u201315}}\n\nIn the 1890s, Norton's Point on the western side of Coney Island was developed into [[Sea Gate, Brooklyn|Sea Gate]], a [[gated community|gated]] summer community that catered mainly to the wealthy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/50387044/|title=Sea Gate and Sheepshead|date=August 6, 1899|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=July 21, 2018|page=16|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=QUEST FOR RURAL HOMES; Toilers of Greater New York to Gain by Long Island Rapid Transit. TWENTY MINUTES TO JAMAICA Pretty Suburban Villas Springing Up in Anticipation of the Proposed Atlantic Avenue Tunnel -Grass and Air for All.|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 16, 1897|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1897/05/16/archives/quest-for-rural-homes-toilers-of-greater-new-york-to-gain-by-long.html|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref> A private yacht carried visitors directly from [[the Battery (Manhattan)|the Battery]] at the southern tip of Manhattan Island. Notable tenants within the community included the [[Atlantic Yacht Club]], which built a [[colonial style]] house along the waterfront.<ref>{{cite web|author=J.B.T.|title=SEA GATE.|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=August 14, 1898|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1898/08/14/archives/sea-gate.html|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Amusement park era ===\n\nBetween about 1880 and [[World War II]], Coney Island was the largest amusement area in the United States, attracting several million visitors per year. Its development as an amusement area was concurrent with the erection of urban amusement parks elsewhere in the United States, which changed amusement from a passive to an active concept.<ref name=\"Kasson 2011\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pRC1mjAzFXsC|title=Amusing the Million: Coney Island at the Turn of the Century|last=Kasson|first=J.F.|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|year=2011|isbn=978-1-4299-5223-1}}</ref>{{Rp|7, 8}} Of these amusement areas, Coney Island was the largest. At its height, it contained three competing major amusement parks\u2014[[Luna Park (Coney Island, 1903)|Luna Park]], [[Dreamland (Coney Island, 1904)|Dreamland]], and [[Steeplechase Park]]\u2014as well as many independent amusements.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|147\u2013150}}<ref name=\"Parascandola 2014\" />{{rp|11}}<ref name=\"Kasson 2011\" />{{Rp|4}} The area was also the center of new technological events, with electric lights, roller coasters, and [[baby incubator]]s among the innovations at Coney Island in the 1900s.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|147}} By the first decade of the 20th century, Coney Island was seen as a top getaway and \"a symbol of Americans' increasing pride\".<ref name=\"Parascandola 2014\" />{{rp|21\u201322}}\n\n==== 19th century ====\n[[File:The first carousel and amusement ride at Coney Island was hand-carved and built by Danish carver, Charles I. D. Looff and installed at Mrs. Lucy Vanderveer's Bathing Pavilion in 1876.jpg|thumb|left|First Coney Island Charles Looff carousel]]\n\nBy the late 1870s, Coney Island's hotels had drawn people from many different social classes, and attractions were being built.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|30}} When the [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit]] Company electrified the steam railroads and connected Brooklyn to [[Manhattan]] via the [[Brooklyn Bridge]] at the beginning of the 20th century, Coney Island turned rapidly from a resort to an accessible location for day-trippers seeking to escape the summer heat in New York City's [[apartment building|tenements]].<ref name=\"NYCS 2001\" /><ref name=\"Matus, Paul\">{{cite web|author=Matus, Paul|work=The Third Rail Online|title=The New BMT Coney Island Terminal|url=http://thethirdrail.net/0305/stillwell4.html|access-date=August 29, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926235717/http://thethirdrail.net/0305/stillwell4.html|archivedate=September 26, 2007}}</ref> [[Charles I. D. Looff]], a [[Denmark|Danish]] [[wood carving|woodcarver]], built the first carousel and amusement ride at Coney Island in 1876, at Lucy Vandeveer's bath-house complex at West 6th Street and Surf Avenue. Looff personally hand-carved the designs into the carousel.<ref name=\"Westland Network 1997\">{{cite web|title=Coney \u2013 Carousel List|website=Westland Network|date=August 27, 1997|url=http://www.westland.net/coneyisland/articles/carousellist.htm|access-date=November 13, 2015}}</ref> Looff subsequently commissioned another carousel at Feltman's Ocean Pavilion in 1880.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|88}} Another early attraction was the Seaside Aquarium, which operated from 1877 to 1887 and included aquatic exhibits, aviaries, zoo attractions, and various sideshows.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|31}}<ref name=\"Cross Walton 2005\">{{cite book | last=Cross | first=G. | last2=Walton | first2=J.K. | title=The Playful Crowd: Pleasure Places in the Twentieth Century | publisher=Columbia University Press | year=2005 | isbn=978-0-231-50283-2 | url=https://archive.org/details/playfulcrowdplea0000cros | url-access=registration | page=[https://archive.org/details/playfulcrowdplea0000cros/page/15 15] | access-date=October 21, 2019 }}</ref>{{rp|15}} The earliest rides, including Looff's first carousel and the Seaside Aquarium, were located at the Centennial Observatory's site.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|32}} The first sideshows and fireworks displays came to Coney Island in 1883, and combined with constant musical performances, brought increased excitement to the area.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|34\u201337}}\n\nThe very first [[roller coaster]] at Coney Island was the [[Switchback Railway]], a gravity coaster installed by [[LaMarcus Adna Thompson]] at West 10th Street in 1884. Nearby was the [[Elephantine Colossus]], a seven-story building (including a [[brothel]]) in the shape of an elephant, which opened the following year.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|38\u201339}} Until its demolition in 1896, the elephant was the first sight to greet immigrants arriving in New York, who would see it before they saw the [[Statue of Liberty]].<ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|40\u201342}}<ref name=\"heartofconeyislandelephant\">{{cite web|access-date=November 19, 2016|work=www.heartofconeyisland.com|url=http://www.heartofconeyisland.com/elephant-hotel-coney-island-history.html|title=Coney Island History: The Elephant Hotel and Roller Coaster (1885\u20131896)|author=David A. Sullivan}}</ref> Next to be developed were horse-racing tracks, and by 1890, Coney Island had three tracks: [[Sheepshead Bay Race Track]], [[Brighton Beach Race Course]], and [[Gravesend Race Track]].<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|46}} However, crime and corruption in Coney Island were prevalent. The main leader of this corruption was John Y. McKane, who ran prizefighting rings behind the elephant until he was arrested and sentenced in 1894.<ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|48\u201351}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://brooklyneagle.com/articles/2012/03/01/on-this-day-in-history-march-1-brooklyns-answer-to-boss-tweed/|title=On This Day in History, March 1: Brooklyn's Answer to Boss Tweed|date=February 1, 2012|website=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=July 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe development of amusement rides in Coney Island intensified in the 1890s with the opening of amusement parks. The first such park was the [[Sea Lion Park]], which opened in 1895 and continued operating until 1902, and was the first amusement park to charge entry fees. The Sea Lion Park's opening spurred the construction of George C. Tilyou's [[Steeplechase Park]], which opened in 1897.<ref name=\"Parascandola 2014\" />{{rp|12}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Remembering Parks Past|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 7, 1989|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/07/07/arts/remembering-parks-past.html|access-date=January 20, 2019}}</ref> The Coney Island \"Funny Face\" logo, which is still extant, dates to the early days of Steeplechase Park.<ref>{{cite web | title=\"The Face of Steeplechase\" at the Coney Island History Project | website=Brooklyn Paper | date=May 30, 2014 | url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/37/22/24-steeplechase-face-2014-05-30-bk_37_22.html | access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:1879 Coney Island.jpg|thumb|center|800px|Map of Coney Island in 1879]]\n\n==== 20th century ====\n[[File:Night in Luna Park, Coney Island (1905).jpg|thumb|Luna Park, seen 1905]]\n[[File:Potthast-coney-island.jpg|thumb|''Coney Island'', c. 1914, by [[Edward Henry Potthast]]]]\n\nThe first decade of the 20th century saw two more large amusement parks. Luna Park opened in 1903 on the site of the old Sea Lion Park, which had closed the previous year.<ref>{{cite web | title=LUNA PARK FIRST NIGHT; Coney Island Visitors Dazzled by Electric City. Many Colored Illuminations and Canals -- A Midway of Nations and a Trip to the Moon Replace the Old-Time Recreations. | website=The New York Times | date=May 17, 1903 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1903/05/17/archives/luna-park-first-night-coney-island-visitors-dazzled-by-electric.html | access-date=October 21, 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|60\u201361}} The park's flagship was [[A Trip to the Moon (attraction)|A Trip to the Moon]], an attraction based off [[Jules Verne]]'s novel ''[[From the Earth to the Moon]]'', which had previously been located at Steeplechase Park.<ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|62}} The following year saw the opening of Dreamland, which reproduced many attractions at Luna Park, but at a grander scale, with a large central tower and one million electric lights.<ref>{{cite web | title=NEW CONEY DAZZLES ITS RECORD MULTITUDE; Luna Park and Dreamland the Centres of Great Crush. 250,000 PERSONS AT ISLAND Novel and Costly Shows, with the Frankfurter and Peanut as Reminders of By-Gone Days. | website=The New York Times | date=May 15, 1904 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1904/05/15/archives/new-coney-dazzles-its-record-multitude-luna-park-and-dreamland-the.html | access-date=October 21, 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|68\u201369}} Additionally, the City of New York made efforts to condemn all buildings and piers built south of Surf Avenue in an effort to reclaim the beach and create a boardwalk, though the local amusement community opposed the move.<ref>{{cite web|title=CONEY ISLAND BOARDWALK.; Much Opposition to the Bill for a Public Recreation Ground.|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=February 27, 1901|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1901/02/27/archives/coney-island-boardwalk-much-opposition-to-the-bill-for-a-public.html|access-date=May 16, 2018}}</ref> Eventually a settlement was reached where the beach did not begin until {{convert|1000|ft|m}} south of Surf Avenue, the territory marked by a city-owned boardwalk, while the city would demolish any structures that had been built over public streets, to reclaim beach access.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coney Island Realty Settlement.|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 24, 1904|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1904/07/24/archives/coney-island-realty-settlement.html|access-date=January 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1915, the [[BMT Sea Beach Line|Sea Beach Line]] was upgraded to a [[rapid transit|subway]] line, followed by the other former excursion roads, and the opening of the [[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue (New York City Subway)|Stillwell Avenue]] station in 1919 ushered in Coney Island's busiest era.<ref name=\"NYCS 2001\" /><ref name=\"Matus, Paul\" /> On the busiest summer days, over a million people would travel to Coney Island. This created tensions between longtime New York City residents and more recent immigrants who liked to patronize Coney Island.<ref name=\"Parascandola 2014\" />{{rp|23}} One of the entrepreneurs who took advantage of the increased visitor counts was [[Nathan Handwerker]], who in 1916 started selling hot dogs at Coney Island for a nickel each, and eventually expanded his enterprise into the [[Nathan's Famous]] hot dog chain.<ref name=BuffaloNews-LostGlamour-1957 /><ref name=\"Parascandola 2014\" />{{rp|22\u201323}}\n\nConey Island's development as an amusement area continued through the end of World War II. The opening of the [[Wonder Wheel]] in 1920; the [[Riegelmann Boardwalk]] in 1923; the [[Shore Theater]] in 1925; several roller coasters in the 1920s including the [[Tornado (Coney Island)|Tornado]], [[Thunderbolt (1925 roller coaster)|Thunderbolt]], and [[Coney Island Cyclone]]; and the [[Parachute Jump]] in 1941 contributed to the area's quality as an amusement destination. In particular, the Riegelmann Boardwalk enabled the crowds to be dispersed away from Surf Avenue, the main west-east avenue in the area.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|147}}<ref name=\"Parascandola 2014\">{{cite book|last=Parascandola|first=L.J.|title=A Coney Island Reader: Through Dizzy Gates of Illusion|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2014|isbn=978-0-231-53819-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NDMzBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA24|access-date=January 20, 2019|page=24}}</ref>{{rp|23\u201324}} Despite staff shortages during World War II, Coney Island retained its popularity and was frequented by [[military personnel]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1943/06/27/archives/coney-has-a-war-boom-there-are-priorities-shortages-and-the-dimout.html|title=CONEY HAS A WAR BOOM; There Are Priorities, Shortages and the Dimout, but the Subway Is Convenient|last=Lindheim|first=Burton|date=June 27, 1943|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 18, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the era was also marked by frequent fires, and those at the beginning of the 20th century were particularly destructive.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/07/14/archives/early-coney-fires-razed-large-areas-dreamland-was-burned-in-1911.html|title=EARLY CONEY FIRES RAZED LARGE AREAS Dreamland Was Burned in 1911 With Damage Estimated at More Than $5,000,000.; STEEPLECHASE FIRE IN 1907 Loss Kept Down to $1,500,000 When Wind Shifted -- In 1908 Flames Destroyed Two Hotels.|date=July 14, 1932|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 12, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Elmira Star-Gazette\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33793308/|title=$3,000,000 Fire Sweeps Over Coney Island|date=July 14, 1932|work=Elmira Star-Gazette|access-date=July 12, 2019|page=1|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> A 1907 fire at Steeplechase Park<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1907/07/29/archives/coney-swept-by-1500000-fire-steeplechase-park-and-blocks-of-flimsy.html|title=CONEY SWEPT BY $1,500,000 FIRE; Steeplechase Park and Blocks of Flimsy Bowery Buildings in Ruins. STARTS IN CAVE OF WINDS Eats Over 35 Acres of Wooden Structures; Checked at Stauch's Brick Hotel. ONE MAY DIE; DOZEN HURT Many Uninsured Business Men Ruined -- Tilyou,Chief Loser, Takes It Bravely -- Coney's Gayety Is Unchecked. CONEY SWEPT BY $1,500,000 FIRE|date=July 29, 1907|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=|title=Investigating Fire at Coney; No More Tinsel Buildings|date=July 29, 1907|work=Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=|pages=[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33760417/ 1], [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33760426/ 10]|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref>  resulted in the park having to be completely rebuilt.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1909/05/16/archives/the-lambs-gambol-brooklyn-amusements-greater-dreamland-opening.html|title=The Lambs' Gambol.; Brooklyn Amusements. Greater Dreamland, Opening Steeplechase Park.|date=May 16, 1909|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Dreamland burned down in 1911<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1911/06/04/archives/rang-two-nines-for-dreamland-fire-first-time-the-call-ever-was.html|title=RANG 'TWO NINES' FOR DREAMLAND FIRE; First Time the Call Ever Was Sounded for a Fire in Brooklyn Borough. WHAT THE SIGNAL MEANS Called Out 33 Companies and 250 Men -- Longest Run Was More Than Nine Miles -- Great Race to the Sea.|date=June 4, 1911|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 12, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and was never rebuilt.<ref name=\":13\" /> One of the largest conflagrations at Coney Island, which occurred in 1932,<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\"Elmira Star-Gazette\" /> left at least a thousand people homeless.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/07/14/archives/1000-are-made-homeless-one-of-resorts-worst-fires-razes-section-of.html|title=1,000 ARE MADE HOMELESS; One of Resort's Worst Fires Razes Section of Boardwalk. BLAZE STARTS IN RUBBISH Burns District Between 21st and 24th Streets -- Shift in 40-Mile Wind Saves Large Area. FLAMES VISIBLE FOR MILES 500 Receive First-Aid -- Police Rush Help to the Destitute -- Manhattan Sends Apparatus. $5,000,000 FIRE SWEEPS CONEY|date=July 14, 1932|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 12, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe 20th century also saw the filling-in of a portion of the {{convert|3|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[Coney Island Creek]], thereby connecting Coney Island to the rest of Brooklyn. In the previous decades, there had been plans to dredge and straighten the creek as a [[ship canal]], which were later abandoned. By 1924, local land owners and the city had filled a portion of the creek.<ref name=NYC.gov-ResilientNY-Ch17 />{{rp|337}}<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://hiddenwatersblog.wordpress.com/2016/03/04/photo-of-the-week-9/|title=Photo of the Week|date=March 4, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> A major section of the creek was further filled in to allow construction of the [[Belt Parkway]] in the 1930s, and the western and eastern ends of the island became peninsulas. More fill was added in 1962 during the construction of the [[Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/06/nyregion/thecity/06grav.html/partner/rssnyt|title=The Ghost Ships of Coney Island Creek|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 6, 2006|access-date=June 11, 2014|author=JONAH OWEN LAMB}}</ref>\n\n=== Residential development and decline ===\n==== Robert Moses era ====\n[[File:Coney Island (ca. 1940s).ogv|thumb|thumbtime=44|alt=Coney Island, circa 1940|Coney Island, circa 1940]]\n[[File:Brooklyn Museum - Coney Island Bathers - Irving Underhill.jpg|thumb|Bathers in Coney Island by Irving Underhill, in the [[Brooklyn Museum]] collection]]\n\nIn 1937, New York City parks commissioner [[Robert Moses]] published a report about the possible redevelopment of Coney Island, which would have entailed the addition of parking lots and reconstruction of part of the boardwalk.<ref name=\"Beaches-Improvement-1937\">{{cite book|title=Improvement of Coney Island, Rockaway and South Beaches|last=Moses|first=Robert|via=Internet Archive|date=1937|url=https://archive.org/stream/improvementofcon00newy/improvementofcon00newy_djvu.txt|access-date=July 26, 2018}}</ref> The city purchased a {{convert|400|ft|m|-wide|adj=mid}} strip of land along the shoreline, which would allow the boardwalk to be moved {{convert|300|ft|m}} inland.<ref name=\"NYTimes-RevisedPlan-1939\">{{cite web|title=Mayor Ready to Remodel Coney, Asks Moses for Revised Plan; Indicates He Favors Reconstruction of Resort on Broader Scale Than 1937 Proposal-- Says Demand for Recreation Has Changed Mayor for Broad Plan Mayor's Letter to Moses Held Up by Lack of Funds|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=June 25, 1939|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1939/06/25/archives/mayor-ready-to-remodel-coney-asks-moses-for-revised-plan-indicates.html|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref> At this point, Coney Island was so crowded on summer weekends that Moses observed that a coffin would provide more space per person.<ref name=\"BuffaloNews-LostGlamour-1957\">{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Evening%2520News%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Evening%2520News%25201957%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Evening%2520News%25201957%2520-%25203502.pdf|title=Coney Isle Fishing For Way to Regain Its Lost Glamour|first=Edith Kermit|last=Roosevelt|work=Buffalo Evening News|date=June 1, 1957|access-date=July 26, 2018|via=fultonhistory.com}}</ref> Though ride construction was delayed due to material shortages caused by the onset of [[World War II]], two new rides were constructed in 1946 at the end of the war.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/05/05/archives/face-lifted-coney-awaits-old-gang-amusement-owners-put-paint-on-the.html|title=FACE LIFTED, CONEY AWAITS OLD GANG; Amusement Owners Put Paint on the Rides and Trot Out a Few New Super-Thrillers|date=May 5, 1946|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1944, [[Luna Park (Coney Island, 1903)|Luna Park]] was severely damaged by a fire.<ref>{{cite web|title=HALF OF LUNA PARK DESTROYED BY FIRE AS 750,000 WATCH; Flames Sweep Over 8-Acre Area and Cause $500,000 Loss in 1 1/2-Hour Battle|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=August 13, 1944|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1944/08/13/archives/half-of-luna-park-destroyed-by-fire-as-750000-watch-flames-sweep.html|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> Two years later, it was closed permanently and sold to a company who wanted to tear down the park's remnants and build [[Quonset hut]]s for military veterans and their families.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coney's OId Luna Park Will Yield To New Homes for 625 GI Families; LUNA PARK TO BOW TO HOMES FOR GI'S|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=August 18, 1946|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/08/18/archives/coneys-oid-luna-park-will-yield-to-new-homes-for-625-gi-families.html|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> Moses asked the city to transfer Luna Park's land along the Coney Island waterfront to the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation|Parks Department]], a request that was granted in 1949.<ref>{{cite web|title=NEW PARKING LOTS PLANNED BY MOSES; 25-Cent Fee Would Be Charged for Facilities at Coney Island and Rockaway Beach|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=August 18, 1949|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1949/08/18/archives/new-parking-lots-planned-by-moses-25cent-fee-would-be-charged-for.html|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> Moses then had the land rezoned for residential use, with plans to demolish \"about a third\" of attractions along Surf Avenue, one block north of the beach, and replace these with housing.<ref name=NYTimes-ConeyGimmicks-1949 /> Moses moved the boardwalk back from the beach several yards, demolishing many structures, including the city's municipal bath house, as well as several blocks of amusements.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|149}} He claimed that fewer amusement-seekers were going to Coney Island every year, because they preferred places where they could bathe outdoors, such as [[Jones Beach State Park]] on Long Island, rather than the \"mechanical gadget\" attractions of Coney Island.<ref name=\"NYTimes-ConeyGimmicks-1949\">{{cite web|title=PUBLIC SEEN TIRING OF CONEY GIMMICKS; Moses Says People Are Turning to Places Like Jones Beach as Against 'Gadget' Resorts LONG BEACH 'A WARNING' Commissioner Advises Jersey Group Not to Commercialize Sandy Hook Project|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=October 6, 1949|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1949/10/06/archives/public-seen-tiring-of-coney-gimmicks-moses-says-people-are-turning.html|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> Moses also announced that the Steeplechase Pier would be closed for a year so it could be renovated.<ref>{{cite web|title=STEEPLECHASE PIER PLAN; Closing in Summer Slated for $190,000 Rebuilding|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=April 7, 1949|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1949/04/07/archives/steeplechase-pier-plan-closing-in-summer-slated-for-190000.html|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, Moses proposed that most of the peninsula be rezoned for various uses, claiming that it would be an \"upgrade\" over the various business and unrestricted zones that existed at the time. Steeplechase Park would be allowed to remain open, but much of the shorefront amusements and concessions would be replaced by residential developments.<ref>{{cite web|title=Moses Asks Coney Island Rezoning To 'Upgrade' It as Residential Area; REZONING SOUGHT FOR CONEY ISLAND|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=April 2, 1953|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1953/04/02/archives/moses-asks-coney-island-rezoning-to-upgrade-it-as-residential-area.html|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref><ref name=BDE-Greatest-Aquarium-1954 /> After many complaints from the public and from concession operators, the Estimate Board reinstated the area between West 22nd and West Eighth Streets as an amusement-only zone, with the zone extending {{convert|200|to|400|ft|m}} inland from the shoreline.<ref>{{cite web|title=AMUSEMENT AREA IN CONEY EXEMPT; Estimate Board Votes Exclusion From Rezoning of a Section North of the Boardwalk|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=June 12, 1953|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1953/06/12/archives/amusement-area-in-coney-exempt-estimate-board-votes-exclusion-from.html|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=That Hot Dog Flavor To Remain at Coney|first=Clarence|last=Greenbaum|page=1|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com|date=June 12, 1953|url=http://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53706179/|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref> Moses's subsequent proposal to extend the Coney Island boardwalk east to Manhattan Beach was denied in 1955.<ref>{{cite web|title=CONEY EXTENSION DENIED TO MOSES; Estimate Board Rejects His Plan to Join Boardwalk With Manhattan Beach RESIDENTS PROTEST IT Their Willingness to Pay for Restoring Own Esplanade Spurs Unanimous Vote|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=September 23, 1955|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/09/23/archives/coney-extension-denied-to-moses-estimate-board-rejects-his-plan-to.html|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref> A proposal to make the Quonset hut development into a permanent housing structure was also rejected.<ref>{{cite web|title=PLANNERS OPPOSE HOUSING AT BEACH; Reject Proposal for Municipal Operation of Ex-G. I. Units -- Ask Quick Shift to Park WEIGH REZONING FOR TV N.B.C. Ties Favorable Vote on Flatbush Studio to Location of Its Color Operations|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 28, 1953|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1953/05/28/archives/planners-oppose-housing-at-beach-reject-proposal-for-municipal.html|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA new building for the [[New York Aquarium]] was approved for construction in the neighborhood in 1953.<ref name=\"Caro 1974\">{{Cite Power Broker}}</ref>{{rp|687}}<ref>{{cite web|title=PLAN OF AQUARIUM AT CONEY APPROVED; Estimate Board Appropriates $450,000 for First Stage -- Work Starts in Spring|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=October 23, 1953|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1953/10/23/archives/plan-of-aquarium-at-coney-approved-estimate-board-appropriates.html|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref> Construction started on the aquarium in 1954.<ref name=\"BDE-Greatest-Aquarium-1954\">{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/54529888/|title=Break Ground for World's Greatest Aquarium at Coney Island|first=Al|last=Salerno|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|date=October 24, 1954|pages=1, 21|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com}}</ref> The development of the new New York Aquarium was expected to revitalize Coney Island.<ref name=Billboard-19550129 /><ref name=BDE-Greatest-Aquarium-1954 /> By 1955, the area still included four children's amusement areas, five roller coasters, several [[flat ride|flat]] and [[dark ride]]s, and various other attractions such as the Wonder Wheel.<ref name=\"Billboard-19550129\">{{cite book|title=Coney Girds for '55; Aquarium Progressing|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UxkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA63|language=en|date=January 29, 1955|access-date=July 22, 2018|page=63}}</ref> The New York Aquarium's new site opened in June 1957.<ref name=\"NYParks-Aquarium-History\">{{cite web|title=History of the New York Aquarium : NYC Parks|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|date=May 31, 1934|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/about/history/zoos/ny-aquarium|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> At this point, there were still several dozen rides on Coney Island.<ref name=BuffaloNews-LostGlamour-1957 />\n\n==== Fred Trump era ====\nDuring the summers of 1964 and 1965, there was a large decrease in the number of visitors to Coney Island because of the [[1964 New York World's Fair|1964/1965 World's Fair]] at [[Flushing Meadows\u2013Corona Park]] in Queens.<ref name=\"Phillips 1966\" /> Crime increases, insufficient parking facilities, bad weather, and the post-World War II automotive boom were also cited as contributing factors in the visitor decrease. During the summer of 1964, concessionaires saw their lowest profits in a quarter-century. Ride operators reported that they had 30% to 90% fewer visitors in 1964 compared to the previous year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coney Island Slump Grows Worse; Decline in Business Since the War Years Has Been Steady|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 2, 1964|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/07/02/archives/coney-island-slump-grows-worse-decline-in-business-since-the-war.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1964, Coney Island's last remaining large amusement park, [[Steeplechase Park]], was closed and demolished.<ref name=\"NYT2005\">{{cite web | last=Chan | first=Sewell | title=Leaps of Imagination for the Parachute Jump | website=The New York Times | date=July 21, 2005 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/21/arts/design/leaps-of-imagination-for-the-parachute-jump.html | access-date=July 6, 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|172}} The surrounding blocks were filled with amusement rides and concessions that were closed or about to close.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|172}} The rides at Steeplechase Park were auctioned off, and the property was sold to developer [[Fred Trump]], who in 1965 announced that he wanted to build luxury apartments on the old Steeplechase property.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steeplechase Park Planned as the Site Of Housing Project|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 1, 1965|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/07/01/archives/steeplechase-park-planned-as-the-site-of-housing-project.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> At the time, residential developments on Coney Island in general were being built at a rapid rate. The peninsula, which had 34,000 residents in 1961, was expected to have more than double that number by the end of 1964. Many of the new residents moved into middle-income [[co-operative housing]] developments such as [[Trump Village]], [[Warbasse Houses]], and [[Luna Park Apartments]]; these replaced what ''The New York Times'' described as \"a rundown sprawl of rickety houses\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Kaufman|first=Michael T.|title=Housing and Amusements Give Coney Island a Dual Place in the Sun|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=March 19, 1964|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/03/19/housing-and-amusements-give-coney-island-a-dual-place-in-the-sun.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> Developers were spending millions of dollars on new housing developments, and by 1966, the peninsula housed almost 100,000 people.<ref name=\"Phillips 1966\">{{cite web|last=Phillips|first=McCandlish|title=Return of Coney Island; Amusement Area, Badly Hurt Last Year, Is Attempting to Win Back Customers|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=April 13, 1966|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/04/13/archives/return-of-coney-island-amusement-area-badly-hurt-last-year-is.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nTrump destroyed Steeplechase Park's Pavilion of Fun during a highly publicized ceremony in September 1966.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|172}}<ref>{{cite web|title=6 Bikinied Beauties Attend Demolishing Of Coney Landmark|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=September 22, 1966|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/09/22/archives/6-bikinied-beauties-attend-demolishing-of-coney-landmark.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> In its stead, Trump proposed building a {{convert|160|ft|m|adj=mid|-high}} enclosed dome with recreational facilities and a convention center, a plan which was supported by Brooklyn borough president [[Abe Stark]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A 160-Foot-High Pleasure Dome Is Proposed for Coney Island; A DOME PROPOSED FOR CONEY ISLAND|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 24, 1966|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/07/24/archives/a-160foothigh-pleasure-dome-is-proposed-for-coney-island-a-dome.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> That summer, developers tried to revitalize the Coney Island boardwalk as an amusement area.<ref name=\"Phillips 1966\" /> In October 1966, the city announced its plans to acquire the {{convert|125|acre|ha}} of the former Steeplechase Park,<ref>{{cite web|last=Fowle|first=Farnsworth|title=City Wants Site of Steeplechase For Seafront Coney Island Park; Planning Board Sets Oct. 19 Hearing to Bar Area for High-Rise Homes|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=October 5, 1966|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/10/05/archives/city-wants-site-of-steeplechase-for-seafront-coney-island-park.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> a move that many residents supported but that Trump considered to be \"wasteful\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Roberts|first=Steven V.|title=A PARK IS BACKED FOR CONEY ISLAND; Developer Who Bought Site Calls Plan Wasteful|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=October 20, 1966|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/10/20/archives/a-park-is-backed-for-coney-island-developer-who-bought-site-calls.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> In January 1968, New York City parks commissioner [[August Heckscher II]] proposed that the New York state government build an \"open-space\" state park on the Steeplechase site,<ref>{{cite web|last=Clark|first=Alfred E.|title=State Is Urged to Build a Park At Coney Island's Steeplechase|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=January 6, 1968|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1968/01/06/archives/state-is-urged-to-build-a-park-at-coney-islands-steeplechase.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> and that May, the New York City Board of Estimate voted in favor of funding to buy the land from Trump.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|title=PARK USAGE VOTED FOR STEEPLECHASE; City to Seek $2-Million Aid to Buy Coney Island Tract|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 23, 1968|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1968/05/23/archives/park-usage-voted-for-steeplechase-city-to-seek-2million-aid-to-buy.html|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":19\">{{cite news|url=|title=Coney Island stages a comeback|last=Glave|first=Judie|date=September 2, 1990|work=The Journal-News|access-date=|location=White Plains, NY|pages=[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34116222/ 68], [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34116227/ 69], [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34116234/ 70]|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> Condemnation of the site started in 1969.<ref name=\"Fowler 1979\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/06/03/archives/15year-dispute-over-lease-for-coney-island-steeplechase-continues.html|title=15\u2010Year Dispute Over Lease for Coney Island Steeplechase Continues|last=Fowler|first=Glenn|date=June 3, 1979|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref> The city ultimately purchased the proposed park's site for $4 million, with a stipulation blocking Trump from developing the site as apartments.<ref name=\"Carmody 1985\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28804609/|title=A plan to bring back Coney Island|last=Mirabella|first=Alan|date=June 2, 1985|work=New York Daily News|access-date=February 24, 2019|page=311|via=Newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref>\n\nTrump filed a series of court cases related to the proposed residential rezoning, and ultimately won a $1.3 million judgment.<ref name=\"Fowler 1979\" /> The Steeplechase Park site laid empty for several years. Trump started [[lease|subleasing]] the property to [[Norman Kaufman]], who ran a small collection of fairground amusements called \"Steeplechase Park\" on part of the site.<ref name=Immerso2002 />{{rp|172}}<ref name=\"Fowler 1979\" /> The city also leased the boardwalk and parking lot sites at extremely low rates, which resulted in a $1 million loss of revenue over the following seven years. Since the city wanted to build the state park on the site of Kaufman's Steeplechase Park, it attempted to evict him by refusing to grant a lease extension.<ref name=\"Chambers 1977\" />\n\n==== Late-1970s attempts at restoration ====\n[[File:ABANDONED \"GIANT SLIDE\" AT CONEY ISLAND MARKS DECLINE OF AREA'S RECREATIONAL USE - NARA - 547902.jpg|thumb|right|A 1973 photo of an abandoned \"Giant Slide\" that had been set up for a few years on the old Steeplechase site]]\n\nThe 1970s brought along further renewal plans, such as proposals to construct public housing. However, it was beset by social issues such as high crime and a drug epidemic.<ref name=\":19\" /> By 1975, the city was considering demolishing the [[Coney Island Cyclone]] in favor of an extension of the adjacent New York Aquarium.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|153}} The proposed demolition was controversial,<ref>{{cite web|title=Aquarium Urges Razing Of Coney Island Cyclone|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 27, 1975|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/05/27/archives/aquarium-urges-razing-of-coney-island-cyclone.html|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref> and after a refurbishment by [[Astroland]], the Cyclone reopened for the summer 1975 season.<ref>{{cite book|last=Futrell|first=J.|title=Amusement Parks of New York|publisher=Stackpole Books|series=Amusement Parks Series|year=2006|isbn=978-0-8117-3262-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MKOkQoVeGWAC&pg=PA66|access-date=September 15, 2018|page=66}}</ref> The abandoned Parachute Jump was left in situ, and the New York City Board of Estimate planned to tear down the structure.<ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|174}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Parachute Jump at Coney Island Loses Chance of Landmark Status|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=October 21, 1977|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/10/21/archives/parachute-jump-at-coney-island-loses-chance-of-landmark-status.html|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref> In the meanwhile, Coney Island was still affected by a perception of crime and deterioration of old rides, but by the mid-1970s, middle-class families started returning to Coney Island following the implementation of a unified admission ticket to Coney Island's amusement areas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34018580/|title=Coney Island: battered but unbowed, it still amuses|date=April 9, 1976|work=New York Daily News|access-date=July 18, 2019|page=53|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref>\n\nThe city continued to pursue litigation over the site occupied by Norman Kaufman, but for over a decade, was unsuccessful.<ref name=\"Fowler 1979\" /> It had no plan for the proposed state park, and in 1975 the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development]] nearly withdrew a proposed grant of $2 million to fund the proposed park.<ref name=\"Chambers 1977\">{{cite web|last=Chambers|first=Marcia|title=New York, After 10 Years, Finds Plan to Create a Coney Island Park Is Unsuccessful|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=April 3, 1977|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/04/03/archives/new-york-after-10-years-finds-plan-to-create-a-coney-island-park-is.html|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref> The city ultimately accepted the grant, though different city agencies still disagreed over whether to return the funds.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chambers|first=Marcia|title=City, in a Shift, Says Coney I. Park Should Become Amusement Area|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=June 16, 1977|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/06/16/archives/city-in-a-shift-says-coney-i-park-should-become-amusement-area.html|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref> Kaufman continued to operate the site until the end of summer 1980. The following June, the city paid Kaufman a million dollars for the rides, effectively evicting him, even though the amusements were estimated to be worth much less.<ref name=\"NYTimes-TalkofConeyIsland-1981\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 1979, the state announced that it would be conducting a report on the feasibility of legalizing gambling in New York State, Mayor [[Ed Koch]] proposed that the state open casinos in New York City to revitalize the area's economy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lynn|first=Frank|title=Koch Urges City Be Considered As a Site for Gambling Casinos|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=April 6, 1979|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/04/06/archives/koch-urges-city-be-considered-as-a-site-for-gambling-casinos-panel.html|access-date=September 16, 2018}}</ref> Residents and politicians supported the idea of building casinos at Coney Island, which they felt would alleviate its poverty, crime, and property vacancy rates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28712821/|title=Casinos seen as a Coney lifesaver|last=Fitzgerald|first=Owen|date=June 21, 1979|work=New York Daily News|access-date=February 21, 2019|page=652|via=Newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> However, there was substantial controversy over the plans to place a gambling site in Coney Island.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/08/14/archives/opinions-mixed-on-casino-plan-in-coney-island-prospect-of-gambling.html|title=Opinions Mixed On Casino Plan In Coney Island|last=Basler|first=Barbara|date=August 14, 1979|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref> The state's interest in legalizing gambling had subsided by 1981, and the New York state legislature failed to take action on such proposal.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28713218/|title=Effort renewed for rides park|last=Fitzgerald|first=Owen|date=November 17, 1982|work=New York Daily News|access-date=February 21, 2019|page=110|via=Newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes-TalkofConeyIsland-1981\">{{cite web|last=Campbell|first=Colin|title=BELEAGUERED CONEY ISLANDERS RALLY WITH SENSE OF AFFECTION; The Talk of Coney Island|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=August 29, 1981|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/08/29/nyregion/beleaguered-coney-islanders-rally-with-sense-affection-talk-coney-island.html|access-date=September 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn an effort to reduce crime, the city also began demolishing abandoned bungalows on Coney Island.<ref name=\":19\" /> By 1982, the area was filled with vacant lots, though several residential developments were being planned for Coney Island.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/02/25/nyregion/about-new-york-a-ray-of-hope-gleams-in-coney-island.html|title=About New York; a Ray of Hope Gleams in Coney Island|last=Quindlen|first=Anna|date=February 25, 1982|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 22, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Having finally acquired Kaufman's rides, the New York City government began advertising for developers to redevelop the former amusement park area that November.<ref name=\":2\" /> The Mermaid-Neptune Development Corporation constructed three residential developments at the neighborhood's western edge, with a combined total of 430 units. These developments were completed through the mid-1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/06/10/realestate/postings-housing-reprieve.html|title=POSTINGS; HOUSING REPRIEVE|date=June 10, 1984|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=February 22, 2019}}</ref> Even so, the area still suffered from drug-related killings and other crimes, especially west of West 20th Street. Former amusement structures such as the Parachute Jump lay unused, and prostitutes roamed around the neighborhood at night.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/08/20/nyregion/the-talk-of-coney-island-at-coney-i-symbols-of-heyday-fading-away.html|title=The Talk of Coney Island; at Coney I., Symbols of Heyday Fading Away|last=Chira|first=Susan|date=August 20, 1983|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 22, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> Through the 1980s, prostitution and drug use in Coney Island increased, as did the area's murder and felony crime rate.<ref>{{cite web|last=Freedman|first=Samuel G.|title=CONEY I.: SYMBOL OF FUN IS NOW ONE OF DESPAIR|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 29, 1986|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/05/29/nyregion/coney-i-symbol-of-fun-is-now-one-of-despair.html|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US}}</ref> By the late 1980s, deadly shootings were common, particularly in the low-income housing developments inside Coney Island.<ref>{{cite web|last=Williams|first=Winston|title=THE TALK OF CONEY ISLAND; Faded Funland: Fears and Hopes|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 18, 1988|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/07/18/nyregion/the-talk-of-coney-island-faded-funland-fears-and-hopes.html|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref> Commercial activity also decreased, and by 1990, storefronts on Mermaid Avenue had decreased by 90%, from over 400 stores before the urban renewal to 39 stores afterward.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\n=== Revival ===\n==== Bullard deal, Sportsplex, and KeySpan Park ====\n[[File:CI BUG apts fr W12 jeh.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.25|Co-ops on Coney Island]]\nIn the mid-1980s, restaurant mogul [[Horace Bullard]] proposed rebuilding Steeplechase Park.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|150}}<ref name=\":3\" /> On the site bounded by West 15th and 19th Streets between Surf Avenue and the boardwalk, Bullard wanted to build a $55 million amusement park based on the originals. The city agreed, and the project was approved in 1985.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|150}}<ref name=\"Carmody 1985\">{{cite web|last=Carmody|first=Deirdre|title=REBORN STEEPLECHASE PARK PLANNED AT CONEY I.|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=August 5, 1985|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/08/05/nyregion/reborn-steeplechase-park-planned-at-coney-i.html|access-date=September 16, 2018}}</ref> Bullard planned to open the park by mid-1986 to coincide with the [[Statue of Liberty]]'s centennial.<ref name=\"Carmody 1985\" /> However, the project was delayed while the New York City Planning Commission compiled an environmental impact report.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|last=Rangel|first=Jesus|title=CONEY I. OPENING SEASON WITH HOPE|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=March 29, 1986|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/03/29/nyregion/coney-i-opening-season-with-hope.html|access-date=September 16, 2018}}</ref> By early 1987, the cost of the amusement park nearly doubled, to $100 million.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/06/05/nyregion/broad-redevelopment-is-urged-for-coney-island.html|title=Broad Redevelopment Is Urged for Coney Island|last=Rangel|first=Jesus|date=June 5, 1987|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nConcurrently, in December 1986, the New York State Urban Development Corporation formally proposed a 17,000-seat minor-league baseball stadium north of the boardwalk between West 19th and West 22nd Streets as well as 15,000-seat indoor arena north of the Abe Stark Rink. Negotiations were ongoing with the [[New York Mets|Mets]] and [[New York Yankees|Yankees]] to ensure their support for the minor-league stadium.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rangel|first=Jesus|title=STATE PROPOSES BASEBALL STADIUM FOR CONEY I.|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=December 5, 1986|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/12/05/nyregion/state-proposes-baseball-stadium-for-coney-i.html|access-date=September 16, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{cite news|url=|title=The Business of Bringing Baseball Back to Brooklyn|last=Arena|first=Salvatore|date=April 26, 1987|work=New York Daily News|access-date=|pages=[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28807554/ 1], [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28807722/ 8\u20139]|via=Newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> State senator [[Thomas Bartosiewics]] attempted to block Bullard's plan, as he was part of a foundation that had promised another developer, Sportsplex, the right to build an amateur sports arena on the site.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":11\" /> Construction was held up for another four years, and by 1989, Bullard and the city were ready to sign a contract that would allow the developer to construct a 60-ride amusement park on a {{Convert|25|acre|ha|abbr=|adj=on}} waterfront strip, which would be completed by 2002.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/08/09/business/real-estate-coney-island-development-deal-gaining.html|title=Real Estate; Coney Island Development Deal Gaining|last=Kennedy|first=Shawn G.|date=August 9, 1989|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Other proposals for the area included a $7.9 million restoration of the boardwalk, as well as a new high-school and college sports stadium.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nSome of Coney Island's iconic rides were designated as official city landmarks during the late 1980s.<ref name=\"BrooklynEagle-CILandmarks-2016\" /> In 1988, the Cyclone roller coaster was made a New York City designated landmark.<ref name=\"NYTimes-Cyclone-1988\">{{cite web|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|title=Coney I. Thriller Becomes Landmark|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=July 13, 1988|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/07/13/nyregion/coney-i-thriller-becomes-landmark.html|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref> This was followed by the Parachute Jump and the Wonder Wheel in 1989.<ref name=\"NYTimes-PJ-1989\">{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2010/02/15/coney-island-parachute-jump-no-climbing-allowed/|title=Coney Island Parachute Jump \u2013 No climbing allowed!|last=Maniscalco|first=Joe|date=February 15, 2010|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BrooklynEagle-CILandmarks-2016\">{{Cite web|url=https://brooklyneagle.com/articles/2016/05/11/coney-island-landmarks-present-and-we-hope-future/|title=Coney Island landmarks, present and (we hope) future|date=May 11, 2016|website=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|language=en-US|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref> The neighborhood's high crime rate had reversed slightly by the 1990s. However, Coney Island's relative isolation from the rest of New York City, along with its ethnic diversity, deprived the area of significant political power, and to a greater extent money.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wolff|first=Craig|title=Coney Island on the Edge; A Region's Venerable Magic Is Buffeted by Modern Times|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 25, 1994|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/05/25/nyregion/coney-island-on-the-edge-a-region-s-venerable-magic-is-buffeted-by-modern-times.html|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Rudy Giuliani]] took office as New York City mayor of New York in 1994, he negated the Bullard deal by approving the construction of a minor-league baseball stadium on the site allotted for Steeplechase Park.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|150}} Giuliani had wanted to build Sportsplex in order to improve sports facilities in the area, and to create a professional baseball team in Brooklyn.<ref>{{cite web|last=Farrell|first=Bill|title=Baseball Pitch Back in Sportsplex Mix Rally for Coney Venue|website=NY Daily News|date=January 21, 1998|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/boroughs/baseball-pitch-back-sportsplex-mix-rally-coney-venue-article-1.788295|access-date=November 13, 2015}}</ref> By the late 1990s, some $67 million had been secured for the development of Sportsplex.<ref name=\":6\" /> In 1997, developer [[Bruce Ratner]] proposed constructing a $100 million entertainment complex between West 9th and West 15th Streets, with a \"virtual-reality amusement park\" as well as a [[Multiplex (movie theater)|movie theater multiplex]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/21/nyregion/with-times-square-reborn-attention-turns-to-coney-island.html|title=With Times Square Reborn, Attention Turns to Coney Island|last=Martin|first=Douglas|date=July 21, 1997|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Concurrently, a four-phase, 873-unit housing development in Coney Island was completed in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rozhon|first=Tracie|title=Coney Island Housing Project Complete|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=November 22, 1996|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/11/22/business/coney-island-housing-project-complete.html|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Giuliani canceled Sportsplex and the entertainment complex, and instead unveiled another plan where only the parking lot would be built. The Sports Foundation had prepared another proposal that would allow a scaled-down Sportsplex to be built next to the minor-league baseball stadium.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite news|last=Martin|first=Douglas|title=Back to the Drawing Board in Coney Island|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=November 23, 1998|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/23/nyregion/back-to-the-drawing-board-in-coney-island.html|access-date=November 13, 2015}}</ref> The minor league team was called the Brooklyn Cyclones, though naming rights to the stadium were sold to [[Keyspan Energy]]. Bullard, now no longer rebuilding Steeplechase Park, had wanted to restore the Thunderbolt as part of a scaled-down amusement park, but it was demolished instead.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|150}} In 2000, the city approved the $31 million project to construct [[MCU Park|Keyspan Park]] using the funds from the canceled Sportsplex,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/12/nyregion/deal-gives-coney-island-a-ballpark-and-a-team-that-some-didn-t-want.html|title=Deal Gives Coney Island a Ballpark, and a Team That Some Didn't Want|last=Barnes|first=Julian E.|date=April 12, 2000|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and the minor-league baseball stadium opened the following year.<ref name=\":15\">{{cite web|last=Vecsey|first=George|title=Sports of The Times; Summer Rite Returns To Borough of Churches|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=June 26, 2001|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/06/26/sports/sports-of-the-times-summer-rite-returns-to-borough-of-churches.html|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref> Other major projects at the time included the reconstruction of Coney Island's sewers and the refurbishment of the Stillwell Avenue subway station,<ref name=\":6\" /> the latter of which was completed in 2005.<ref name=\"Chan\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/28/nyregion/and-now-for-the-good-news-from-the-subway-system.html|title=And Now for the Good News From the Subway System|last=Chan|first=Sewell|date=May 28, 2005|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Thor Equities ownership and rezoning proposals ====\n[[File:Astroland Coney Island by David Shankbone.JPG|thumb|left|The Wonder Wheel and Astroland Park from a Coney Island beach]]\n\nIn 2003, Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] took an interest in revitalizing Coney Island as a possible site for the [[New York City bid for the 2012 Summer Olympics|New York City bid]] of the [[2012 Summer Olympics bids|2012 Summer Olympics]]. A plan was developed by the [[Astella Development Corporation]]. When the city lost the bid for the Olympics, revitalization plans were passed on to the Coney Island Development Corporation (CIDC), which came up with a plan to restore the resort.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nycedc.com/press-release/mayor-bloomberg-announces-strategic-plan-future-coney-island|title=Mayor Bloomberg Announces Strategic Plan For Future of Coney Island|last=|first=|date=September 14, 2005|work=NYCEDC|access-date=July 21, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Shortly before the CIDC's plans were to be publicly released, a development company named [[Thor Equities]] purchased all of Bullard's {{convert|168000|ft2|m2|adj=on}} western property for $13 million, later selling the property to [[Taconic Investment Partners]] for over $90 million.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|158}} Taconic now had {{convert|100|acre|ha}}, on which it planned to build 2,000 apartment units.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|158\u2013159}}<ref name=\"Fung 2009\">{{cite web|last=Fung|first=Amanda|title=Coney Island keeper|website=Crain's New York Business|date=June 28, 2009|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20090628/SMALLBIZ/306289868/coney-island-keeper|access-date=November 14, 2015}}</ref> Thor then went about using much of its $77 million profit to purchase property on Stillwell Avenue for well over market value, and offered to buy out every piece of property inside the traditional amusement area.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|158\u2013159}}\n\nIn September 2005, Thor's founder, [[Joe Sitt]], unveiled his new plans for a large [[Bellagio (resort)|Bellagio]]-style hotel resort with a [[timeshare]] development, surrounded by rides and amusements. The CIDC report suggested adding year-round commercial and amusement area, and recommended that property north of Surf Avenue and west of Abe Stark Rink could be rezoned for other uses, including residential.<ref name=\":0\" /> Sitt, a resident of the area, spent more than $100 million to buy land in Coney Island.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/04/nyregion/04coney.html|title=Down by the Boardwalk, a $1 Billion Revival Plan|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|date=July 4, 2006|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Astroland]] owner Carol Hill Albert, whose husband's family had owned the park since 1962, sold the site to Thor in November 2006. Two months later, Thor released renderings for a $1.5 billion amusement park, entertainment complex, and indoor water park called Coney Island Park.<ref>{{cite web | title=A $1.5 Billion Vision For Coney Island | website=The New York Sun | url=https://www.nysun.com/new-york/15-billion-vision-for-coney-island/43372/ | access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite web | title=Plans Coming Together For Coney Island Amusement Park Expansion | website=ny1.com | date=November 14, 2006 | url=http://www.ny1.com/ny1/content/index.jsp?stid=9&aid=64315 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071008063611/http://www.ny1.com/ny1/content/index.jsp?stid=9&aid=64315 | archive-date=October 8, 2007 | url-status=dead | access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the DCP started circulating a rezoning plan that would cover {{Convert|47|acre|ha|abbr=}} of Coney Island. The city would spend $120 million to redevelop {{Convert|15|acre|ha|abbr=}} into an amusement park surrounded by around 5,000 new housing units.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/home.html|title=New York City Department of City Planning&nbsp;\u2014 Amanda M. Burden, Director|publisher=Nyc.gov|date=|access-date=August 13, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/09/nyregion/09coney.html|title=City Offers Coney Island Plan That Conflicts With a Developer's|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|date=November 9, 2007|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Aquarium was also planning a renovation in conjunction with the rezoning.<ref name=\":7\" /> The city's and Sitt's proposals directly conflicted: Sitt wanted to build housing inside the amusement park, while the city's rezoning would create a special amusement district where residential development was forbidden.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/17/nyregion/17coney.html|title=City and Developer Spar Over Coney Island Visions|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|date=February 16, 2009|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In April 2008, because of objections from land owners, residents, and developers, the city revised its rezoning proposal. Only 9 acres would be used as an amusement park, while private owners and developers could build on the rest of the land as long as they followed the DCP's general master plan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/17/nyregion/17coney.html|title=City's Coney Island Design Revised to Break Deadlock|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|date=April 17, 2008|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> While the city negotiated with Thor, Sitt evicted several amusement operators on his land, including Astroland, in the expectation that he would soon be able to redevelop it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/11/nyregion/11coney.html|title=City and Developer at Odds Over Future of Coney Island|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|date=April 10, 2009|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 26, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>[[File:COneyIsland1506.jpg|thumb|right|Senior housing on Coney Island]]The DCP certified the rezoning plan in January 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/html/luproc/ulpro.shtml|title=Uniform Land Use Review Procedure (ULURP)&nbsp;\u2013 New York City Department of City Planning|publisher=Nyc.gov|access-date=August 13, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120719144905/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/html/luproc/ulpro.shtml|archivedate=July 19, 2012}}</ref> which allowed the city to create a {{Convert|9.4|acre|ha|abbr=|adj=on}} amusement district.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/12/nyregion/12coney.html|title=New York to Buy 7 Acres in Coney Island, Hoping for Revival|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|date=November 11, 2009|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> At the time, Thor Equities said it hoped to complete the project by 2011.<ref>{{cite news | last=Santos | first=Fernanda | title=Coney Island's Astroland Closes, Maybe for Good | work=The New York Times | date=September 10, 2007 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/10/nyregion/10coney.html | access-date=October 20, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In June 2009, the city's planning commission approved the construction of 4,500 units of housing, including 900 affordable units, and promised to preserve affordable housing already in the neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web | last=Edroso | first=Roy | title=New York \u2013 Runnin' Scared \u2013 Planning Commission Approves Unloved Coney Plan | website=blogs.villagevoice.com | date=July 3, 2009 | url=http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/archives/2009/06/planning_commis.php | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090703160349/http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/archives/2009/06/planning_commis.php | archive-date=July 3, 2009 | url-status=dead | access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" /> Subsequently, the city government paid Sitt $95.6 million for {{Convert|7|acre|ha|abbr=}} of land.<ref name=\":10\" /> The nonprofit civic group, [[Municipal Art Society]], wanted the city-operated park to be larger, though the city was reluctant to spend so much money.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n==== Progress on expansion ====\nThe Zipper and Spider on West 12th Street were closed permanently and dismantled in September 2007 after its owner lost his lease.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ride Over for Coney Classics|first=Rich|last=Calder|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/09052007/news/regionalnews/ride_over_for_coney_classics.htm|newspaper=New York Post|date=September 5, 2007|access-date=September 5, 2007}}</ref> The same year, plans to restore Coney Island's historic [[B&B Carousell]] were revealed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/13/nyregion/13carousel.html|title=Plans Afoot to Restore Coney Island Carousel for New Spin on the Boardwalk|last=McGeehan|first=Patrick|date=September 13, 2007|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 24, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> After Astroland closed in 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ireport.com/ir-topic-stories.jspa?topicId=22385|title=Coney Island amusement park closing: News & Videos about Coney Island amusement park closing|publisher=CNN|work=Ireport.com|access-date=March 17, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081230203827/http://www.ireport.com/ir-topic-stories.jspa?topicId=22385|archive-date=December 30, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> it was replaced by a new [[Dreamland (Coney Island, 2009)|Dreamland]] in 2009<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn/dreamland-amusement-park-place-astroland-coney-island-article-1.362110|title=Dreamland amusement park to take place of Astroland at Coney Island|last=Sederstrom|first=Jotham|date=April 8, 2009|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref> and by a new [[Luna Park (Coney Island, 2010)|Luna Park]] in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/33/23/all_coneypreview_2010_06_04_bk.html|title=It's Saturday \u2014 and a new day dawns at Coney Island|last=Donahue|first=Courtney|date=June 4, 2010|website=Brooklyn Paper|language=en|access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/gonna-new-coney-island-baby-19-rides-added-luna-park-article-1.198180|title=It's gonna be a new Coney Island, baby! 19 rides added to Luna Park|last=Durkin|first=Erin|date=February 20, 2010|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref> In April 2011, the first new roller coasters to be built at Coney Island in eighty years were opened as part of efforts to reverse the decline of the amusement area.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-rollercoasters-idUSTRE73K57P20110421|title=Coney Island gets first new roller coasters in 80 years|date=April 21, 2011|work=Reuters|access-date=July 22, 2019|language=en}}</ref> The B&B Carousell reopened in 2013 at Luna Park.<ref name=\"Foderaro 2013\" /> The [[Thunderbolt (2014 roller coaster)|Thunderbolt]] steel roller coaster, named after the original wooden coaster on the site, was opened in June 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn/coney-island-new-thunderbolt-roller-coaster-officially-opens-article-1.1830380|title=Coney Island's new Thunderbolt roller coaster officially opens|date=June 14, 2014|work=NY Daily News|access-date=June 29, 2014|author=Brown, Stephen R.}}</ref> Furthermore, a live performance venue, the [[Ford Amphitheater at Coney Island]], opened on the boardwalk in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pix11.com/2016/06/29/massive-entertainment-amphitheater-opens-on-iconic-coney-island-boardwalk/|title=Massive entertainment amphitheater opens on iconic Coney Island Boardwalk|date=June 29, 2016|website=WPIX 11 New York|language=en|access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, [[Hurricane Sandy]] caused major damage to the Coney Island amusement parks, the Aquarium, and businesses. However, the [[Nathan's Hot Dog Eating Contest]] was held the following summer, as usual.<ref>{{cite web | title=Nathan's Famous to Reopen in Spring 2013 after Hurricane Sandy | website=Brooklyn Paper | date=December 7, 2012 | url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/35/48/all_nathansrecovery_2012_12_07_bk.html | access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> Luna Park at Coney Island reopened as scheduled on March 24, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Despite Sandy's Wrath, Coney Island's Luna Park To Reopen On Schedule Sunday|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2013/03/22/despite-sandys-wrath-coney-islands-luna-park-to-reopen-on-schedule-sunday/|publisher=CBS News New York|access-date=March 22, 2013}}</ref> Rebuilding of the aquarium started in early 2013, and a major expansion of the aquarium opened in summer 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/06/inside-ocean-wonders-sharks-at-the-new-york-aquarium.html|title=What to Know About the New York Aquarium's New Shark Building|last=Schneider|first=Katy|date=June 28, 2018|website=Daily Intelligencer|access-date=June 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/28/arts/design/new-york-aquarium-sharks-sandy.html|title=Coney Island's Newest Wonder: Sharkitecture!|last=Hodgson|first=Sam|date=June 28, 2018|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=July 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Coney Island Brooklyn Jul 2019 03.jpg|thumb|Reconstruction of [[Shore Theater]] into hotel, seen in 2019]]\n\nIn August 2018, the NYCEDC and NYC Parks announced that Luna Park would be expanded between West 15th and West 16th Streets, next to the Thunderbolt.<ref>{{cite web|title=Log flume ride, zip lines coming to Coney Island|website=am New York|date=August 23, 2018|url=https://www.amny.com/news/coney-island-luna-park-expansion-1.20626460|access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Chung 2018\">{{cite web|last=Chung|first=Jen|title=Coney Island's Luna Park Is Getting Log Flume Ride, A Ropes Course, And More!|website=Gothamist|date=August 23, 2018|url=http://gothamist.com/2018/08/23/luna_park_expanding_coney_island.php|access-date=August 24, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823223421/http://gothamist.com/2018/08/23/luna_park_expanding_coney_island.php | archive-date=August 23, 2018 | url-status=dead}}</ref> There would be a public plaza and an [[amusement arcade]] within the newly expanded amusement area.<ref name=\"Chung 2018\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=City Unveils Plans For New Water Park, Arcade On Coney Island|website=CBS New York|date=August 23, 2018|url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2018/08/23/city-unveils-plans-for-new-water-park-arcade-on-coney-island/|access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref> The same month, it was also announced that a 50-room [[boutique hotel]] was being planned for Coney Island within the former [[Shore Theater]] on Surf and Stillwell Avenues.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ramirez|first=Jeanine|title=Coney Island could see first new hotel in over 50 years|website=Spectrum News NY1 &#124; New York City|date=August 21, 2018|url=http://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2018/08/21/coney-island-could-see-first-new-hotel-in-over-50-years|access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Franklin|first=Sydney|title=Shore Theater on Coney Island will be converted into a boutique hotel|website=Archpaper.com|date=August 21, 2018|url=https://archpaper.com/2018/08/shore-theater-coney-island-hotel/|access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref> The city also expressed its intent to demolish the Abe Stark Rink and redevelop the site, as per the 2009 rezoning, though residents wanted NYC Parks to retain control over the site rather than sell it off to a private developer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Locals demand beloved Coney ice rink remain under Parks Department control|website=Brooklyn Daily|date=August 31, 2018|url=https://www.brooklyndaily.com/stories/2018/35/bn-abe-stark-demolition-2018-08-31-bk.html|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe addition of new amusements coincided with the development of over 2,000 new residential units on empty lots, through the early 2020s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/12/28/coney-island-sees-a-budding-real-estate-boom-after-years-of-decline.html|title=Coney Island, home to hot dogs and the Cyclone roller coaster, sees a budding real estate boom|last=Bukszpan|first=Daniel|date=December 30, 2018|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2018/11/04/wave-of-residential-construction-in-coney-island-to-attract-new-residents-|title=A Wave of New Housing is Being Built in Coney Island|website=www.ny1.com|language=en|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref> These included a 1,000-unit mega-development and a 40-story, 522-unit residential tower that would be the tallest in southern Brooklyn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brooklyneagle.com/articles/2018/08/23/sea-breeze-tower-to-rise-above-coney-island/|title=Sea Breeze Tower to rise above Coney Island|date=August 23, 2018|website=Brooklyn Eagle|language=en-US|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ny.curbed.com/2018/1/4/16850666/coney-island-surf-avenue-megaproject|title=Massive Coney Island development to have 1,000 apartments, retail|last=Warerkar|first=Tanay|date=January 4, 2018|website=Curbed NY|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Amusement parks and attractions ==\n{{anchor|Amusement parks|Theme parks|Amusement}}\nConey Island has two amusement parks, [[Luna Park (Coney Island, 2010)|Luna Park]] and [[Deno's Wonder Wheel Amusement Park]], as well as several rides that are not incorporated into either amusement park. These are owned and managed by several different companies and operate independently of each other. Coney Island also has several other visitor attractions such as [[skee ball|skeeball]] and ball tossing, as well as a [[sideshow]], that contains shooting, throwing, and tossing skills. The area hosts renowned events as well. Coney Island's amusement area is one of a few in the United States that is not mostly owned by any one entity.<ref name=\"DeSenaShortell2012\" />{{rp|153}}\n\n=== Rides ===\n==== Current rides ====\n{{For|a more detailed list of rides operating in Coney Island amusement parks|Luna Park (Coney Island, 2010)#Attractions|Deno's Wonder Wheel Amusement Park#Attractions}}\nConey Island contains three rides with landmark status. One is a [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission|New York City designated landmark]], another is [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Brooklyn|listed]] in the [[National Register of Historic Places]] (NRHP), and a third is both a city landmark and a NRHP-listed landmark.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\"cyclone-nycl\" /><ref>{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Wonder Wheel]], built in 1918 and opened in 1920, is a steel [[Ferris wheel]] with both stationary cars and rocking cars that slide along a track.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amny.com/lifestyle/wonder-wheel-photos-1.10691209|title=The Wonder Wheel at Coney celebrates its 95th summer season|last=Salazar|first=Cristian|date=July 30, 2015|website=am New York|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> It holds 144 riders, stands {{convert|150|ft|m|abbr=on}} tall, weighs over {{convert|200|ST|LT t|sp=us}}, and is located at Deno's Wonder Wheel Amusement Park.<ref name=\"Denson 2011\" />{{rp|47}} The Wonder Wheel was made a city landmark in 1989.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1708.pdf|title=The Wonder Wheel|date=May 23, 1989|publisher=New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>{{Rp|1}}\n\nThe [[B&B Carousell]] {{sic}} (as spelled by the frame's builder, [[William F. Mangels]]) is Coney Island's last traditional [[carousel]], near the old entrance to [[Luna Park (Coney Island, 1903)|Luna Park]]. The carousel was built circa 1906\u20131909 with a traditional roll-operated [[fairground organ]]. It was relocated multiple times, most recently to Luna Park's Steeplechase Plaza in 2013,<ref name=\"Foderaro 2013\">{{cite web|last=Foderaro|first=Lisa W.|title=B&B Carousell Horses Return Home to Coney Island|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 24, 2013|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/26/nyregion/bb-carousell-horses-return-home-to-coney-island.html|access-date=July 28, 2018}}</ref> and listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coney Island's B&B Carousell placed on National Register of Historic Places|website=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|date=July 28, 2018|url=http://www.brooklyneagle.com/articles/2016/3/8/coney-island%E2%80%99s-bb-carousell-placed-national-register-historic-places|access-date=July 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=B&B Carousell designated national historic place, up for federal preservation money \u2022 Brooklyn Daily|website=Brooklyn Daily|date=March 11, 2016|url=https://www.brooklyndaily.com/stories/2016/11/bn-b-and-b-carousell-on-historic-register-2016-03-11-bk.html|access-date=July 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Coney Island Cyclone]], built in 1927, is one of the United States's oldest [[wooden roller coaster]]s still in operation. The Cyclone includes an {{convert|85|ft|m|abbr=on}}, 58-degree drop. It is owned by the City of New York, and is operated by [[Luna Park (Coney Island, 2010)|Luna Park]] under a franchise agreement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/04/nyregion/04critic.html|work=The New York Times|title=Thrilling Reminder of Old Coney Island|first=Ariel|last=Kaminer|date=April 2, 2010}}</ref> The Cyclone was made a city landmark in 1988<ref name=\"cyclone-nycl\">{{Cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1636.pdf|title=The Cyclone|date=July 12, 1988|publisher=New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>{{Rp|1}}<ref name=\"NYTimes-Cyclone-1988\" /> and was listed on the NRHP in 1991.<ref>{{NRISref|2013a|dateform=mdy|access-date=February 26, 2019|refnum=91000907|name=Cyclone Roller Coaster}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n| align = center\n| direction = horizontal\n| total_width = 800\n| image1 = Coney-island-cyclone-usgs-photo.jpg\n| caption1 =  [[Coney Island Cyclone]]\n| image2 = WonderWheelNewYork.jpg\n| caption2 = [[Wonder Wheel]]\n| image3 = Thunderbolt 2014-08-11 view from west.JPG\n| caption3 = [[Thunderbolt (2014 roller coaster)|Thunderbolt]]\n| image4 = Coney Carousel 006.JPG\n| caption4 = [[B&B Carousell]]\n}}\n\nThere are also multiple other rides in Coney Island. In March 2014, construction started on the new [[Thunderbolt (2014 roller coaster)|Thunderbolt]], a [[steel roller coaster]] that was manufactured by [[Zamperla]] at a cost of $10 million. The ride features {{Convert|2000|ft|m}} of track, a height of {{Convert|125|ft|m}}, and a top speed of {{Convert|65|mph}}, as well as four [[Roller coaster inversions|inversions]].<ref name=\"RCDB2\">{{cite RCDB|coaster_name=Thunderbolt|location=Luna Park|rcdb_number=8788|access-date=November 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://brooklyn.news12.com/news/luna-park-breaks-ground-on-new-roller-coaster-the-thunderbolt-on-coney-island-1.7344601|title=Luna Park breaks ground on new roller coaster, the Thunderbolt, on Coney Island \u2013 News 12 Brooklyn|date=March 10, 2014|publisher=Brooklyn.news12.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140311180202/http://brooklyn.news12.com/news/luna-park-breaks-ground-on-new-roller-coaster-the-thunderbolt-on-coney-island-1.7344601|archivedate=March 11, 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=June 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=New Roller Coaster Promises Coney Island a Return of Thrills | website=The New York Times | date=March 11, 2014 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/11/nyregion/new-roller-coaster-promises-coney-island-a-return-of-thrills.html | access-date=October 22, 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2014/03/10/coney-islands-luna-park-to-get-new-roller-coaster/|title=Coney Island's Luna Park To Get New Roller Coaster \u00ab CBS New York|date=March 10, 2014|publisher=Newyork.cbslocal.com|access-date=June 4, 2014}}</ref> The Thunderbolt opened in June 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn/coney-island-new-thunderbolt-roller-coaster-officially-opens-article-1.1830380|title=Coney Island's new Thunderbolt roller coaster officially opens|work=NY Daily News|date=June 14, 2014|access-date=June 29, 2014|author=Brown, Stephen R.}}</ref>\n\nThere are also multiple [[bumper car]] rides in Coney Island, all operated separately. {{As of|2019||df=|since=}}, these include an attraction in Deno's Wonder Wheel Park,<ref name=\"denos-map\">{{cite web|url=https://www.denoswonderwheel.com/s/0302-Denos-WW-Park-map-2018compressed.pdf|title=Park Map|website=DENO'S WONDER WHEEL|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> as well as Eldorado Auto Skooter on Surf Avenue. Historically, the earliest bumper car rides were located in Coney Island.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/experience/america/theme-parks/2019/02/21/bumper-cars-history/2843129002/|title=Bumper cars: A crash course on the classic amusement park ride|date=February 21, 2019|website=USA TODAY|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> Furthermore, two traditional [[dark ride]] [[Haunted attraction (simulated)|haunted houses]] operate at Coney Island: [[Spook-a-Rama]] at Deno's,<ref name=\"denos-map\" /> and [[Ghost Hole]] on West 12th Street adjacent to Deno's.<ref name=\"fun-guide\">{{cite web|url=http://coneyislandfunguide.com/fun-map-of-coney-island/|title=Fun Map of Coney Island|date=December 5, 2013|website=Coney Island Fun Guide|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Former rides ====\n[[File:ThunderboltConeyIsland1995.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The original [[Thunderbolt (1925 roller coaster)|Thunderbolt]] in 1995]]\n\nConey Island has had three major amusement parks in its past\u2014[[Steeplechase Park]] (1897\u20131964), [[Luna Park (Coney Island, 1903)|Luna Park]] (1903\u20131944), and [[Dreamland (Coney Island, 1904)|Dreamland]] (1904\u20131911)\u2014as well as several standalone attractions.<ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|74}}<ref>{{cite web | title=Steeplechase, Luna Park, and Dreamland \u2013 BKM TECH | website=Brooklyn Museum | date=January 16, 2008 | url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/community/blogosphere/2008/01/16/steeplechase-luna-park-and-dreamland/ | access-date=July 17, 2019}}</ref> In addition, [[Astroland]] operated at the site of the current Luna Park from 1962 to 2008,<ref>{{cite web | title=Astroland is truly dead | website=Brooklyn Paper | date=September 5, 2008 | url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/31/36/31_36_mm_astroland.html | access-date=October 19, 2019}}</ref> while a second [[Dreamland (Coney Island, 2009)|Dreamland]] only operated for the 2009 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn/nightmare-dreamland-rent-woes-shut-coney-island-park-owner-vows-court-battle-article-1.396209|title=Nightmare at Dreamland: Rent woes shut Coney Island park as owner vows court battle|last=Durkin|first=Erin|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/32/35/32_35_mm_dreamland_is_dead.html|title=IT'S OVER! Coney's Dreamland will be closed for the rest of the summer|last=McLaughlin|first=Mike|website=Brooklyn Paper|language=en|access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the rides in Coney Island's former amusement parks, there were also several dozen roller coasters that are now defunct.<ref>{{cite web|title=Roller Coasters|website=Coney Island|date=June 2, 2004|url=https://www.westland.net/coneyisland/articles/coasterlist.htm|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> The Comet, next to the Cyclone's current site, was built in 1921 and destroyed in 1945.<ref name=\"Denson 2011\" />{{rp|46}} Another coaster, the Oriental Scenic Railway, was created by [[LaMarcus Adna Thompson]] in 1887,<ref name=\"Immerso2002\" />{{rp|98\u201399}}<ref name=\"Denson 2011\" />{{rp|41}} and was demolished in 1955 to be replaced with a \"hot rod\" amusement ride.<ref name=\"Billboard-19550129\" /> The [[steeplechase roller coaster]], created by Steeplechase Park operator George C. Tilyou in 1897, consisted of people riding wooden horses around the park on a steel track.<ref name=\"Ierardi\" /> The original wooden [[Thunderbolt (1925 roller coaster)|Thunderbolt]] coaster, located between West 15th and West 16th Streets, was constructed in 1925, closed in 1983, and torn down in 2000 during the construction of nearby Keyspan Park.<ref>{{cite RCDB|coaster_name=Thunderbolt|location=Coney Island \u2013 George Moran|rcdb_number=423|access-date=November 16, 2013}}</ref><ref name=endofln>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=iopOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vR4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5735%2C906219 |work=Spartanburg Herald-Journal |location=South Carolina |agency=Associated Press |title=End of the line |date=November 19, 2000 |page=10A}}</ref> Nearby was [[Tornado (Coney Island)|Tornado]], a wooden coaster constructed in&nbsp;1926,<ref name=\"Parascandola 2014\" />{{rp|24}}<ref>{{cite RCDB|coaster_name=Tornado|location=Coney Island \u2013 Independent Vendor 5|rcdb_number=5690|access-date=November 16, 2013}}</ref> and destroyed by arson in&nbsp;1977.<ref>{{cite web|title=3 Women Killed in Brooklyn Fires|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=December 11, 1977|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/12/11/archives/3-women-killed-in-brooklyn-fires.html|access-date=January 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nConey Island also contains one defunct ride that is still standing, the [[Parachute Jump]]. Originally built as the [[Life Savers]] Parachute Jump at the [[1939 New York World's Fair]], this was the first ride of its kind. Patrons were hoisted {{convert|262|ft|m|abbr=on}} in the air before being allowed to drop using guy-wired parachutes. The Parachute Jump was closed in the 1960s, but was officially preserved,<ref name=\"NYT2005\" /> having been listed on the NRHP in 1980<ref>{{NRISref|2013a|dateform=mdy|access-date=February 26, 2019|refnum=80002645|name=Parachute Jump}}</ref> and made a city landmark in 1989.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1638.pdf|title=The Parachute Jump|date=May 23, 1989|publisher=New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>{{rp|1}}<ref name=\"NYTimes-PJ-1989\" />\n\n=== Beaches ===\n[[File:Coney Island beach (June 2016).jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1|The beach at Coney Island in June 2016, with the [[Marine Parkway\u2013Gil Hodges Memorial Bridge]] visible on the horizon]]\nThere is a broad public sand beach that starts at Sea Gate at West 37th Street, through the central Coney Island area and [[Brighton Beach]], to the beginning of the community of [[Manhattan Beach, Brooklyn|Manhattan Beach]], a distance of approximately {{convert|2.7|mi|km|abbr=on}}. The beach is continuous and is served for its entire length by the broad [[Riegelmann Boardwalk]]. Numerous amusements, as well as the aquarium and a variety of food shops and arcades, are directly accessible from the landward side of the boardwalk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/coney-island-beach-and-boardwalk/highlights/204|title=Coney Island Beach & Boardwalk Highlights|date=June 26, 1939|website=Coney Island : NYC Parks|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"La Rocco 2004\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tx-3l1hZfPQC&pg=PA137|title=Going Coastal New York City|last=La Rocco|first=Barbara|publisher=Going Coastal|year=2004|isbn=978-0-9729803-0-2|page=137|language=et|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> The boardwalk in Manhattan Beach, located within Manhattan Beach Park, is not connected with the Riegelmann Boardwalk.<ref name=\":20\">{{cite web | title=Manhattan Beach Park : NYC Parks | website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation | date=June 26, 1939 | url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/manhattan-beach-park | access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe beaches in Coney Island used to be private until 1923, when the city bought all the land on the waterfront and created the Riegelmann Boardwalk and Beach.<ref>{{cite web|title=Secrets of Coney Island|website=am New York|date=August 23, 2018|url=https://www.amny.com/secrets-of-new-york/secrets-of-coney-island-1.10182810|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> Today, only the sand beach inside Sea Gate is private; it is accessible solely to residents of that community.<ref name=\"La Rocco 2004\" />\n\nThe public beaches are maintained on a regular basis by the city. Because sand no longer naturally deposits on the beach, it is replenished in regular [[beach nourishment]] projects using [[Dredging|dredged]] sand.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> The public beaches are open and free to use, though the boardwalk is closed during nights from 1 to 5 a.m.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/coney-island-beach-and-boardwalk/facilities/beaches|title=Coney Island Beach & Boardwalk Beaches : NYC Parks|date=June 26, 1939|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref> The beach area is divided into several sections by rock [[groyne]]s that were built in the 1920s to prevent erosion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/2583.pdf|title=Coney Island (Riegelmann) Boardwalk|date=May 15, 2018|website=nyc.gov|publisher=New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref>{{Rp|15}}\n\nThere are several clubs that host activities on Coney Island's beach. The [[Coney Island Polar Bear Club]] consists of a group of people who swim at Coney Island throughout the winter months. Their most popular event is an annual swim on [[New Year's Day]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amny.com/secrets-of-new-york/coney-island-polar-bear-club-forging-into-the-icy-atlantic-ocean-for-decades-1.11255114|title=The Coney Island Polar Bear Club, braving the icy Atlantic|date=December 31, 2018|website=am New York|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Denson 2011\">{{cite book|last=Denson|first=Charles|title=Coney Island and Astroland|publisher=Arcadia Pub.|series=Images of America Series|year=2011|isbn=978-0-7385-7428-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CVNG35jlce8C&pg=PA50|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>{{rp|50}} The beach also serves as the training grounds for the Coney Island Brighton Beach Open Water Swimmers, a group dedicated to promoting [[open water swimming]], which hosts several open water swim races each year.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stein|first=Mara Lemos|title=Brooklyn's Swimming Mecca|website=Wall Street Journal|date=November 24, 2011|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204452104577055950095852414|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mooney|first=Jake|title=On a Beach in Brooklyn, an Empty Lifeguard's Chair|website=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|date=May 10, 2009|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/10/nyregion/thecity/10disp.html|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Coney island board walk.jpg|900px|The boardwalk around sunset}}\n\n=== Public parks ===\nThere are several public parks in Coney Island, operated by the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]. Parks within the main Coney Island neighborhood include:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/maps/|title=Maps : NYC Parks|date=June 26, 1939|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|access-date=June 12, 2019}}</ref>\n* The [[Abe Stark#Legacy|Abe Stark]] Skating Rink, located on the south side of Surf Avenue between West 19th and West 20th Streets, adjacent to the boardwalk. It opened in 1970.<ref>{{cite web|title=Abe Stark Skating Rink Highlights : NYC Parks|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/abe-stark-skating-rink/history|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref>\n* Coney Island Creek Park, located along the south shore of Coney Island Creek. Opened in 1984, it is composed mostly of plants.<ref name=\"NYC Parks CIC\">{{cite web|title=Coney Island Creek Park : NYC Parks|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/coney-island-creek-park/history|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref>\n* Leon S. Kaiser Park, located on the northern side of Neptune Avenue between West 24th and West 32nd Streets, and contains playgrounds, athletic facilities, fitness equipment, and open spaces for barbecuing.<ref name=\"NYC Parks Kaiser\">{{cite web|title=Kaiser Park : NYC Parks|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|date=October 16, 2004|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/leon-s-kaiser-park|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref>\n* Poseidon Playground, located along the beach between West 25th and West 27th Streets, and contains water spray showers, playgrounds, and handball courts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Poseidon Playground : NYC Parks|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/poseidon-playground/history|access-date=July 28, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Steeplechase Park#Current status|Steeplechase Park]], located along the beach between West 16th and West 19th Streets. It contains a public plaza with seating, as well as [[MCU Park]], a [[minor league baseball]] stadium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/steeplechase-park|title=Steeplechase Park : NYC Parks|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|access-date=July 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* Surf Playground, located on the south side of Surf Avenue between West 25th and West 27th Streets, just north of Poseidon Playground. It contains basketball courts, playgrounds, and water spray showers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Surf Playground Highlights|website=New York City Department of Parks & Recreation|date=May 15, 1923|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/surf-playground/history|access-date=July 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Other attractions ===\nThe [[New York Aquarium]] opened in 1957 on the former site of the Dreamland amusement park.<ref name=NYParks-Aquarium-History /> It is located on 602 Surf Avenue between West 5th and West 10th Streets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nyaquarium.com/visitor-info/getting-here|title=Getting Here|date=January 2, 2019|website=New York Aquarium|language=en|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> {{As of|2018}}, the New York Aquarium consists of five exhibits: Aquatheater; Conservation Hall; Sea Cliffs; Sharks, Rays & Turtles; and Ocean Wonders: Sharks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nyaquarium.com/exhibits |title=Exhibits|publisher=New York Aquarium|accessdate=September 22, 2019}}</ref> The original [[Bathysphere]], a deep-sea submersible that made historic journeys underwater in the 1930s, is on display at the aquarium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aps.org/publications/apsnews/201808/history.cfm|title=This Month in Physics History|last=Poffenberger|first=Leah|date=August\u2013September 2018|website=American Physical Society|access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nKeySpan Park, located on the former site of Steeplechase Park, opened in 2001.<ref name=\":15\" /> It hosts the [[Brooklyn Cyclones]] minor league baseball team.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HIxPgnmtQlcC&pg=PA135|title=Brooklyn!, 3rd Edition: The Ultimate Guide to New York's Most Happening Borough|last=Freudenheim|first=E.|last2=Wiener|first2=A.|publisher=St. Martin's Press|year=2004|isbn=978-0-312-32331-8|page=135|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> In 2010, it was renamed after the [[Municipal Credit Union]] (MCU), the city's largest credit union, in an eleven-year naming rights deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/33/6/33_06_sb_keyspan_is_dead.html|title=Lights Out at Keyspan Park as Naming Rights Deal Ends|last=Brown|first=Stephen|date=January 29, 2010|newspaper=[[The Brooklyn Paper]]|accessdate=January 31, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/ny_local/brooklyn/2010/02/04/2010-02-04_brooklyn_cyclones_keyspan_park_renamed_mcu_park.html|title=Brooklyn Cyclones' KeySpan Park Renamed MCU Park|last=Epstein|first=Victor|date=February 4, 2010|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|accessdate=February 4, 2010|last2=Yaniv|first2=Oren|location=New York}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, the [[Ford Amphitheater at Coney Island]] opened on the boardwalk to the west of MCU Park, hosting several live musical acts as well as other events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2016/03/14/coney-island-ampitheater.html|title=NY1 Exclusive: A Look at the New Coney Island Amphitheater|publisher=Ny1.com|date=March 14, 2016|access-date=September 17, 2016}}</ref> It was constructed at the location of the [[Childs Restaurants (Coney Island Boardwalk location)|Childs Restaurant]], which was originally constructed in 1923 and was renovated when the amphitheater was being constructed. The rooftop part of the restaurant reopened in July 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theconeyislandblog.com/?p=902|title=UPDATED: Construction Begins on Controversial Seaside Amphitheater &#124;|publisher=Theconeyislandblog.com|date=|access-date=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe nonprofit organization [[Coney Island USA]] also operates the Coney Island Museum, a collection of memorabilia that chronicles the history of the neighborhood. The museum opened in 1980, and is located at 1208 Surf Avenue near the intersection with West 12th Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thevillager.com/2014/06/coney-island-museum-returns-to-form/|title=Coney Island Museum returns to form|date=June 19, 2014|website=The Villager|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> It charges a $5 admission fee per adult.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coneyisland.com/programs/coney-island-museum|title=Coney Island USA|website=Coney Island Museum|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nycgo.com/museums-galleries/coney-island-museum|title=Coney Island Museum \u2013 Museums & Galleries|website=NYCgo.com|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> Another nonprofit founded in 2004, the Coney Island History Project, operates a space near the Wonder Wheel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nycgo.com/museums-galleries/coney-island-history-project2|title=Coney Island History Project \u2013 Museums & Galleries|website=NYCgo.com|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Events ===\n{{multiple image\n|align=right\n|direction=horizontal\n|total_width=350\n|image1=Nathan's Coney Island July 2007.jpg\n|alt1=Nathan's Famous hot dog restaurant on the Coney Island boardwalk\n|caption1=[[Nathan's Famous]]\n|image2=Freak bar.jpg\n|alt2=The Freak Bar, a Coney Island bar with a Freakshow/Sideshow theme\n|caption2=The Freak Bar\n}}\n\nConey Island USA sponsors various seasonal acts every year. In April, the organization hosts the Noisefest and the Congress of Curious Peoples. This is followed in May or June by the [[Coney Island Mermaid Parade]], which takes place on Surf Avenue and the boardwalk, and features [[Float (parade)|floats]] and performances. During August or September, Coney Island USA produces the Beard and Moustache Competition; Tattoo and Motorcycle Festival; and Coney Island Film Festival. The organization then hosts the Creepshow at the Freakshow, an interactive [[Halloween]]-themed event, in October.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coneyisland.com/programs/special-events|title=Special Events|website=Coney Island USA|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe annual Cosme 5K Charity Run/Walk, supported by the Coney Island Sports Foundation, takes place on the Riegelmann Boardwalk toward the end of June.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/31/29/sports_brooklyn_sportsrunnerspou07142008.html|title=Runners pound the b'walk \u2013 Cosme 5K Charity Run brings athletes to the shore|date=January 1, 2019|website=Brooklyn Paper|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA major national [[volleyball]] tournament hosted by the [[Association of Volleyball Professionals]] (AVP), which is typically hosted on the [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]] of the U.S., was held in Coney Island starting in 2006. The AVP built a 4,000-seat stadium and twelve outer courts next to the boardwalk for the event.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coney Island on the Ball \u2013 Beach volleyball is hitting New York ... & the boardwalk is the place to be|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/nydn-features/coney-island-ball-beach-volleyball-hitting-new-york-boardwalk-place-article-1.634345|website=NY Daily News|access-date = January 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/12/nyregion/thecity/on-a-gritty-shore-california-dreaming.html|title=On a Gritty Shore, California Dreaming|last=Mooney|first=Jake|date=February 12, 2006|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 26, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The tournament returned to Coney Island from 2007 through 2009, but was not hosted at Coney Island in 2010 due to a lack of money.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2010/05/07/spiked-pro-volleyball-tourney-to-skip-coney-island-this-summer/|title=Spiked! Pro volleyball tourney to skip Coney Island this summer|last=Maniscalco|first=Joe|date=May 7, 2010|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> When AVP tournaments resumed in Brooklyn in 2015, they were hosted at [[Brooklyn Bridge Park]] instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/38/30/dtg-park-vs-coney-volleyball-2015-07-24-bk.html|title=Beach bums! Pro volleyball shuns Coney, serves up in Brooklyn Bridge Park|date=July 24, 2015|website=Brooklyn Paper|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the [[Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus]] performed in Coney Island for the first time since 1956. The event, titled ''The Coney Island Boom-A-Ring'', was housed in tents that were located between the boardwalk and Surf Avenue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2009/10/13/coney-island-boom-a-ring-return-in-the-works/|title=Coney Island Boom-A-Ring return in the works|last=Maniscalco|first=Joe|date=October 13, 2009|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/33/23/sg_circus_2010_bk.html|title=Ringling's 'Illuscination' opens on June 17|last=Glass|first=Claire|date=June 4, 2010|website=Brooklyn Paper|language=en|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> The following year, they returned to the same location with ''The Coney Island Illuscination''.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\nStarting in May 2015, Thor Equities unveiled Coney Art Walls, a public art wall project curated by former [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles]] director [[Jeffrey Deitch]] and Thor CEO Joe Sitt. Located at 3050 Stillwell Avenue, the project featured work from more than 30 artists.<ref name=\"auto\" /> Since then, the exhibition has been held every year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/41/25/sci-coney-art-walls-2018-06-22-bk.html|title=Walls of sound: Coney Art Walls host concerts, food, and art|date=June 22, 2018|website=Brooklyn Paper|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brownstoner.com/brooklyn-life/coney-art-walls-brooklyn-jeffrey-deitch-lee-quinones/|title=Coney Art Walls Returns to Brooklyn on May 25|last=Hubert|first=Craig|date=May 24, 2018|website=Brownstoner|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n{{wide image|Coney Island panorama (June 2016) 2.jpg|1500px|3={{center|Panorama of Coney Island waterfront as seen from the pier in June 2016}}}}\n\n== Demographics ==\n[[File:W15 CI volunteers arrive Sandy jeh.jpg|thumb|Volunteers arrive to clear the boardwalk after [[Hurricane Sandy]].]]\nBased on data from the [[2010 United States Census]], the combined population of Coney Island and Sea Gate was 31,965, a decrease of 2,302 (6.7%) from the 34,267 counted in [[2000 United States Census|2000]]. Covering an area of {{convert|851.49|acres}}, the neighborhood had a population density of {{convert|37.5|PD/acre|PD/sqmi PD/sqkm}}.<ref name=\"PLP5\">[http://www1.nyc.gov/assets/planning/download/pdf/data-maps/nyc-population/census2010/t_pl_p5_nta.pdf Table PL-P5 NTA: Total Population and Persons Per Acre \u2013 New York City Neighborhood Tabulation Areas*, 2010], Population Division \u2013 [[New York City]] Department of City Planning, February 2012. Accessed June 15, 2016.</ref>\n\nThe racial makeup of the neighborhood was 32.2% (10,307) [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 30.9% (9,880) [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 8.7% (2,793) [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.2% (78) [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.0% (4) [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.2% (67) from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.5% (467) from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 26.2% (8,369) of the population.<ref name=\"PLP3A\">[http://www1.nyc.gov/assets/planning/download/pdf/data-maps/nyc-population/census2010/t_pl_p3a_nta.pdf Table PL-P3A NTA: Total Population by Mutually Exclusive Race and Hispanic Origin \u2013 New York City Neighborhood Tabulation Areas*, 2010], Population Division \u2013 [[New York City Department of City Planning]], March 29, 2011. Accessed June 14, 2016.</ref> 82% of the population were [[high school]] graduates and 40% had a [[bachelor's degree]] or higher.<ref name=\"PLP3A\" /><ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|2}}\n\nThe entirety of Community Board 13 had 106,459 inhabitants as of [[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene|NYC Health]]'s 2018 Community Health Profile, with an average life expectancy of 80.4 years.<ref name=\"CHP2018\">{{Cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/data/2018chp-bk13.pdf|title=CONEY ISLAND (Including Brighton Beach, Coney Island, Gravesend, Homecrest, Sea Gate and West Brighton)|last=|first=|date=2018|website=nyc.gov|publisher=NYC Health|access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>{{Rp|2, 20}} This is lower than the median life expectancy of 81.2 for all New York City neighborhoods.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/tcny/community-health-assessment-plan.pdf|title=2016-2018 Community Health Assessment and Community Health Improvement Plan: Take Care New York 2020|last=|first=|date=2016|website=[[government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene]]|access-date=September 8, 2017}}</ref>{{Rp|53 (PDF p. 84)}}<ref>{{cite web | title=New Yorkers are living longer, happier and healthier lives | website=New York Post | date=June 4, 2017 | url=https://nypost.com/2017/06/04/new-yorkers-are-living-longer-happier-and-healthier-lives/ | access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> Most inhabitants are adults, with 25% between the ages of 25\u201344, 27% between 45\u201364, and 22% who are at least 65 years old. The ratio of young and college-aged residents was lower, at 19% and 8% respectively.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|2}} Coney Island's elderly population, as a share of the area's total population, is higher than in other New York City neighborhoods.<ref name=\":14\" />{{rp|6}}\n\nAs of 2016, the median [[household income]] in Community District 13 was $39,213.<ref>{{cite web|title=Census profile: NYC-Brooklyn Community District 13--Brighton Beach & Coney Island PUMA, NY|website=Census Reporter|date=July 22, 2018|url=https://censusreporter.org/profiles/79500US3604018-nyc-brooklyn-community-district-13-brighton-beach-coney-island-puma-ny|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> In 2018, an estimated 24% of Coney Island residents lived in poverty, compared to 21% in all of Brooklyn and 20% in all of New York City. One in eight residents (11%) were unemployed, compared to 9% in the rest of both Brooklyn and New York City. Rent burden, or the percentage of residents who have difficulty paying their rent, is 55% in Coney Island, slightly higher than the citywide and boroughwide rates of 52% and 51% respectively. Based on this calculation, {{as of|2018|lc=y}}, Coney Island is not considered to be [[gentrification|gentrifying]].<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|7}}\n\n== Police and crime ==\nConey Island is patrolled by the [[New York City Police Department|NYPD]]'s 60th Precinct, located at 2950 West Eighth Street.<ref name=\"NYPD 60th Precinct\">{{Cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/nypd/bureaus/patrol/precincts/60th-precinct.page|title=NYPD \u2013 60th Precinct|last=|first=|date=|website=www.nyc.gov|publisher=[[New York City Police Department]]|access-date=October 3, 2016}}</ref> Transit District 34 is located at 1243 Surf Avenue, within the [[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue (New York City Subway)|Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue]] subway station.<ref>{{cite web|title=Transit District 34 \u2013 NYPD|website=Welcome to NYC.gov|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/nypd/bureaus/transit-housing/transit-district-34.page|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe 60th Precinct ranked 34th safest out of 69 patrol areas for per-capita crime in 2010. Between 1993 and 2010, major crimes decreased by 72%, including a 76% decrease in robberies, 71% decrease in felony assaults, and 67% decrease in shootings.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnainfo.com/crime-safety-report/brooklyn/coney-island/|title=Coney Island \u2013 DNAinfo.com Crime and Safety Report|website=www.dnainfo.com|access-date=October 6, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723034345/https://www.dnainfo.com/crime-safety-report/brooklyn/coney-island/|archive-date=July 23, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> With a non-fatal assault rate of 51 per 100,000 people, Coney Island's rate of violent crimes per capita is less than that of the city as a whole. The incarceration rate of 168 per 100,000 people is about the same of that of the city as a whole.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|8}} The 60th Precinct has a lower crime rate than in the 1990s, with crimes across all categories having decreased by 84.6% between 1990 and 2017. The precinct saw 0 murders, 20 rapes, 1138 robberies, 232 felony assaults, 89 burglaries, 422 grand larcenies, and 46 grand larcenies auto in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/nypd/downloads/pdf/crime_statistics/cs-en-us-060pct.pdf|title=60th Precinct CompStat Report|date=|website=www.nyc.gov|publisher=[[New York City Police Department]]|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Fire safety ==\n[[File:CI Engine 318 jeh.jpg|thumb|Engine Co. 318/Ladder Co. 166]]\nThe [[New York City Fire Department]] (FDNY) operates two [[firehouse]]s in the area:<ref name=\"fdny-locs\">{{Cite FDNY locations}}</ref>\n* Engine Co. 318/Ladder Co. 166, located at 2510 Neptune Avenue.<ref>{{cite web|title=Engine Company 318/Ladder Company 166|website=FDNYtrucks.com|url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e318.htm|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref> It contains the [[Coney Island Fire Station Pumping Station]], [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Brooklyn|listed]] on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3186|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration:Coney Island Fire Station Pumping Station|date=August 1980|accessdate=February 20, 2011 |author1=Michael S. May |author2=Carol Clark |author3=Anne B. Covell |publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]}} ''See also:'' {{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3293|title=Accompanying four photos}}</ref>\n* Engine Co. 245/Ladder Co. 161/Battalion 43, located at 2929 West 8th Street.<ref>{{cite web|title=Engine Company 245/Ladder Company 161/Battalion 43|website=FDNYtrucks.com|url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e245.htm|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[New York City Fire Department Bureau of EMS|FDNY EMS]] Station 43 is on the grounds of Coney Island Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nychealthandhospitals.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Coney_Island_Hospital_Environmental_Assessment.pdf|title=Environmental Assessment HHC Coney Island Hospital New Critical Services Structure New York City, Kings County, New York|date=July 2015|publisher=[[United States Department of Homeland Security]]; [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]]|website=[[NYC Health + Hospitals|nychealthandhospitals.org]]|access-date=March 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Health ==\n[[File:CIH @ Shore & Ocean Pkwys jeh.jpg|thumb|left|Coney Island Hospital]]\nPreterm and teenage births are slightly more common in Coney Island than in other places citywide. In Coney Island, there were 95 preterm births per 1,000 live births (compared to 87 per 1,000 citywide), and 20.2 teenage births per 1,000 live births (compared to 19.3 per 1,000 citywide), slightly higher than in the median neighborhood.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|11}} Coney Island has a high population of residents who are [[Health insurance coverage in the United States|uninsured]], or who receive healthcare through [[Medicaid]].<ref name=\":14\">[http://www.health.ny.gov/health_care/medicaid/redesign/dsrip/pps_applications/docs/maimonides_medical_center/3.8_maimonides_cna.pdf New York City Health Provider Partnership Brooklyn Community Needs Assessment: Final Report], [[New York Academy of Medicine]] (October 3, 2014).</ref> In 2018, this population of uninsured residents was estimated to be 14%, which is higher than the citywide rate of 12%.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|14}}\n\nThe concentration of [[particulates|fine particulate matter]], the deadliest type of [[air pollution|air pollutant]], in Coney Island is {{convert|0.0067|mg/m3|oz/ft3}}, lower than the citywide and boroughwide averages.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|9}} Nineteen percent of Coney Island residents are [[Smoking|smokers]], which is higher the city average of 14% of residents being smokers.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|13}} In Coney Island, 28% of residents are [[Obesity|obese]], 15% are [[Diabetes mellitus|diabetic]], and 31% have [[hypertension|high blood pressure]]\u2014higher than the citywide averages of 24%, 11%, and 28% respectively.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|16}} In addition, 18% of children are obese, compared to the citywide average of 20%.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|12}}\n\nNinety-two percent of residents eat some fruits and vegetables every day, which is slightly higher than the city's average of 87%. In 2018, 70% of residents described their health as \"good,\" \"very good,\" or \"excellent,\" lower than the city's average of 78%.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|13}} For every supermarket in Coney Island, there are 21 [[convenience store|bodegas]].<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|10}}\n\nThe primary hospital in the neighborhood is [[Coney Island Hospital]].<ref name=\":14\" />{{rp|6}}\n\n== Post offices and ZIP codes ==\nConey Island's primary [[ZIP Code]] is 11224,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zipmap.net/zips/11224.htm|title=Zip Code 11224, Brooklyn, New York Zip Code Boundary Map (NY)|website=United States Zip Code Boundary Map (USA)|access-date=March 10, 2019}}</ref> though the small portions located east of West 1st Street and Ocean Parkway are located in ZIP Code 11235.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zipmap.net/zips/11235.htm|title=Zip Code 11235, Brooklyn, New York Zip Code Boundary Map (NY)|website=United States Zip Code Boundary Map (USA)|access-date=March 10, 2019}}</ref> There are two [[United States Post Office]] branches in Coney Island. The Coney Island Station is located at 2727 Mermaid Avenue,<ref>{{cite web|title=USPS Locations|url=https://tools.usps.com/go/POLocatorDetailsAction!input.action?&radius=20&locationType=po&locationTypeQ=po&locationID=1358925| accessdate = June 20, 2018}}</ref> and the Neptune Station is located at 532 Neptune Avenue.<ref>{{cite web|title=USPS Locations|url=https://tools.usps.com/go/POLocatorDetailsAction!input.action?&radius=20&locationType=po&locationTypeQ=po&locationID=374586| accessdate = June 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nConey Island generally has a similar ratio of college-educated residents to the rest of the city. While 45% of residents age 25 and older have a college education or higher, 18% have less than a high school education and 37% are high school graduates or have some college education. By contrast, 40% of Brooklynites and 38% of city residents have a college education or higher.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|6}} The percentage of Coney Island students excelling in math has been increasing, though reading achievement has declined; math achievement rose from 53 percent in 2000 to 72 percent in 2011, but reading achievement fell from 57 to 55 percent within the same time period.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=http://furmancenter.org/files/sotc/BK_13_11.pdf|title=Coney Island \u2013 BK 13|last=|first=|date=2011|website=|publisher=[[Furman Center for Real Estate and Urban Policy]]|access-date=October 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nConey Island's rate of elementary school student absenteeism is higher than the rest of New York City. In Coney Island, 26% of elementary school students missed twenty or more days per [[school year]], compared to the citywide average of 20% of students.<ref name=\":21\" />{{Rp|24 (PDF p. 55)}}<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|7}}\n\n=== Elementary, middle, and high schools ===\n[[File:Abraham Lincoln High School.jpg|thumb|Abraham Lincoln High School]]\nConey Island is served by the [[New York City Department of Education]], and students in the neighborhood are automatically \"zoned\" into the nearest public schools. The zoned schools for the main portion of Coney Island include:\n* PS 90 Edna Cohen School (grades K-5)<ref>Tartar, Andre. \"[http://nymag.com/daily/intel/2012/08/teacher-exodus-at-troubled-coney-island-school.html Teacher Exodus at Coney Island School Where Principal Banned \u2018God Bless the USA\u2019].\" ''[[New York Magazine]]''. August 19, 2012. Retrieved on October 17, 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=P.S. 90 Edna Cohen School|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K090|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* PS 100 Coney Island School (grades K-5)<ref>{{cite web|title=P.S. 100 The Coney Island School|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K100|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Scharfenberg1\">{{cite web | last=Scharfenberg | first=David | title=Safety Belts On? Renewal Has Its Hazards | website=The New York Times | date=November 19, 2006 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/19/realestate/19livi.html | access-date=July 6, 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* PS 188 The Michael E. Berdy School (grades K-4)<ref>{{cite web|title=P.S. 188 Michael E. Berdy|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K188|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* PS/IS 288 The Shirley Tanyhill School (grades PK-8)<ref>{{cite web|title=P.S. 288 The Shirley Tanyhill|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K288|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* IS 303 Herbert S. Eisenberg (grades 6-8)<ref name=Scharfenberg1 /><ref name=\"Hughes2\">{{cite web | last=Hughes | first=C. J. | title=Waterfront Living That Doesn't Break the Bank | website=The New York Times | date=April 30, 2010 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/02/realestate/02living.html | access-date=July 6, 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=I.S. 303 Herbert S. Eisenberg|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K303|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* PS 329 (grades PK-5)<ref>{{cite web|title=P.S. 329 Surfside|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K329|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIS 239, the [[Mark Twain School for the Gifted and Talented]] (6\u20138), is a [[magnet school]] for gifted students, and it accepts students from around the city.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mark Twain I.S. 239 for the Gifted & Talented|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K239|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref> In 2006, David Scharfenberg of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said, \"Coney Island's elementary schools are a mixed lot, with only some exceeding citywide averages on the state's testing regimen.\"<ref name=Scharfenberg1 />\n\nAll New York City high school students can go to any high school in the city. There are two public high schools in Coney Island: [[Abraham Lincoln High School (Brooklyn)|Abraham Lincoln High School]]<ref name=Scharfenberg1 /><ref>{{cite web|title=Abraham Lincoln High School|website=New York City Department of Education|url=https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/K410|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref> and [[Rachel Carson High School for Coastal Studies]].<ref name=\"Lucadamo\">\"[http://articles.nydailynews.com/2006-05-03/local/18332169_1_teachers-students-troubled-school Teachers Boycott Hs To Protest An Arrest].\" ''[[New York Daily News]]''. May 3, 2007. Retrieved on October 11, 2012.</ref>\n\n=== Public library ===\n[[File:CI BPL 1901 Mermaid Av jeh.jpg|thumb|Coney Island library branch]]\nThe [[Brooklyn Public Library]] (BPL)'s Coney Island branch is located at 1901 Mermaid Avenue, near the intersection with West 19th Street. It opened in 1911 as an unmanned deposit station. Ten years later, it moved to the former ''[[Coney Island Times]]'' offices and became fully staffed. In 1954 another branch was built. According to BPL's website, the library was referred to as \"the first-ever library built on stilts over the Atlantic Ocean.\" The branch was rebuilt in 2013 after being damaged in Hurricane Sandy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bklynlibrary.org/locations/coney-island/history|title=Coney Island Library|last=|first=|date=August 19, 2011|website=Brooklyn Public Library|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Transportation ==\n[[File:Coney IslandStillwell.JPG|thumb|left|[[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue station]]]]\nConey Island is served by four [[New York City Subway]] stations.<ref>{{NYCS const|map}}</ref><ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\">{{cite NYCS map|neighborhood|Coney Island}}</ref> The [[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue station]], the terminal of the {{NYCS trains|Stillwell}}, is one of the largest elevated rapid transit stations in the world, with eight tracks serving four platforms.<ref name=\"MTA-Stillwell-2014\" /> The entire station, built in 1917\u20131920 as a replacement for the former surface-level [[Culver Depot]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thethirdrail.net./0305/stillwell4.html|title=The New BMT Coney Island Terminal|last=Matus|first=Paul|date=May 2003|website=thethirdrail.net|page=4|access-date=August 15, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303172251/http://thethirdrail.net/0305/stillwell4.html|archive-date=March 3, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> was rebuilt in 2001\u20132004.<ref name=\"Chan\" /><ref name=\"MTA-Stillwell-2014\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/news/2014/05/20/stillwell-terminal-remains-sparkling-jewel-decade-after-full-rehabilitation|title=Stillwell Terminal Remains a Sparkling Jewel a Decade after Full Rehabilitation|last=|first=|date=May 20, 2014|website=www.mta.info|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|access-date=August 15, 2016}}</ref> The other subway stations within Coney Island are {{stn|West Eighth Street\u2013New York Aquarium}}, served by the {{NYCS trains|West 8th|time=nolink}}; {{stn|Neptune Avenue}}, served by the {{NYCS trains|Culver IND south|time=nolink}}; and {{stn|Ocean Parkway}}, served by the {{NYCS trains|Brighton south|time=nolink}}.<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n\nA [[Bus station|bus terminal]] beneath the Stillwell Avenue station serves the {{NYC bus link|B68}} to [[Prospect Park (Brooklyn)|Prospect Park]], the {{NYC bus link|B74}} to Sea Gate, the {{NYC bus link|B64}} to [[Bay Ridge, Brooklyn|Bay Ridge]], and the {{NYC bus link|B82}} to [[Starrett City, Brooklyn|Starrett City]]. Additionally, the {{NYC bus link|B36}} runs from Sea Gate to [[Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn|Sheepshead Bay]]. The {{NYC bus link|X28|X38|prose=y}} provide express bus service to Manhattan.<ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n\nThe three main west-east arteries in the neighborhood are Neptune Avenue, Mermaid Avenue, and Surf Avenue from north to south. Neptune Avenue becomes Emmons Avenue at Sheepshead Bay, while Surf Avenue becomes [[Ocean Parkway (Brooklyn)|Ocean Parkway]] and then runs north toward Prospect Park. The north-south cross streets in Coney Island are numbered, with \"West\" prepended to their numbers. The street numbers run from West 1st Street at Coney Island's eastern border to West 37th Street at the western border, adjacent to Sea Gate.<ref>{{Google maps|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Coney+Island,+Brooklyn,+NY/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x89c24448979d75cb:0x54745adc3c8f1179?sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjk652izLDcAhVhiOAKHVPCClYQ8gEI9QEwFg|title=Coney Island, Brooklyn, NY|access-date=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nConey Island contains several [[Cycling in New York City|bicycle paths]]. The Ocean Parkway bicycle path terminates in the neighborhood, while the [[Shore Parkway]] bike path (part of the [[Brooklyn Waterfront Greenway]]) runs east along [[Jamaica Bay]] and west and north along New York Harbor. On-street bike lanes are marked in Neptune Avenue and other streets in Coney Island. In addition, the Riegelmann Boardwalk is open to cyclists during the daytime, though bicycling hours are restricted during summers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bicycle Maps|website=NYC.gov|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/bikemap-2018.pdf|publisher=[[New York City Department of Transportation]]|date=2018|access-date=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe western part of Coney Island is expected to be served by [[NYC Ferry]]'s Coney Island route beginning in 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amny.com/transit/nyc-ferry-routes-1.25782023|title=NYC Ferry is adding 2 new routes|date=January 10, 2019|website=am New York|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ny.curbed.com/2019/1/10/18177078/nyc-ferry-transportation-staten-island-coney-island|title=NYC Ferry will launch service to Staten Island, Coney Island|last=Plitt|first=Amy|date=January 10, 2019|website=Curbed NY|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NYC Ferry Expansion 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ferry.nyc/nycferry-2020-2021-service-route-expansion/|title=2020-2021 Expansion|website=New York City Ferry Service|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n{{Main|Coney Island in popular culture}}\nConey Island has been featured in many novels, films, television shows, cartoons, and theatrical plays.<ref name=\"Immerso2002\">{{cite book|last=Immerso|first=Michael|title=Coney Island: the people's playground|publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=2002|edition=illustrated|isbn=978-0-8135-3138-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i4POVzmwY9cC}}</ref>{{rp|176}}<ref name=\"Rabinovitz 2004\">{{cite book|last=Rabinovitz|first=Lauren|title=American cinema's transitional era: audiences, institutions, practices|editor=Charlie Keil, Shelley Stamp|publisher=University of California Press|year=2004|edition=illustrated|chapter=The Coney Island Comedies|isbn=978-0-520-24027-8|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cB2MfzmdwYkC&pg=RA1-PA171#v=onepage&q=&f=false}}</ref> This is linked to its iconic status as a vacation destination.<ref>{{cite book | last=Frank | first=R.J. | author2=Wadsworth Atheneum Museum of Art | author3=San Diego Museum of Art | author4=Brooklyn Museum | author5=McNay Art Museum | title=Coney Island: Visions of an American Dreamland, 1861\u20132008 | publisher=Wadsworth Atheneum Museum of Art | year=2015 | isbn=978-0-300-18990-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pt22oQEACAAJ | access-date=February 28, 2019 | page=}}</ref> Various [[slapstick]] comedies and films have been set at Coney Island or allude to it. There have also been several television documentaries about the area's history.<ref name=\"Rabinovitz 2004\" />{{rp|137\u2013142}}<ref>{{cite web | title=Movie Shot at Coney Island List | website=Westland | date=July 10, 2006 | url=https://www.westland.net/coneyisland/articles/movielist.htm | access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* [[Rem Koolhaas]], ''[[Delirious New York: A Retroactive Manifesto for Manhattan]]'' (Academy Editions, London, 1978; republished, The Monacelli Press, 1994&nbsp;\u2014 a large part of the book focuses on Coney Island amusement parks)\n* John F. Kasson, ''Amusing The Million: Coney Island at the Turn of the Century'' (Hill and Wang, New York, 1978; Distributed in Canada by Douglas and McIntyre Ltd.)\n* Charles Denson, ''Coney Island: Lost and Found (Ten Speed Press, 2002)\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/coney Coney Island], a 1991 documentary film by [[Ric Burns]] for [[American Experience]]\n* {{Cite book|publisher=E. Leypoldt |location = New York|title=Percy's Pocket dictionary of Coney Island|author=Townsend Percy |date = 1880|oclc=5926329|ol = 6906857M}}\n* {{Cite book|publisher=Austin Publishing Co. |location = New York|title=The tourists companion and guide to Coney Island, Fort Hamilton, Bath Beach, Sheepshead Bay, Rockaway Beach and Far Rockaway|author=J. Perkins Tracy |date = 1887|ol = 23411073M}}\n{{refend}}\n\n=== Further reading ===\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* [http://www.heartofconeyisland.com/ The Comprehensive History of Coney Island] at Heart of Coney Island\n* Coney Island [http://www.westland.net/coneyisland/histart.htm History Articles]\n* [http://www.indypendent.org/?p=449 Bland as Sand: Developers Stalk Coney Island], The Indypendent\n* [http://www.indypendent.org/?p=450 Gritty and Trashy... That\u2019s Why I Love It], The Indypendent\n* Bruce, Jeannette. [https://archive.is/20130102055107/http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1080222/index.htm \"Where The Fun Was,\"]''Sports Illustrated'', August 28, 1967\n* Coney Island [http://www.coneyislandhistory.org/ History Project]\n* {{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Coney Island |volume=6 |page=897 |short=1}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikivoyage|Brooklyn/Coney Island and Brighton Beach}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|Coney Island, Brooklyn}}\n* [http://cityinenvironment.blogspot.com/2013/03/evolution-coney-island.html City in Environment \u2013 Evolution Coney Island]\n* [http://newyork.thecityatlas.org/lifestyle/future-southern-brooklyn-including-coney-island/ The future of Southern Brooklyn, including Coney Island \u2013 newyork.thecityatlas.org]\n\n{{Coney Island}}\n{{Brooklyn}}\n{{Portal bar|New York (state)|New York City}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Coney Island| ]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Barrier islands of New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Islands of Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Former islands of New York City]]\n[[Category:Seaside resorts in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Islands of New York City]]\n[[Category:Dutch place names in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Epicgenius", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eName:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coney_Island"}
