{"title_page": "Joseph Geierman", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician}}\n'''Joseph Geierman''' is the current [[Mayor]] of [[Doraville, Georgia]] and a director at the law firm [[Troutman Sanders]]. Geierman began his term in 2020 after previously serving as a member of Doraville City Council. Geierman is the first openly [[LGBT]] Mayor of Doraville and the second openly LGBT mayor in Georgia.\n\n== Education ==\nGeierman received a [[B.A.]] from the [[University of California, Santa Cruz]] in 1998 and an [[M.S.]] in Building Construction and Facilities Management from [[Georgia Tech]] in 2009.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.troutman.com/professionals/joseph-geierman.html|title=Joseph Geierman|last=|first=|date=|website=Troutman Sanders|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 2009, Geierman began working at the Atlanta-based law firm [[Troutman Sanders]], where he now serves as Director of Real Estate and Facilities. There, he \"manages leasing, real estate-related capital projects, and facilities-related contracts and operating budgets for the firm.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2017, Geierman was elected to a four-year term on the Doraville City Council.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2019, he gave up his seat in order to run for Mayor of Doraville.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Saunders|first=Patrick|url=https://www.projectq.us/atlanta/gay_councilmember_jumps_into_race_for_doraville_mayor|title=Gay councilmember jumps into race for Doraville mayor|date=July 29, 2019|work=Project Q|access-date=April 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the November 2019 [[general election]] for Mayor of Doraville, Geierman did not get the 50% of votes needed to unseat an incumbent.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Robins|first=Taylor|url=http://thechampionnewspaper.com/news/local/pittman-geierman-head-to-run-off/|title=Pittman, Geierman head to run off|date=November 6, 2019|work=The Champion|access-date=April 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Wheeler|first=Candace|url=https://www.wabe.org/episode/closer-look-doraville-mayor-candidate-discusses-his-vision-for-the-city-sesame-street-addresses-parental-addiction-celebrates-50th-anniversary-musicians-pay-tribute-to-mr-rogers/|title=Closer Look: Doraville Mayor Candidate Discusses His Vision For The City; Sesame Street Addresses Parental Addiction, Celebrates 50th Anniversary; Musicians Pay Tribute To Mr. Rogers|date=November 18, 2019|work=WABE|access-date=April 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He went on to defeat the incumbent Mayor Donna Pittman in an [[run-off election]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Robins|first=Taylor|url=http://thechampionnewspaper.com/news/local/theres-a-new-mayor-in-town/|title=There\u2019s a new mayor in town|date=December 5, 2019|work=The Champion|access-date=April 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Geierman became the first openly LBGT Mayor of Doraville and the second openly LGBT mayor in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Saunders|first=Patrick|url=https://www.projectq.us/atlanta/doraville_elects_first_openly_lgbtq_mayor_in_blowout|title=Doraville elects its first openly LGBTQ mayor in blowout|date=December 4, 2019|work=Project Q|access-date=April 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 6, 2020, Geierman was sworn into office as Mayor of Doraville.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Love|first=Juanita|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local/doraville-officials-sworn/1JouY8ccjlcuwrosayhXHL/|title=Doraville officials to be sworn in|date=December 20, 2019|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=April 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Fonville|first=Christine|url=https://www.mdjonline.com/neighbor_newspapers/dekalb/new-mayor-sets-sight-on-unlocking-doraville-s-potential-and/article_c1f5a0a0-32f7-11ea-9412-77d124fe2e69.html|title=New mayor sets sight on unlocking Doraville's potential and civic engagement|date=January 9, 2020|work=DeKalb Neighbor|access-date=April 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Geierman's current term will end on December 31, 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.doravillega.us/departments/mayor_and_council/index.php|title=Mayor and City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=The City of Doraville|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nGeierman is married to his husband, B.J. Abbott.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Doraville, Georgia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician}}\n'''Joseph Geierman''' is the current [[Mayor]] of [[Doraville, Georgia]] and a director at the law firm [[Troutman Sanders]]. Geierman began his term in 2020 after previously serving as a member of Doraville City Council. Geierman is the first openly [[LGBT]] Mayor of Doraville and the second openly LGBT mayor in Georgia.\n\n== Education ==\nGeierman recieved a [[B.A.]] from the [[University of California, Santa Cruz]] in 1998 and an [[M.S.]] in Building Construction and Facilities Management from [[Georgia Tech]] in 2009.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.troutman.com/professionals/joseph-geierman.html|title=Joseph Geierman|last=|first=|date=|website=Troutman Sanders|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 2009, Geierman began working at the Atlanta-based law firm [[Troutman Sanders]], where he now serves as Director of Real Estate and Facilities. There, he \"manages leasing, real estate-related capital projects, and facilities-related contracts and operating budgets for the firm.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2017, Geierman was elected to a four-year term on the Doraville City Council.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2019, he gave up his seat in order to run for Mayor of Doraville.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Saunders|first=Patrick|url=https://www.projectq.us/atlanta/gay_councilmember_jumps_into_race_for_doraville_mayor|title=Gay councilmemb