==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young, B}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English people of Cypriot descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:People from the London Borough of Hackney]]\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n\n\n{{UK-singer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "91.125.87.104", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B_Young"}
{"title_page": "Khatri", "text_new": "{{short description|Punjabi trading caste in the Indian subcontinent}}\n{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{infobox caste\n|caste_name    = Khatri\n|image         = A Khattri nobleman, in 'Kitab-i tasrih al-aqvam' by Col. James Skinner, aka Sikandar (1778-1841).jpg\n|caption       = A Khattri nobleman, in ''Kitab-i tasrih al-aqvam'' by [[James Skinner (soldier)|Col. James Skinner]], aka Sikandar (1778\u20131841)\n|religions     = [[Hinduism]], [[Sikhism]] and [[Islam]]\n|languages     = [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]], [[Hindi]], [[Urdu]],<ref>{{cite book |author=Christine Everaert|title=Tracing the Boundaries Between Hindi and Urdu: Lost and Added in Translation Between 20th Century Short Stories|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LqZ-6QRKc7wC&pg=PA259|year=1996 |publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004177314|pages=259}}</ref> [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]]<ref>{{cite book |author=K.S. Singh|title=People of India: A - G., Volume 4|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jHQMAQAAMAAJ&q=brahman-khatri|publisher=Oxford University. Press |year=1998|isbn=978-0-19563-354-2|page=3285}}</ref>\n|country       = Primarily India and Pakistan\n|region        = [[Punjab]], [[Sindh]], [[Delhi]],<ref>{{cite book |author=A. H. Advani|title=The India Magazine of Her People and Culture, Volume 16|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cAluAAAAMAAJ&q=khatris+delhi|year=1995|publisher=the University of Michigan|pages=56\u201358}}</ref> [[Haryana]],<ref>{{cite book |author=Kiran Prem|title=Haryana District Gazetteers: Ambala|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IFXRAAAAMAAJ&dq=khatris|year=1970|publisher=Haryana Gazetteers Organization|page=42}}</ref> [[Gujarat]]<ref>{{cite book |first=Satish Chandra |last=Misra|title=Muslim communities in Gujarat: preliminary studies in their history and social organization|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H1k1AQAAIAAJ&dq=khatris|year=1964|publisher=Asia Pub. House|page=97}}</ref>\n|population=\n}}\n\n'''Khatri''' is a predominantly Hindu [[caste]] of northern India and Pakistan, mostly from the [[Punjab region]], that provided many significant figures in Sikhism, including all of the [[Sikh Gurus]].\n\nthey also played an important role in India's trans-regional trade during the Mughal era, when they also adopted administrative and military roles outside the Punjab region.\n\n==History==\nAccording to ''[[Bichitra Natak]]'', said to be the autobiography of the last Sikh Guru, [[Gobind Singh]],<ref>Different approaches to Bachitar Natak, Journal of Sikh studies, Surjit Singh Hans, Volume 10, 66-78, Guru Nanak University.</ref><ref>The Sikh Struggle in the Eighteenth Century and Its Relevance for Today, W. H. McLeod, History of Religions, Vol. 31, No. 4, Sikh Studies (May 1992), pp. 344-362, The University of Chicago Press/ quote: \"Although Bachitar Natak is traditionally attributed to Guru Gobind Singh, there is a strong case to be made for regarding it as the work of one of his followers...\"</ref><ref>Dasam Granth: A historical study, Sikh Review, 42(8), Aug 1994, 9-20</ref> the Bedi sub-caste of the Khatris derives its lineage from [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kush]], the son of [[Rama]] (according to Hindu epic ''[[Ramayana]]''). The descendants of Kush, according to the disputed Bachitar Natak legend, learned the [[Vedas]] at [[Benares]], and were thus called Bedis (Vedis).<ref>{{cite book |title=Glimpses of Sikhism |author= Major Nahar Singh Jawandha |isbn=978-93-8021-325-5 |page=16 |publisher=Sanbun|year= 2010 }}</ref> Similarly, according to the same legend, the [[Sodhi]] sub-caste claims descent from [[Lava (Ramayana)|Lav]], the other son of Rama.<ref name=\"Bichitra\">The Cosmic Drama: Bichitra Natak, Author Gobind Singh, Publisher Himalayan International Institute of Yoga Science and Philosophy of the U.S.A., 1989 {{ISBN|0-89389-116-9}}, {{ISBN|978-0-89389-116-9}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Ancient Greek]] sources, \"The people that held the territory comprised between the [[Ravi River|Hydrastes]] ([[Ravi River|Ravi]]) and the [[Beas River|Hyphasis]] ([[Beas River|Beas]]) were the ''Khatriaioi'', whose capital was Sangala\". [[Sangala]] find mention in ''[[Mahabharata]]'' and Pali Buddhist texts as the capital of [[Madra Kingdom]]. [[J. W. McCrindle]], the translator and writer adds that the name is found in the modern era, spread across a vast region in the northwest of India, from Hindukush to Bengal and from Nepal to Gujarat, in slightly variant forms, including the term ''Khatris'' and others.<ref>{{Cite book|last=John Watson McCrindle|url=https://archive.org/details/ancientindiaasd00mccrgoog|title=Ancient India as Described by Ptolemy: Being a Translation of the Chapters ...|date=1885|publisher=Tr\u00fcbner|others=Oxford University|page=[https://archive.org/details/ancientindiaasd00mccrgoog/page/n174 157]|language=English}}</ref>\n\nHaving gained the patronage of Mughal nobles, the Khatris then adopted administrative and military roles outside the Punjab region. According to a Khatri legend of the 19th century, they continued their military service until the time of the Mughal emperor Aurangzeb, when the death of many of their number during the emperor's Deccan Campaign caused him to order their [[Women in Hinduism#Widowhood and remarriage|widows to be remarried]]. The order was made out of sympathy for the widows but when the Khatri community leaders refused to obey it, Aurangzeb terminated their military service and said that they should be shopkeepers and brokers. This legend is probably fanciful: John McLane notes that a more likely explanation for their revised position was that a Sikh rebellion against the Mughals in the early 1700s severely compromised the Khatri's ability to trade and forced them to take sides. Those who were primarily dependent on the Mughals went to significant lengths to assert that allegiance in the face of accusations that they were in fact favouring the rebel [[Jat Sikh]]s, led by [[Banda Singh Bahadur|Banda]]. The outcome of their assertions - which included providing financial support to the Mughals and shaving their beards - was that the Khatris became still more important to the Mughal rulers as administrators at various levels, in particular because of their skills in financial management and their historic connections with bankers.<ref>{{cite book |title=Land and Local Kingship in Eighteenth-Century Bengal |first=John R. |last=McLane |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=YH6ijJnUPmcC&pg=PA132 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2002 |isbn=978-0-521-52654-8 |pages=132\u2013133}}</ref>\n\nAuthor Suresh Kumar described Khatris as silk weavers.<ref>{{Cite book|editor1-first=Kumar Suresh |editor1-last=Singh |editor1-link=Kumar Suresh Singh |year=1998|title=India's Communities |volume=2 H\u2013M |publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New Delhi, India|pages=1722, 1729|isbn=978-0-19-563354-2}}</ref> Author Purnima Dhawan described that together with [[Jat people|Jat]] community, the Khatris gained considerably from the expansion of the Mughal empire, although both groups supported [[Guru Hargobind]] in his campaign for Sikh self-government in the Punjab plains.<ref>{{cite book |title=When Sparrows Became Hawks: The Making of the Sikh Warrior Tradition, 1699-1799 |first=Purnima |last=Dhavan |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-19987-717-1 |pages=3, 30\u201331 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q0ZpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA31}}</ref> The khatris played an important role in India's trans-regional trade during the period,<ref>{{cite book |title=Global Indian diasporas |first=Gijsbert |last=Oonk |publisher=Amsterdam University Press |year=2007 |page=43 |isbn=978-90-5356-035-8}}</ref> being described by Scott Cameron Levi as among the \"most important merchant communities of early modern India.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=The Indian Diaspora in Central Asia and Its Trade, 1550\u20131900 |first=Scott Cameron |last=Levi |publisher=BRILL |location=Leiden |year=2002 |isbn=978-90-04-12320-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9qVkNBge8mIC}}</ref>\n\n==Origin==\nKhatris consider themselves to be of pure [[Vedic]] descent and thus superior to the [[Rajput]]s who, like them, claim the [[Kshatriya]] status of the Hindu [[Varna (Hinduism)|varna system]].<ref name=\"syan\">{{cite book |last=Syan |first=Hardip Singh |year=2013 |title=Sikh Militancy in the Seventeenth Century: Religious Violence in Mughal and Early Modern India |publisher=I. B. Tauris |isbn=978-1-78076-250-0 |pages=35, 39 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9RzzxcEL4C0C&pg=PA35}}</ref> The Khatri's standards of literacy and caste status were such during the early years of [[Sikh]]ism that, according to [[W. H. McLeod]], they dominated it.<ref name=\"syan\"/> Author McLeod mentions the employment of khatris as soldiers by Mughal emperors but notes by the time of [[Company rule in India|British arrival]] in India they were mostly merchants and scribes<ref>{{cite book |title=The A to Z of Sikhism |first=W. H. |last=McLeod |authorlink=W. H. McLeod |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-8108-6828-1 |page=115}}</ref> Kenneth W. Jones says \"the Khatris claimed with some justice and increasing insistence, the status of Rajputs, or Kshatriyas, a claim not granted by those above but illustrative of their ambiguous position on the great varna scale of class divisions\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Arya dharm: Hindu consciousness in 19th-century Punjab |first=Kenneth W. |last=Jones |publisher=[[University of California Press]] |year=1976 |isbn=978-0-520-02920-0 |pages=4\u20135 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/americocastromea0000unse }}</ref> Purnima Dhavan sees the claim as originating from a conflation of the words ''khatri'' and ''kshatriya'', which are phonetically similar.<ref name=\"dhavan\"/> In the 19th-century British administrators failed to agree whether the Khatri claim of Kshatriya status should be accepted, since the overwhelming majority of them were engaged in ''Vaishya'' (mercantile) occupation rather than in ''Kshatriya'' (military) pursuits.<ref>{{cite book |title=Land and Local Kingship in Eighteenth-Century Bengal |first=John R. |last=McLane |publisher=Cambridge University Press |page=131 |year=2002 |isbn=978-0-521-52654-8 |quote=The Khatris were a Punjabi mercantile caste who claimed to be Kshatriyas. Nineteenth-century Indians and British administrators failed to agree whether that claim should be accepted. The fact that overwhelming majority were engaged in Vaishya (mercantile), not Kshatriya (military), pursuits was balanced against the Khatri origin myths...}}</ref> [[Dasharatha Sharma]] described Khatris as a mixed ''pratiloma'' caste of low ritual status but suggested that they could be a mixed caste born of Kshatriya fathers and [[Brahmin]] mothers.<ref>{{cite book |title=Early Chauh\u0101n dynasties: a study of Chauh\u0101n political history, Chauh\u0101n political institutions, and life in the Chauh\u0101n dominions, from 800 to 1316 A.D. |first=Dasharatha |last=Sharma |authorlink=Dasharatha Sharma |page=279 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |year=1975}}</ref>\n\nThe Khatris of Gujarat and Rajasthan are said to have tailoring skills like \"Darji\" (tailor) caste.<ref>Indian settlers: the story of a New Zealand South Asian community, p48, Jacqueline Leckie, Otago University Press, 2000/ quote :\"Tailoring was a caste occupation that continued in New Zealand by those from Darji and Khatri castes who had been trained in appropriate skills. Bhukandas Masters, a Khatri, emigrated to New Zealand in 1919. He practised as tailor in central Auckland...\"</ref> In the case of those Khatris who avow Sikism, their Kshatriya claim reflects the confusing, even seemingly contradictory, attitude towards the traditional Hindu caste system that is evident in Sikh texts such as the ''[[Guru Granth Sahib]]'', which on the one hand renounces the Hindu caste paradigm and on the other seeks to portray the gurus as a group of warrior-defenders of their faith, just as with the Kshatriya varna.<ref name=\"dhavan\">{{cite book |title=When Sparrows Became Hawks: The Making of the Sikh Warrior Tradition, 1699-1799 |first=Purnima |last=Dhavan |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-19987-717-1 |pages=36\u201337 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q0ZpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA36}}</ref>\n\n==Religion==\n===Hindu Khatris===\nThe vast majority of Khatris are Hindu.<ref>{{cite report |author= Gopal Krishan|date= |title= Demography of the Punjab (1849-1947)|url= http://www.global.ucsb.edu/punjab/sites/secure.lsit.ucsb.edu.gisp.d7_sp/files/sitefiles/journals/volume11/no1/6_krishan.pdf|publisher= UCSB|page= 83|access-date= 24 September 2018|quote= \"Conversion was negligible from the higher castes such as Brahmins, Aroras, Khatris and Aggarwals.\"}}</ref> Most Hindu Khatris migrated to India after partition and settled in urban areas across India. They were estimated to constitute 9% of the total population of Delhi in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.india-seminar.com/2004/534/534%20sanjay%20kumar.htm|title=534 Sanjay Kumar, A tale of three cities|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Sikh Khatris===\nAll the ten Sikh Gurus were Khatris:<ref>{{cite book |title=The Encyclopedia of Sikhism |first=H. S. |last=Singha |page=125 |isbn=978-81-7010-301-1 |publisher=Hemkunt Press |year=2000 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gqIbJz7vMn0C&pg=PA125}}</ref> [[Guru Nanak]] was a Bedi, [[Guru Angad]] was a Trehan, [[Guru Amar Das]] was a Bhalla, and the remainder were [[Sodhi]]s.<ref>{{cite book |title=The A to Z of Sikhism |first=W. H. |last=McLeod |authorlink=W. H. McLeod |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-8108-6828-1 |page=86}}</ref> During the lifetime of the Gurus, most of their major supporters were Khatris. A list of these is provided by a contemporary of the Sikh Gurus, [[Bhai Gurdas]], in his ''[[Varan Bhai Gurdas]]''.<ref>Bhai Gurdas ''Ji'', Varan Bhai Gurdas Ji, Vaar 8&nbsp;\u2013 Pauri 10.</ref>{{qn|date=February 2019}} However, many of the more successful Khatri traders opposed the strictures of the [[Khalsa]] movement, introduced by [[Guru Gobind Singh]] to end the concept of caste in Sikhism by removing traditional rituals and identities.<ref>{{cite book |title=When Sparrows Became Hawks: The Making of the Sikh Warrior Tradition, 1699-1799 |first=Purnima |last=Dhavan |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-19987-717-1 |pages=42, 47, 184 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q0ZpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA42}}</ref>\n\nAside from the gurus, other Khatris influential in the history of Sikhism include:\n\n* [[Bhai Daya Singh]], the first of the [[Panj Pyare]] (the initial members of the [[Khalsa]]), belonged to the Sobti clan of the Khatris.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Sikhs in history: a millenium study, with new afterwords |author=Sangat Singh |publisher=Uncommon Books |year=2001 |isbn=978-81-900650-2-3 |page=71}}</ref>\n* [[Hari Singh Nalwa]] (1791\u20131837), the Commander-in-chief of the Khalsa army of the Sikh Empire.\n* [[Dewan Mokham Chand]] Nayyar(- 1814), the Commander-in-chief of the Khalsa army of the Sikh Empire\n* [[Diwan Mulraj Chopra]] (1814 - 11 August 1851) was the Diwan of Multan and leader of a Sikh rebellion against the British which led to the Second Anglo-Sikh War.\n\n===Punjabi Khatris post-Independence===\nD.L.Sheth, the former director of the [[Centre for the Study of Developing Societies|Center for the Study of Developing Societies in India(CSDS)]], lists Indian upper castes that constituted the middle class and were traditionally \"[[Urban area|urban]] and [[professional]]\" (following professions like doctors, lawyers, teachers, engineers, etc.) immediately after Independence in 1947. This list included the Khatris from Punjab, [[Kashmiri Pandits]], [[Nagar Brahmin]] and the South Indian Brahmins; [[Chitpawan]]s and CKPs([[Chandraseniya Kayastha Prabhu]]s) from Maharashtra; [[Kayastha]]s from northern India; the Probasi and the [[Bhadralok]] [[Bengalis]], the [[Parsis]] and the upper crusts of Muslim and Christian communities. According to P.K.Verma, \"Education was a common thread that bound together this pan Indian elite\" and almost all the members of these communities could read and write English and were educated beyond school.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Great Indian Middle class|page=28|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pbgMy8KfD74C&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=false|author=Pavan K. Varma|publisher=Penguin Books|quote=...its main adherents came from those in government service, qualified '''professionals''' such as doctors,engineers and lawyers,business entrepreneurs,teachers in schools in the bigger cities and in the institutes of higher education, journalists[etc]...The upper castes dominated the Indian middle class. Prominent among its members were Punjabi Khatris, Kashmiri Pandits and South Indian brahmins. Then there were the 'traditional urban-oriented professional castes such as the Nagars of Gujarat, the Chitpawans and the Ckps (Chandrasenya Kayastha Prabhus)s of Maharashtra and the Kayasthas of North India. Also included were the old elite groups that emerged during the colonial rule: the Probasi and the Bhadralok Bengalis, the Parsis and the upper crusts of Muslim and Christian communities. Education was a common thread that bound together this pan Indian elite...But almost all its members spoke and wrote English and had had some education beyond school|isbn=9780143103257|year=2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Social Action, Volume 50|publisher=Indian Social Institute|year=2000|page=72}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csds.in/d_l_sheth|title=D.L. Sheth}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Khatris]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{Ethnic groups, tribes and clans of the Punjab}}\n\n[[Category:Social groups of Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Punjab, Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Punjabi tribes|*]]\n[[Category:Merchant castes]]\n[[Category:Hindu communities]]\n[[Category:Sikh communities]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Punjabi trading caste in the Indian subcontinent}}\n{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{infobox caste\n|caste_name    = Khatri\n|image         = A Khattri nobleman, in 'Kitab-i tasrih al-aqvam' by Col. James Skinner, aka Sikandar (1778-1841).jpg\n|caption       = A Khattri nobleman, in ''Kitab-i tasrih al-aqvam'' by [[James Skinner (soldier)|Col. James Skinner]], aka Sikandar (1778\u20131841)\n|religions     = [[Hinduism]], [[Sikhism]] and [[Islam]]\n|languages     = [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]], [[Hindi]], [[Urdu]],<ref>{{cite book |author=Christine Everaert|title=Tracing the Boundaries Between Hindi and Urdu: Lost and Added in Translation Between 20th Century Short Stories|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LqZ-6QRKc7wC&pg=PA259|year=1996 |publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004177314|pages=259}}</ref> [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]]<ref>{{cite book |author=K.S. Singh|title=People of India: A - G., Volume 4|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jHQMAQAAMAAJ&q=brahman-khatri|publisher=Oxford University. Press |year=1998|isbn=978-0-19563-354-2|page=3285}}</ref>\n|country       = Primarily India and Pakistan\n|region        = [[Punjab]], [[Sindh]], [[Delhi]],<ref>{{cite book |author=A. H. Advani|title=The India Magazine of Her People and Culture, Volume 16|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cAluAAAAMAAJ&q=khatris+delhi|year=1995|publisher=the University of Michigan|pages=56\u201358}}</ref> [[Haryana]],<ref>{{cite book |author=Kiran Prem|title=Haryana District Gazetteers: Ambala|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IFXRAAAAMAAJ&dq=khatris|year=1970|publisher=Haryana Gazetteers Organization|page=42}}</ref> [[Gujarat]]<ref>{{cite book |first=Satish Chandra |last=Misra|title=Muslim communities in Gujarat: preliminary studies in their history and social organization|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H1k1AQAAIAAJ&dq=khatris|year=1964|publisher=Asia Pub. House|page=97}}</ref>\n|population=\n}}\n\n'''Khatri''' is a predominantly Hindu [[caste]] of northern India and Pakistan, mostly from the [[Punjab region]], that provided many significant figures in Sikhism, including all of the [[Sikh Gurus]].\n\nThe ancestral occupation of the Khatris is weaving [[silk]]<ref name=\"Levi2016\">{{cite book|author=Scott Levi|title=Caravans: Punjabi Khatri Merchants on the Silk Road|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-uviBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT38|date=15 January 2016|publisher=Penguin Books Limited|isbn=978-93-5118-916-9|pages=38\u2013}}</ref> and they also played an important role in India's trans-regional trade during the Mughal era, when they also adopted administrative roles outside the Punjab region.\n\n==History==\nAccording to ''[[Bichitra Natak]]'', said to be the autobiography of the last Sikh Guru, [[Gobind Singh]],<ref>Different approaches to Bachitar Natak, Journal of Sikh studies, Surjit Singh Hans, Volume 10, 66-78, Guru Nanak University.</ref><ref>The Sikh Struggle in the Eighteenth Century and Its Relevance for Today, W. H. McLeod, History of Religions, Vol. 31, No. 4, Sikh Studies (May 1992), pp. 344-362, The University of Chicago Press/ quote: \"Although Bachitar Natak is traditionally attributed to Guru Gobind Singh, there is a strong case to be made for regarding it as the work of one of his followers...\"</ref><ref>Dasam Granth: A historical study, Sikh Review, 42(8), Aug 1994, 9-20</ref> the Bedi sub-caste of the Khatris derives its lineage from [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kush]], the son of [[Rama]] (according to Hindu epic ''[[Ramayana]]''). The descendants of Kush, according to the disputed Bachitar Natak legend, learned the [[Vedas]] at [[Benares]], and were thus called Bedis (Vedis).<ref>{{cite book |title=Glimpses of Sikhism |author= Major Nahar Singh Jawandha |isbn=978-93-8021-325-5 |page=16 |publisher=Sanbun|year= 2010 }}</ref> Similarly, according to the same legend, the [[Sodhi]] sub-caste claims descent from [[Lava (Ramayana)|Lav]], the other son of Rama.<ref name=\"Bichitra\">The Cosmic Drama: Bichitra Natak, Author Gobind Singh, Publisher Himalayan International Institute of Yoga Science and Philosophy of the U.S.A., 1989 {{ISBN|0-89389-116-9}}, {{ISBN|978-0-89389-116-9}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Ancient Greek]] sources, \"The people that held the territory comprised between the [[Ravi River|Hydrastes]] ([[Ravi River|Ravi]]) and the [[Beas River|Hyphasis]] ([[Beas River|Beas]]) were the ''Khatriaioi'', whose capital was Sangala\". [[Sangala]] find mention in ''[[Mahabharata]]'' and Pali Buddhist texts as the capital of [[Madra Kingdom]]. [[J. W. McCrindle]], the translator and writer adds that the name is found in the modern era, spread across a vast region in the northwest of India, from Hindukush to Bengal and from Nepal to Gujarat, in slightly variant forms, including the term ''Khatris'' and others.<ref>{{Cite book|last=John Watson McCrindle|url=https://archive.org/details/ancientindiaasd00mccrgoog|title=Ancient India as Described by Ptolemy: Being a Translation of the Chapters ...|date=1885|publisher=Tr\u00fcbner|others=Oxford University|page=[https://archive.org/details/ancientindiaasd00mccrgoog/page/n174 157]|language=English}}</ref>\n\nHaving gained the patronage of Mughal nobles, the Khatris then adopted administrative and military roles outside the Punjab region. According to a Khatri legend of the 19th century, they continued their military service until the time of the Mughal emperor Aurangzeb, when the death of many of their number during the emperor's Deccan Campaign caused him to order their [[Women in Hinduism#Widowhood and remarriage|widows to be remarried]]. The order was made out of sympathy for the widows but when the Khatri community leaders refused to obey it, Aurangzeb terminated their military service and said that they should be shopkeepers and brokers. This legend is probably fanciful: John McLane notes that a more likely explanation for their revised position was that a Sikh rebellion against the Mughals in the early 1700s severely compromised the Khatri's ability to trade and forced them to take sides. Those who were primarily dependent on the Mughals went to significant lengths to assert that allegiance in the face of accusations that they were in fact favouring the rebel [[Jat Sikh]]s, led by [[Banda Singh Bahadur|Banda]]. The outcome of their assertions - which included providing financial support to the Mughals and shaving their beards - was that the Khatris became still more important to the Mughal rulers as administrators at various levels, in particular because of their skills in financial management and their historic connections with bankers.<ref>{{cite book |title=Land and Local Kingship in Eighteenth-Century Bengal |first=John R. |last=McLane |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=YH6ijJnUPmcC&pg=PA132 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2002 |isbn=978-0-521-52654-8 |pages=132\u2013133}}</ref>\n\nAuthor Suresh Kumar described Khatris as silk weavers.<ref>{{Cite book|editor1-first=Kumar Suresh |editor1-last=Singh |editor1-link=Kumar Suresh Singh |year=1998|title=India's Communities |volume=2 H\u2013M |publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New Delhi, India|pages=1722, 1729|isbn=978-0-19-563354-2}}</ref> Author Purnima Dhawan described that together with [[Jat people|Jat]] community, the Khatris gained considerably from the expansion of the Mughal empire, although both groups supported [[Guru Hargobind]] in his campaign for Sikh self-government in the Punjab plains.<ref>{{cite book |title=When Sparrows Became Hawks: The Making of the Sikh Warrior Tradition, 1699-1799 |first=Purnima |last=Dhavan |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-19987-717-1 |pages=3, 30\u201331 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q0ZpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA31}}</ref> The khatris played an important role in India's trans-regional trade during the period,<ref>{{cite book |title=Global Indian diasporas |first=Gijsbert |last=Oonk |publisher=Amsterdam University Press |year=2007 |page=43 |isbn=978-90-5356-035-8}}</ref> being described by Scott Cameron Levi as among the \"most important merchant communities of early modern India.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=The Indian Diaspora in Central Asia and Its Trade, 1550\u20131900 |first=Scott Cameron |last=Levi |publisher=BRILL |location=Leiden |year=2002 |isbn=978-90-04-12320-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9qVkNBge8mIC}}</ref>\n\n==Origin==\nKhatris consider themselves to be of pure [[Vedic]] descent and thus superior to the [[Rajput]]s who, like them, claim the [[Kshatriya]] status of the Hindu [[Varna (Hinduism)|varna system]].<ref name=\"syan\">{{cite book |last=Syan |first=Hardip Singh |year=2013 |title=Sikh Militancy in the Seventeenth Century: Religious Violence in Mughal and Early Modern India |publisher=I. B. Tauris |isbn=978-1-78076-250-0 |pages=35, 39 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9RzzxcEL4C0C&pg=PA35}}</ref> The Khatri's standards of literacy and caste status were such during the early years of [[Sikh]]ism that, according to [[W. H. McLeod]], they dominated it.<ref name=\"syan\"/> Author McLeod mentions the employment of khatris as soldiers by Mughal emperors but notes by the time of [[Company rule in India|British arrival]] in India they were mostly merchants and scribes<ref>{{cite book |title=The A to Z of Sikhism |first=W. H. |last=McLeod |authorlink=W. H. McLeod |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-8108-6828-1 |page=115}}</ref> Kenneth W. Jones says \"the Khatris claimed with some justice and increasing insistence, the status of Rajputs, or Kshatriyas, a claim not granted by those above but illustrative of their ambiguous position on the great varna scale of class divisions\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Arya dharm: Hindu consciousness in 19th-century Punjab |first=Kenneth W. |last=Jones |publisher=[[University of California Press]] |year=1976 |isbn=978-0-520-02920-0 |pages=4\u20135 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/americocastromea0000unse }}</ref> Purnima Dhavan sees the claim as originating from a conflation of the words ''khatri'' and ''kshatriya'', which are phonetically similar.<ref name=\"dhavan\"/> In the 19th-century British administrators failed to agree whether the Khatri claim of Kshatriya status should be accepted, since the overwhelming majority of them were engaged in ''Vaishya'' (mercantile) occupation rather than in ''Kshatriya'' (military) pursuits.<ref>{{cite book |title=Land and Local Kingship in Eighteenth-Century Bengal |first=John R. |last=McLane |publisher=Cambridge University Press |page=131 |year=2002 |isbn=978-0-521-52654-8 |quote=The Khatris were a Punjabi mercantile caste who claimed to be Kshatriyas. Nineteenth-century Indians and British administrators failed to agree whether that claim should be accepted. The fact that overwhelming majority were engaged in Vaishya (mercantile), not Kshatriya (military), pursuits was balanced against the Khatri origin myths...}}</ref> [[Dasharatha Sharma]] described Khatris as a mixed ''pratiloma'' caste of low ritual status but suggested that they could be a mixed caste born of Kshatriya fathers and [[Brahmin]] mothers.<ref>{{cite book |title=Early Chauh\u0101n dynasties: a study of Chauh\u0101n political history, Chauh\u0101n political institutions, and life in the Chauh\u0101n dominions, from 800 to 1316 A.D. |first=Dasharatha |last=Sharma |authorlink=Dasharatha Sharma |page=279 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |year=1975}}</ref>\n\nThe Khatris of Gujarat and Rajasthan are said to have tailoring skills like \"Darji\" (tailor) caste.<ref>Indian settlers: the story of a New Zealand South Asian community, p48, Jacqueline Leckie, Otago University Press, 2000/ quote :\"Tailoring was a caste occupation that continued in New Zealand by those from Darji and Khatri castes who had been trained in appropriate skills. Bhukandas Masters, a Khatri, emigrated to New Zealand in 1919. He practised as tailor in central Auckland...\"</ref> In the case of those Khatris who avow Sikism, their Kshatriya claim reflects the confusing, even seemingly contradictory, attitude towards the traditional Hindu caste system that is evident in Sikh texts such as the ''[[Guru Granth Sahib]]'', which on the one hand renounces the Hindu caste paradigm and on the other seeks to portray the gurus as a group of warrior-defenders of their faith, just as with the Kshatriya varna.<ref name=\"dhavan\">{{cite book |title=When Sparrows Became Hawks: The Making of the Sikh Warrior Tradition, 1699-1799 |first=Purnima |last=Dhavan |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-19987-717-1 |pages=36\u201337 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q0ZpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA36}}</ref>\n\n==Religion==\n===Hindu Khatris===\nThe vast majority of Khatris are Hindu.<ref>{{cite report |author= Gopal Krishan|date= |title= Demography of the Punjab (1849-1947)|url= http://www.global.ucsb.edu/punjab/sites/secure.lsit.ucsb.edu.gisp.d7_sp/files/sitefiles/journals/volume11/no1/6_krishan.pdf|publisher= UCSB|page= 83|access-date= 24 September 2018|quote= \"Conversion was negligible from the higher castes such as Brahmins, Aroras, Khatris and Aggarwals.\"}}</ref> Most Hindu Khatris migrated to India after partition and settled in urban areas across India. They were estimated to constitute 9% of the total population of Delhi in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.india-seminar.com/2004/534/534%20sanjay%20kumar.htm|title=534 Sanjay Kumar, A tale of three cities|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Sikh Khatris===\nAll the ten Sikh Gurus were Khatris:<ref>{{cite book |title=The Encyclopedia of Sikhism |first=H. S. |last=Singha |page=125 |isbn=978-81-7010-301-1 |publisher=Hemkunt Press |year=2000 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gqIbJz7vMn0C&pg=PA125}}</ref> [[Guru Nanak]] was a Bedi, [[Guru Angad]] was a Trehan, [[Guru Amar Das]] was a Bhalla, and the remainder were [[Sodhi]]s.<ref>{{cite book |title=The A to Z of Sikhism |first=W. H. |last=McLeod |authorlink=W. H. McLeod |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-8108-6828-1 |page=86}}</ref> During the lifetime of the Gurus, most of their major supporters were Khatris. A list of these is provided by a contemporary of the Sikh Gurus, [[Bhai Gurdas]], in his ''[[Varan Bhai Gurdas]]''.<ref>Bhai Gurdas ''Ji'', Varan Bhai Gurdas Ji, Vaar 8&nbsp;\u2013 Pauri 10.</ref>{{qn|date=February 2019}} However, many of the more successful Khatri traders opposed the strictures of the [[Khalsa]] movement, introduced by [[Guru Gobind Singh]] to end the concept of caste in Sikhism by removing traditional rituals and identities.<ref>{{cite book |title=When Sparrows Became Hawks: The Making of the Sikh Warrior Tradition, 1699-1799 |first=Purnima |last=Dhavan |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-19987-717-1 |pages=42, 47, 184 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q0ZpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA42}}</ref>\n\nAside from the gurus, other Khatris influential in the history of Sikhism include:\n\n* [[Bhai Daya Singh]], the first of the [[Panj Pyare]] (the initial members of the [[Khalsa]]), belonged to the Sobti clan of the Khatris.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Sikhs in history: a millenium study, with new afterwords |author=Sangat Singh |publisher=Uncommon Books |year=2001 |isbn=978-81-900650-2-3 |page=71}}</ref>\n* [[Hari Singh Nalwa]] (1791\u20131837), the Commander-in-chief of the Khalsa army of the Sikh Empire.\n* [[Dewan Mokham Chand]] Nayyar(- 1814), the Commander-in-chief of the Khalsa army of the Sikh Empire\n* [[Diwan Mulraj Chopra]] (1814 - 11 August 1851) was the Diwan of Multan and leader of a Sikh rebellion against the British which led to the Second Anglo-Sikh War.\n\n===Punjabi Khatris post-Independence===\nD.L.Sheth, the former director of the [[Centre for the Study of Developing Societies|Center for the Study of Developing Societies in India(CSDS)]], lists Indian upper castes that constituted the middle class and were traditionally \"[[Urban area|urban]] and [[professional]]\" (following professions like doctors, lawyers, teachers, engineers, etc.) immediately after Independence in 1947. This list included the Khatris from Punjab, [[Kashmiri Pandits]], [[Nagar Brahmin]] and the South Indian Brahmins; [[Chitpawan]]s and CKPs([[Chandraseniya Kayastha Prabhu]]s) from Maharashtra; [[Kayastha]]s from northern India; the Probasi and the [[Bhadralok]] [[Bengalis]], the [[Parsis]] and the upper crusts of Muslim and Christian communities. According to P.K.Verma, \"Education was a common thread that bound together this pan Indian elite\" and almost all the members of these communities could read and write English and were educated beyond school.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Great Indian Middle class|page=28|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pbgMy8KfD74C&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=false|author=Pavan K. Varma|publisher=Penguin Books|quote=...its main adherents came from those in government service, qualified '''professionals''' such as doctors,engineers and lawyers,business entrepreneurs,teachers in schools in the bigger cities and in the institutes of higher education, journalists[etc]...The upper castes dominated the Indian middle class. Prominent among its members were Punjabi Khatris, Kashmiri Pandits and South Indian brahmins. Then there were the 'traditional urban-oriented professional castes such as the Nagars of Gujarat, the Chitpawans and the Ckps (Chandrasenya Kayastha Prabhus)s of Maharashtra and the Kayasthas of North India. Also included were the old elite groups that emerged during the colonial rule: the Probasi and the Bhadralok Bengalis, the Parsis and the upper crusts of Muslim and Christian communities. Education was a common thread that bound together this pan Indian elite...But almost all its members spoke and wrote English and had had some education beyond school|isbn=9780143103257|year=2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Social Action, Volume 50|publisher=Indian Social Institute|year=2000|page=72}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csds.in/d_l_sheth|title=D.L. Sheth}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Khatris]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{Ethnic groups, tribes and clans of the Punjab}}\n\n[[Category:Social groups of Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Punjab, Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Punjabi tribes|*]]\n[[Category:Merchant castes]]\n[[Category:Hindu communities]]\n[[Category:Sikh communities]]\n", "name_user": "Rishabkapania77", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khatri"}
{"title_page": "Percy Trompf", "text_new": "{{Lead too short|date=March 2020}}\n'''Percival Albert Trompf''' (1902-1964), was an Australian commercial artist, best known for his travel posters. Some of his most popular designs depicted historical events, including the construction of the [[Sydney Harbour Bridge]].<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news |title=Take a trip into the past: rare Australian vintage travel posters \u2013 in pictures |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/gallery/2019/nov/14/take-a-trip-into-the-past-rare-australian-vintage-travel-posters-in-pictures |accessdate=29 January 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPercival Albert Trompf was born on 30 May 1902 in [[Beaufort, Victoria]], the ninth child of Henry Alexander Trompf, a fruiterer, and his wife Catherine Amelia,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11024846 |title=Family Notices |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)]] |location=Victoria, Australia |date=1 April 1936 |access-date=30 January 2020 |page=1 |via=Trove }}</ref> n\u00e9e Elliott.<ref name=\"ADB\">{{cite web |last1=Spearritt |first1=Katie |last2=Spearritt |first2=Peter |title=Trompf, Percival Albert (Percy) (1902\u20131964) |url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/trompf-percival-albert-percy-8855 |website=Australian Dictionary of Biography |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref> His family later moved to [[Ballarat]], and he was educated at Sebastopol Primary School. He developed an enduring interest in cricket and sang and competed as a member of a church choir.<ref>'South Street Competitions', ''[[The Star (Ballarat)|Ballarat Star]]'', January 18, 1915, Ballarat, p.4</ref>  He became one of the earliest students at the [[University of Ballarat|Ballarat School of Mines]]' [[Technical Education Centre|Ballarat Technical Art School]] where he left with his certificate in 1917,<ref>{{Citation | title=Victorian Education Department Certificates | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/228363929 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | title='Echoes of the Past': Ballarat School of Mines Past Student's Association, 1932, 1936, 1938 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/230212171 }}</ref><ref name=\"ADB\"/><ref name=\"Federation University\">{{cite web |title=Percival Albert TROMPF (1902-1964)  |url=https://federation.edu.au/about-us/our-university/history/geoffrey-blainey-research-centre/honour-roll/t/percival-albert-trompf-1902-1964 |website=Federation University |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref> and where he was remembered in 1930, when his posters were exhibited there, as \"one of Ballarat's most notable old boys\".<ref>'Ballarat Art Show Opens: Fine Posters,' ''[[The Herald (Melbourne)|Melbourne Herald]]'', August 28, 1930, Melbourne, p.19</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nIn 1923,<ref>Ballarat Star, August 07,1922, Ballarat, p.4</ref> Trompf began designing confectionery boxes and wrappings for Giles & Richards, a Melbourne firm of commercial artists,<ref name=\"ADB\"/> before setting up his own studio in Little Collins Street, painting and designing thousands of advertising posters, usually of 25 x 40 inches (64 x 102&nbsp;cm) format, and 24-sheet [[Billboard|advertising hoardings]], for which Trompf supervised all stages of production, including the lithographic printing.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Caban, Geoffrey | title=A fine line : a history of Australian commercial art | date=1983 | publisher=Hale & Iremonger | isbn=978-0-86806-012-5 }}</ref> He also designed books and pamphlets throughout his career.\n\nAn early client was Charles Holmes (later editor of [[Walkabout (magazine)|''Walkabout'']], also a client) chairman of the Victorian Railways Betterment and Publicity Board under [[Harold Winthrop Clapp|Harold Clapp]].<ref name=\"ADB\" /><ref>{{Citation | author1=Rolls, Mitchell | author2=Johnston, Anna, 1972-, (author.) | title=Travelling home, Walkabout magazine and mid-twentieth-century Australia | date=2016 | publisher=Anthem Press, an imprint of Wimbledon Publishing Company | isbn=978-1-78308-537-8 }}</ref> Holmes had recognising the successful use of poster advertising by the [[London Underground]]'s [[Frank Pick]], and hired Trompf for a similar campaign in the 1920s.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Northfield, James | author2=Hetherington, Michelle, 1959- | author3=National Library of Australia | author4=Northfield, James, 1887-1973 | title=James Northfield and the art of selling Australia | date=2006 | publisher=National Library of Australia | isbn=978-0-642-27619-3 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways | title=The holiday spirit, Mt. Buffalo National Park | date=1920 | publisher=Victorian Railways | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/25941042 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways (issuing body.) | title=Take a day at the seaside : go down by train! | date=1923 | publisher=[Victorian Railways] | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/191664947 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways | author3=F.W. Niven Pty. Ltd, (printer.) | title=See the Better Farming Train | date=1924 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/177673637 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways | title=See the better farming train : a wonderful exhibition accompanied by experts to help the farmer and lady demonstrators in household affairs to assist the farmer's wife : increased production, reduced costs, farm efficiency, improved stock | date=1924 | publisher=Victorian Railways, Australia | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/10200505 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways (issuing body.) | author3=Robert Harding Pty Ltd (printer.) | title=Visit Mt. Buffalo National Park this summer | date=1924 | publisher=[Victorian Railways] | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/229618281 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article51432023 |title=A CHANCE FOR ARTISTS |newspaper=[[The Examiner (Tasmania)]] |location=Tasmania, Australia |date=23 July 1927 |page=12 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nBy 1931 Trompf was well known as a poster artist.<ref name=\":3\" /> \"Scuu\" in ''[[Smith's Weekly]]'' of August 8, 1931, rhetorically asked;\n{{quotation|\"Does commercial art pay? Well, ask Percy Trompf, who has just had another striking 'Eat More Oranges' poster accepted by Harold Clapp to brighten Victorian railway stations. So many of Percy\u2019s posters are already on railway hoardings that many people believe he is on the permanent payroll. The A.N.T.A. have also adopted his designs\u2014notably the Landing of Captain Cook and the Sydney Harbour Bridge\u2014while the Orient S.S. Co. has just awarded him first prize in the competition to improve its posters\"<ref>''Smith's Weekly'', August 8, 1931, Sydney, p.15</ref>}}\nClients included the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]],<ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | title=Banff : Canadian Pacific Railway | date=1930 | publisher=J.E. Hackett, print | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/220800743 | accessdate=30 January 2020 }}</ref> [[Bryant & May]], [[Palmolive (brand)|Palmolive]], and the magazine ''[[Walkabout (magazine)|Walkabout]]'' established March 25, 1929 by its parent body the [[Australian National Travel Association]].<ref>{{Citation | author1=Bryans, Dennis | title=Magazines a specialty: the Specialty Press and the Commercial Travellers' Association | journal=Bulletin (Bibliographical Society of Australia and New Zealand) | date=2004 | volume=28 | issue=3 | pages=4\u201323 | issn=0084-7852 }}</ref> For the latter Trompf produced posters targeted at a limited number overseas who could afford travel, and their designs and content reflect this niche market.<ref>LAW, John and Kevin HETHERINGTON, 1999. \"Materialities, spatialities and globalities\", Dept of Sociology,. University of Lancaster</ref> By 1930, 100,000 posters had been distributed.<ref name=\"The author\">{{Citation | author1=Pocock, Celmara Anne | title=Romancing the Reef : history, heritage and the hyper-real | date=2003 | publisher=The author | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/3999062 }}</ref>\n\n== World War II ==\nIn May 1942 he enlisted in the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] and was commissioned as a pilot in June.<ref name=\"ADB\" /> Trompf served mostly at [[Milne Bay]], Papua New Guinea, and worked as a camouflage officer.<ref name=\"ADB\" /> He was demobilized in February 1948, with the rank of flying officer.<ref name=\"ADB\" />\n\n== Postwar ==\nReturning to business after the war, Trompf received little work from A.N.T.A and the Victorian Railways. His clientele reduced during the 1950s to the [[Queensland Government Tourist Bureau]],<ref name=\":2\"/> the Commonwealth Railways, and Victorian Education Department for road safety posters. He produced also some book covers, illustration and design, including ''Under southern skies'', on the Dandenong Ranges, Mornington Peninsula and Gippsland for the Australian Publicity Council.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy, 1902-1964, (book designer.) | author2=Turnbull, Lyle, 1928-2003, (author.) | author3=Australian Publicity Council | title=Under southern skies: Victoria, Australia | date=1954 | publisher=Australian Publicity Council | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/19294668 }}</ref><ref>'Under Southern Skies: production story of a magnificent book', [[Morwell Advertiser]], July 05, 1954, p.7</ref>\n\nPoster design declined in the 1960s as magazines and travel institutions increasingly used more affordable colour photography rather than specially commissioning graphic illustrations, for the sake of faster turn-around and for more persuasive realism.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Reception==\nTrompf enjoyed a growing reputation alongside other poster artists [[James Northfield]], Walter Jardine, [[Eileen Mayo]], [[Gert Sellheim]] and C. Dudley Wood. In their 1940 report on the first annual show of the Australian Commercial and Industrial Artists\u2019 Association in Sydney, ''[[The Bulletin (Australian periodical)|The Bulletin]]'' characterised him as \"one of the few poster men whose signature is well known.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Citation | title=SUNDRY SHOWS (18 December 1940) | journal=The Bulletin | date=1940-12-18 | publisher=John Haynes and J.F. Archibald | volume=61 | issue=3175 | issn=0007-4039 }}</ref> In 1985, surveying Australian representations of beach culture, historian [[Geoffrey Dutton]] equates Trompf to [[Max Dupain]], [[Charles Conder]] and [[Sidney Nolan|Sydney Nolan]].<ref>{{Citation | author1=Dutton, Geoffrey | title=Sun, sea, surf and sand -- the myth of the beach | date=1985 | publisher=Oxford University Press | isbn=978-0-19-554411-4 }}</ref>\n\nThe colour lithography that Trompf used produced bold, simplified realism in an Art Deco style,<ref>{{Citation | author1=Biron, George | title=Lost and found - Percy Everett and Vanne Trompf | journal=Spirit of Progress | date=2018 | volume=19 | issue=4 | pages=26\u201327 | issn=1443-7554 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Lord, Jullie | title=The Percy Trompf story | journal=Spirit of Progress | date=March 2019 | volume=20 | issue=1 | pages=18\u201320 | issn=1443-7554 }}</ref> with wide appeal, especially during the [[Great Depression]]. Posters exhorted Australians to travel by rail, to eat more fruit to the benefit of the country's struggling primary producers and, against competition from cars and buses contributing to unsustainable rail service deficits, they sought to promote diversity of purposes for travel that might provide new sources of revenue.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Symes, Colin | title=\"Even our 2nd class cars are more comfortable than motor buses!\" : an analysis of victorian railway posters between the wars | date=2016 | publisher=Routledge | issn=1444-3058 }}</ref>  They promoted the simple joys of sun-worship,<ref name=\":2\" /> surfing<ref>{{Citation | author1=Walding, Murray | title=Surf-o-rama : treasures of Australian surfing | date=2016 | publisher=Miegunyah Press, an imprint of Melbourne University Publishing | edition=New | isbn=978-0-522-86997-2 }}</ref> and bushwalking,<ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy, 1902-1964, (illustrator.) | author2=Victorian Railways. Betterment and Publicity Board, (issuing body.) | title=Wonderful walks in Victoria | date=1931 | publisher=The Betterment and Publicity Board, Victorian Railways | edition=[New edition] | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/20606597 | accessdate=30 January 2020 }}</ref> which were then becoming popular alongside a general interest in 'body culture' then pervasive among the young,<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation | author1=Booth, Douglas | title=Australian beach cultures : the history of sun, sand, and surf | date=2001 | publisher=Frank Cass | isbn=978-0-7146-5167-5 }}</ref> famously celebrated in Trompf's best-known poster simply titled ''Australia.''<ref>{{Citation | author1=Kerr, Rosemary | title=Roads, tourism and cultural history : on the road in Australia | date=2019 | publisher=Channel View Publications | isbn=978-1-84541-668-3 }}</ref>\n\nIn recent evaluations, Gilfedder, in analysing, as a sample, the visual rhetoric of Trompf's poster for the British market featuring Captain Cook's landing at Botany Bay to invite the traveler to 'Discover Australia', concludes that such travel posters were early instances of 'country branding'.<ref>{{Citation|author1=Gilfedder, Deirdre|title=The visual rhetoric of Australian travel posters between the wars: Branding a new nation|journal=Cultures of the Commonwealth|issue=15/16|pages=95\u2013105|date=2010|issn=1245-2971}}</ref> Symes perceives that railway posters of this period using state-of-the-art techniques of the new field of commercial art developed Victoria's tourist geography, locating, labelling, visualising and imbuing places and regions with specific recreational and leisure attributes<ref>{{Citation | author1=Symes, Colin | title=Motion pictures : an analysis of the posters of Victorian railways during the 1920s and 1930s | date=2015 | publisher=Routledge | issn=1755-182X }}</ref> and Pocock attributes such responsibility, on a whole-of-Australia scale, to Trompf's 1933 poster <ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Queensland Government Tourist Bureau | title=The Marine wonders of the Great Barrier Coral Reef : for particulars & bookings apply Queensland Government Tourist Bureau, Brisbane, Sydney, Melbourne | date=1933 | publisher=Frederick Phillips, Government Printer | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/19832108 }}</ref>  in advancing the Great Barrier Reef as one of the most significant tourist destinations.<ref name=\"The author\"/> Dann<ref>{{Citation | author1=Dann, Graham | title=The language of tourism : a sociolinguistic perspective | date=1996 | publisher=CAB International | isbn=978-0-85198-999-0 }}</ref> and Barnes<ref>Barnes, Jillian E., \u2018Resisting the captured image: how Gwoja Tjungurrayi, \u02bbOne Pound Jimmy\u02bc, escaped the \u02bbStone Age.\u02bc\u2019 In {{Citation | author1=Hannah, Mark, (editor.) | author2=Macfarlane, Ingereth, (editor.) | author3=ANU E Press | title=Transgressions : critical Australian indigenous histories | date=2007 | publisher=ANU E Press and Aboriginal History Incorporated | isbn=978-1-921313-43-1 }}</ref> show how tourism marketing professionals including Trompf created a visual language of modernity, promotion and consumerism.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Spearritt, Peter | title=Symbols for Australia. [The changes to the iconography of political and corporate advertising.] | journal=Artlink | date=1997 | volume=17 | issue=3 | pages=58\u201360 | issn=0727-1239 }}\n</ref>\n\nBarnes cites Trompf's Commonwealth Railway poster as applying an American aesthetic in depicting Central Australia; replacing North American pueblos with Australian indigenous \u2018[[Arrernte people|Arunta]]' men. Juxtaposing modern, white, explorers-cum-tourists with 'primitive natives\u2019 each in formulaic groupings, positions and postures, the colonial figures and their vehicles are given centre- and stage-right to symbolise progress, while Aboriginal men are diminished in scale and backgrounded to represent their servility and symbolic position in the past.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Waitt, Gordon | title=Selling paradise and adventure: representations of landscape in the tourist advertising of Australia | journal=Australian Geographical Studies | date=1997-03-01 | publisher=Blackwell Publishers Ltd | volume=v35 | issue=n1 | pages=47(14) | issn=0004-9190 }}</ref><ref>Waitt, G. (1999). Naturalizing the \u2018primitive\u2019: A critique of marketing Australia's indigenous peoples as \u2018hunter\u2010gatherers\u2019. Tourism Geographies, 1(2), 142-163.</ref>\n\nThe nostalgic attractiveness and historical interest of Trompf's posters endure; they are frequently included in public exhibitions,<ref>{{Citation | author1=Butler, Roger | title=The streets as art galleries - walls sometimes speak : poster art in Australia | date=1993 | publisher=National Gallery of Australia | isbn=978-0-642-13020-4 }}</ref> they have become collectible national treasures<ref>{{Citation | title=Bondi gems beckon in UK | journal=Australasian Business Intelligence | date=2013-10-16 | publisher=COMTEX News Network, Inc | issn=1320-6680 }}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> and they fetch up to $A12,000 at auction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.invaluable.com/artist/trompf-percy-k2wg9l0dxo/sold-at-auction-prices/|title=Percy Trompf Paintings & Artwork for Sale {{!}} Percy Trompf Art Value Price Guide|website=www.invaluable.com|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.joseflebovicgallery.com/advSearchResults.php?action=search&orderBy=relevance&category_id=0&keywordsField=Percy+Trompf|title=Percy Trompf at Joseph Lebovic Gallery|last=www.bibliopolis.com|date=|website=Josef Lebovic Gallery|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 14 May 1932, Trompf married Vera Johns at the Methodist Church, [[Armadale, Victoria|Armadale]], Victoria, Melbourne, and they had two daughters.<ref name=\"ADB\"/><ref name=\"ADB\"/> His nephew (b.1940) was religious historian Professor Garry W. Trompf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://therha.com.au/garry-w-trompf/|title=Emeritus Professor Garry W. Trompf {{!}} Religious History Association|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Cusack, Carole M | author2=Trompf, G. W | author3=Cusack, Carole M., 1962- | author4=Hartney, Christopher | author5=ProQuest (Firm) | title=Religion and retributive logic : essays in honour of professor Garry W. Trompf | date=2010 | publisher=Brill | isbn=978-1-282-78641-7 }}</ref>\n\nTrompf died of a renal infection on 17 July 1964 in [[Heidelberg, Victoria|Heidelberg]], Melbourne.<ref name=\"ADB\"/>\n\n== Works ==\n=== 1920s ===\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways | title=The holiday spirit, Mt. Buffalo National Park | date=1920 | publisher=Victorian Railways | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/25941042 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways (issuing body.) | title=Take a day at the seaside : go down by train! | date=1923 | publisher=[Victorian Railways] | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/191664947 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways | author3=F.W. Niven Pty. Ltd, (printer.) | title=See the Better Farming Train | date=1924 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/177673637 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways | title=See the better farming train : a wonderful exhibition accompanied by experts to help the farmer and lady demonstrators in household affairs to assist the farmer's wife : increased production, reduced costs, farm efficiency, improved stock | date=1924 | publisher=Victorian Railways, Australia | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/10200505 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways (issuing body.) | author3=Robert Harding Pty Ltd (printer.) | title=Visit Mt. Buffalo National Park this summer | date=1924 | publisher=[Victorian Railways] | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/229618281 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Australian Railways Commissioners | title=Australia calls you : settler, investor or tourist | date=1925 | publisher=Australian Railways Commissioners | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/158124346 |ref=none}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16184443 |title=TO ADVERTISE AUSTRALIA. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=5 February 1925 | page=10 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Orient Line Steam Navigation Company | title=Australia, Orient Line 20,000 ton ships | date=1929 | publisher=Orient Line | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/33340895 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Australian National Travel Association | title=The Landing of Captain Cook at Botany Bay 1770, Australia | date=1929 | publisher=Australian National Travel Association | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/35724046 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Australian National Travel Association (issuing body.) | title=Australia : particulars at shipping and travel agencies | date=1929 | publisher=Melbourne Troedel & Cooper Pty. Ltd | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/203346537 |ref=none}}\n\n=== 1930s ===\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways | title=Bendigo, the golden city, Victoria, Australia : take a Kodak | date=1930 | publisher=Victorian Railways, Australia | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/38368707 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Australian National Travel Association | author3=Northfield Studios | author4=J. E. Hackett (Firm) | title=Australia for sunshine & romance | date=1930 | publisher=Australian National Travel Association | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/36944529 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways (issuing body.) | author3=Victoria. State Rivers and Water Supply Commission (issuing body.) | title=Citrus fruits : give glowing health | date=1930 | publisher=[Melbourne] Issued by the Victorian Railways Commissioners in conjunction with the State Rivers & Water Supply Commission | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/223612529 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Trans-Australian Railway | title=Luxurious travel, night & day : across Australia : save days by the Trans-Australian Railway | date=1930 | publisher=Trans-Australian Railway | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/152215155 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | title=Seek the winter sunshine at Mildura, Queen city of the Murray Valley | date=1930 | publisher=Issued by the Victorian Railways Commissioners & the Mildura District Tourist Association | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/34697801 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy, 1902-1964, (illustrator.) | title=Eat more fruit : take some home today! | date=1931 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/213705022 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy, 1902-1964, (artist.) | author2=Victoria. State Rivers and Water Supply Commission (issuing body.) | author3=Victorian Railways (issuing body.) | title=Keep fit, eat more fruit : citrus fruits | date=1931 | publisher=Victorian Railways | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/213705007 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | title=Mt. Buffalo National Park, Victoria, Australia : Take a Kodak | date=1930 | publisher=F.W. Niven, Pty. Ltd | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/193456884 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | title=Seventh city of the Empire - Melbourne, Victoria | date=1930 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/192106667 |re