pf, Percy | author2=Australian National Travel Association, (issuing body.) | title=Tropical North Queensland (April to Sept.), Australia | date=1931 | publisher=Australian National Travel Association | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/235420046 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Australian National Travel Association | author2=Trompf, Percy, 1902-1964 | title=Australia : the tallest trees in the British Empire - Marysville, Victoria | date=1936 | publisher=Australian National Travel Association | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/6701751 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Australian National Travel Association | title=World's greatest air race for MacRobertson Trophy : England to Australia, Victorian and Melbourne Centenary 1934-35 (commencing October) | date=1934 | publisher=Australian National Travel Association | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/19900444 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Government Tourist Bureau | author3=Victorian Railways. Advertising Division | title=Prince's Highway Tour - Melbourne To Sydney : four days - by rail and road - consult Govt. Tourist Bureau, Queen's Walk (opp. Town Hall) Melbourne | date=1935 | publisher=Govt. Tourist Bureau | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/218847670 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Buchan Caves Committee, (issuing body.) | author3=Victorian Government Tourist Bureau | title=The mystic beauty of the Buchan Caves | date=1935 | publisher=Issued by the Buchan Caves Committee | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/232823540 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways (issuing body.) | author3=Robert Harding Pty Ltd (printer.) | title=Days of freedom : go down to the seaside by train | date=1935 | publisher=Victorian Railways, Australia | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/192344564 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victoria. Apple Campaign Committee | author3=Victorian Railways | title=Keep fit, eat more apples : remember - an apple a day - | date=1930 | publisher=Apple Campaign Committee, Dept. of Agriculture & Railways Dept | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/35357774 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Roughley, T. C. (Theodore Cleveland) | author2=Trompf, Percy, 1902-1964 | author3=Australian National Travel Association | title=Big-game angling Australia | date=1937 | publisher=ANTA | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/17246428 |ref=none}}\n\n=== 1940s ===\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Australian National Travel Association | title=Western Australia | date=1940 | publisher=W.A. Government Tourist Bureau | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7555160 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Trans-Australian Railway | title=To Western Australia by Trans-Australian Railway | date=1940 | publisher=Trans-Australian Railway | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/35273981 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Blue Mountains (N.S.W.). Council | title=See for yourself ... : Blue Mountain Resorts - N.S.W | date=1946 | publisher=[Katoomba?] [Blue Mountains County Council?] | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/218847669 |ref=none}}\n\n=== 1950s ===\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Queensland Government Tourist Bureau | title=North Queensland calls you : to a winter holiday in the tropics | date=1950 | publisher=Queensland Government Tourist Bureau | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/32588607 |ref=none}} \n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Queensland Government Tourist Bureau | title=A winter holiday in the sun! : Brisbane river city of the north | date=1950 | publisher=Queensland Government Tourist Bureau | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/5614482 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victoria. Department of Education. Visual Education Centre | title=Always avoid cycling more than two abreast ! | date=1950 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/230496113 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victoria. Department of Education. Visual Education Centre | title=Never walk in groups on country roads ! | date=1950 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/230496110 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Ebeli, Gerard, 1928-2009, (artist.) | title=Across Australia in air-conditioned comfort by the Trans-Australian Railway | date=1951 | publisher=Issued by the Commonwealth Railways Commissioner | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/237019647 |ref=none}} \n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victoria. Department of Education. Visual Education Centre | title=Look both ways before stepping on to the road | date=1950 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/230496111 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victoria. Department of Education. Visual Education Centre | title=Always join or leave a tram correctly! | date=1950 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/230496108 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victoria. Department of Education. Visual Education Centre | title=Always try to understand drivers' signals | date=1950 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/230496109 |ref=none}}\n*{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | title=3 vital words, made in Australia : for value - wherever you trade, buy Australian made | date=1950 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/32663384 |ref=none}}\n*{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victoria. Department of Education. Visual Education Centre | title=Always play in a safe place not on the road | date=1950 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/230496112 |ref=none}}\n*{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Queensland Government Tourist Bureau | title=A winter holiday in the sun! : Brisbane river city of the north | date=1950 | publisher=Queensland Government Tourist Bureau | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/5614482 |ref=none}}\n*{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Commonwealth Railways (Australia) | title=Winter tours to Central Australia | date=1959 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/35353409  |ref=none}}\n*{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Commonwealth Railways (Australia) | title=Winter holidays by rail to Central Australia | date=1959 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/35227936 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Queensland Government Tourist Bureau | title=Visit colourful Queensland | date=1950 | publisher=Queensland Government Tourist Bureau | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7552848 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Queensland Government Tourist Bureau | title=Off to the North for warmth | date=1940 | publisher=Queensland Government Tourist Bureau | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/35218268 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy, 1902-1964, (book designer.) | author2=Turnbull, Lyle, 1928-2003, (author.) | author3=Australian Publicity Council | title=Under southern skies : Victoria, Australia | date=1954 | publisher=Australian Publicity Council | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/19294668 |ref=none}}\n\n=== Posthumous ===\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Australian National Gallery (issuing body.) | title=Canberra : apply New South Wales Railway booking offices, for travel and holiday particulars | date=1989 | publisher=[Canberra] Australian National Gallery | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/191220061 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy, 1902-1964 | author2=Commonwealth Railways (Australia) | title=See the heart of the continent : winter holidays by rail to central Australia [poster] | date=1994 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/222708801 |ref=none}}\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n* 2017, July 14 - October 15; ''Brave new world'', National Gallery of Victoria\n*2012/13, December 12 - July 7; ''Treasures Gallery'', National Library of Australia, 12 December 2012 - 7 July 2013\n*2008, March 5 - June 15; ''Bridging the Distance'', National Library of Australia<ref>{{Citation | author1=Dent, Margaret, 1944- | author2=Clark, John | author3=National Library of Australia | title=Bridging the distance : [exhibition] | date=2008 | publisher=National Library of Australia | isbn=978-0-642-27661-2 }}</ref>\n*2007/8, December 13 - February 17; ''Pioneers of the Inland: Australia's Muslim Cameleers 1860s - 1930s'', National Library of Australia\n*2003/04, 22 October - March; ''Tourism in Australia: an exhibition of material from the Monash University Library Rare Books Collection,'' Sir Louis Matheson Library, [[Monash University]]<ref>{{Citation | author1=Overell, Richard | author2=Overell, Richard (curator) | title=Tourism in Australia: an exhibition of material from the Monash University Library Rare Books Collection 22 October 2003 - March 2004 | date=2003 | publisher=Monash University Library | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/228461138 | accessdate=30 January 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://repository.monash.edu/items/show/13317#?c=0&m=0&s=0&cv=0|title=Tourism in Australia: an exhibition of material from the Monash University Library Rare Books Collection 22 October 2003 - March 2004|website=repository.monash.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n*2001, August 10 - October 22; ''All the rage: the poster in Victoria 1850-2000'', Keith Murdoch Gallery, State Library of Victoria\n*1999/2000, November - March; ''Follow the Sun'', National Library of Australia\n\n== Collections ==\n* Art Gallery of New South Wales<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/collection/works/?artist_id=trompf-percy|title=Works by Percy Trompf :: The Collection :: Art Gallery NSW|website=www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n* National Gallery of Australia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artsearch.nga.gov.au/search.cfm?creirn=21948&order_select=1&view_select=4|title=NGA collection search results|website=artsearch.nga.gov.au|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n*National Library of Australia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/picture/result?q=exact_creator:%22Trompf%20Percy%201902%201964%22|title=Trove search results for 'exact_creator:\"Trompf Percy 1902 1964\"' - Pictures, photos, objects|website=Trove|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Horky, Wanda | title=Australia--a place for surf and sunshine, romance and holidays ... the poster collection at the National Library of Australia | journal=National Library of Australia Gateways | date=2006-10-01 | publisher=National Library of Australia | issue=83 | issn=1039-3498 }}</ref>\n* [[National Museum of Australia]]<ref>{{Citation | author1=National Museum of Australia | title=Appendix 3: National Historical Collection: Material acquired and approved by Council, 1 July 2011 - 30 June 2012 (30 June 2012) | journal=Annual Report | date=2012-06-30 | publisher=Australian Government Publishing Service | issue=291 of 2012 | pages=109 | issn=0818-7142 }}</ref>\n* Australian National Maritime Museum<ref>{{Citation | author1=Australian National Maritime Museum | title=APPENDIX 2 SELECTED ACQUISITIONS (30 June 2003) | journal=Annual Report | date=2003-06-30 | publisher=Australian National Maritime Museum | issue=281 of 2003 | pages=85 | issn=1039-4036 }}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n* 1929: winner, [[P&O (company)|Orient Company]]'s first prize of \u00a330 for a design in the annual industrial poster competition organised by the [[Royal Society of Arts]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article53486983 |title=Ballarat Student Wins Poster Prize |newspaper=[[The Register News-pictorial]] |location=South Australia |date=20 July 1929 |page=4 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n* 1934: Ideal Label Contest  \n* 1946: First prize (\u00a3100) in the Blue Mountains Council's nation-wide competition\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trompf, Percival Albert}}\n[[Category:1902 births]]\n[[Category:1964 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian poster artists]]\n[[Category:Australian graphic designers]]\n[[Category:Royal Australian Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Royal Australian Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Australia]]\n[[Category:Tourism in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Lead too short|date=March 2020}}\n'''Percival Albert Trompf''' (1902-1964), was an Australian commercial artist, best known for his travel posters. Some of his most popular designs depicted historical events, including the construction of the [[Sydney Harbour Bridge]].<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news |title=Take a trip into the past: rare Australian vintage travel posters \u2013 in pictures |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/gallery/2019/nov/14/take-a-trip-into-the-past-rare-australian-vintage-travel-posters-in-pictures |accessdate=29 January 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPercival Albert Trompf was born on 30 May 1902 in [[Beaufort, Victoria]], the ninth child of Henry Alexander Trompf, a fruiterer, and his wife Catherine Amelia,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11024846 |title=Family Notices |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)]] |location=Victoria, Australia |date=1 April 1936 |access-date=30 January 2020 |page=1 |via=Trove }}</ref> n\u00e9e Elliott.<ref name=\"ADB\">{{cite web |last1=Spearritt |first1=Katie |last2=Spearritt |first2=Peter |title=Trompf, Percival Albert (Percy) (1902\u20131964) |url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/trompf-percival-albert-percy-8855 |website=Australian Dictionary of Biography |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref> His family later moved to [[Ballarat]], and he was educated at Sebastopol Primary School. He developed an enduring interest in cricket and sang and competed as a member of a church choir.<ref>'South Street Competitions', ''[[The Star (Ballarat)|Ballarat Star]]'', January 18, 1915, Ballarat, p.4</ref>  He became one of the earliest students at the [[University of Ballarat|Ballarat School of Mines]]' [[Technical Education Centre|Ballarat Technical Art School]] where he left with his certificate in 1917,<ref>{{Citation | title=Victorian Education Department Certificates | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/228363929 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | title='Echoes of the Past': Ballarat School of Mines Past Student's Association, 1932, 1936, 1938 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/230212171 }}</ref><ref name=\"ADB\"/><ref name=\"Federation University\">{{cite web |title=Percival Albert TROMPF (1902-1964)  |url=https://federation.edu.au/about-us/our-university/history/geoffrey-blainey-research-centre/honour-roll/t/percival-albert-trompf-1902-1964 |website=Federation University |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref> and where he was remembered in 1930, when his posters were exhibited there, as \"one of Ballarat's most notable old boys\".<ref>'Ballarat Art Show Opens: Fine Posters,' ''[[The Herald (Melbourne)|Melbourne Herald]]'', August 28, 1930, Melbourne, p.19</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nIn 1923,<ref>Ballarat Star, August 07,1922, Ballarat, p.4</ref> Trompf began designing confectionery boxes and wrappings for Giles & Richards, a Melbourne firm of commercial artists,<ref name=\"ADB\"/> before setting up his own studio in Little Collins Street, painting and designing thousands of advertising posters, usually of 25 x 40 inches (64 x 102&nbsp;cm) format, and 24-sheet [[Billboard|advertising hoardings]], for which Trompf supervised all stages of production, including the lithographic printing.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Caban, Geoffrey | title=A fine line : a history of Australian commercial art | date=1983 | publisher=Hale & Iremonger | isbn=978-0-86806-012-5 }}</ref> He also designed books and pamphlets throughout his career.\n\nAn early client was Charles Holmes (later editor of [[Walkabout (magazine)|''Walkabout'']], also a client) chairman of the Victorian Railways Betterment and Publicity Board under [[Harold Winthrop Clapp|Harold Clapp]].<ref name=\"ADB\" /><ref>{{Citation | author1=Rolls, Mitchell | author2=Johnston, Anna, 1972-, (author.) | title=Travelling home, Walkabout magazine and mid-twentieth-century Australia | date=2016 | publisher=Anthem Press, an imprint of Wimbledon Publishing Company | isbn=978-1-78308-537-8 }}</ref> Holmes had recognising the successful use of poster advertising by the [[London Underground]]'s [[Frank Pick]], and hired Trompf for a similar campaign in the 1920s.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Northfield, James | author2=Hetherington, Michelle, 1959- | author3=National Library of Australia | author4=Northfield, James, 1887-1973 | title=James Northfield and the art of selling Australia | date=2006 | publisher=National Library of Australia | isbn=978-0-642-27619-3 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways | title=The holiday spirit, Mt. Buffalo National Park | date=1920 | publisher=Victorian Railways | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/25941042 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways (issuing body.) | title=Take a day at the seaside : go down by train! | date=1923 | publisher=[Victorian Railways] | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/191664947 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways | author3=F.W. Niven Pty. Ltd, (printer.) | title=See the Better Farming Train | date=1924 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/177673637 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways | title=See the better farming train : a wonderful exhibition accompanied by experts to help the farmer and lady demonstrators in household affairs to assist the farmer's wife : increased production, reduced costs, farm efficiency, improved stock | date=1924 | publisher=Victorian Railways, Australia | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/10200505 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways (issuing body.) | author3=Robert Harding Pty Ltd (printer.) | title=Visit Mt. Buffalo National Park this summer | date=1924 | publisher=[Victorian Railways] | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/229618281 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article51432023 |title=A CHANCE FOR ARTISTS |newspaper=[[The Examiner (Tasmania)]] |location=Tasmania, Australia |date=23 July 1927 |page=12 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nBy 1931 Trompf was well known as a poster artist.<ref name=\":3\" /> \u201cScuu\u201d in ''[[Smith's Weekly|Smith\u2019s Weekly]]'' of August 8, 1931, rhetorically asked;\n{{quotation|\u201cDoes commercial art pay? Well, ask Percy Trompf, who has just had another striking \u201cEat More Oranges\u201d poster accepted by Harold Clapp to brighten Victorian railway stations. So many of Percy\u2019s posters are already on railway hoardings that many people believe he is on the permanent payroll. The A.N.T.A. have also adopted his designs\u2014notably the Landing of Captain Cook and the Sydney Harbour Bridge\u2014while the Orient S.S. Co. has just awarded him first prize in the competition to improve its posters\u201d<ref>''Smiths Weekly'', August 08, 1931, Sydney, p.15</ref>}}\nClients included the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]],<ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | title=Banff : Canadian Pacific Railway | date=1930 | publisher=J.E. Hackett, print | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/220800743 | accessdate=30 January 2020 }}</ref> [[Bryant & May]], [[Palmolive (brand)|Palmolive]], and the magazine ''[[Walkabout (magazine)|Walkabout]]'' established March 25, 1929 by its parent body the [[Australian National Travel Association]].<ref>{{Citation | author1=Bryans, Dennis | title=Magazines a specialty: the Specialty Press and the Commercial Travellers' Association | journal=Bulletin (Bibliographical Society of Australia and New Zealand) | date=2004 | volume=28 | issue=3 | pages=4\u201323 | issn=0084-7852 }}</ref> For the latter Trompf produced posters targeted at a limited number overseas who could afford travel, and their designs and content reflect this niche market.<ref>LAW, John and Kevin HETHERINGTON, 1999. \u201cMaterialities, spatialities and globalities\u201d, Dept of Sociology,. University of Lancaster</ref> By 1930, 100,000 posters had been distributed.<ref name=\"The author\">{{Citation | author1=Pocock, Celmara Anne | title=Romancing the Reef : history, heritage and the hyper-real | date=2003 | publisher=The author | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/3999062 }}</ref>\n\n== World War II ==\nIn May 1942 he enlisted in the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] and was commissioned as a pilot in June.<ref name=\"ADB\" /> Trompf served mostly at [[Milne Bay]], Papua New Guinea, and worked as a camouflage officer.<ref name=\"ADB\" /> He was demobilized in February 1948, with the rank of flying officer.<ref name=\"ADB\" />\n\n== Postwar ==\nReturning to business after the war, Trompf received little work from A.N.T.A and the Victorian Railways. His clientele reduced during the 1950s to the [[Queensland Government Tourist Bureau]],<ref name=\":2\"/> the Commonwealth Railways, and Victorian Education Department for road safety posters. He produced also some book covers, illustration and design, including ''Under southern skies'', on the Dandenong Ranges, Mornington Peninsula and Gippsland for the Australian Publicity Council.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy, 1902-1964, (book designer.) | author2=Turnbull, Lyle, 1928-2003, (author.) | author3=Australian Publicity Council | title=Under southern skies: Victoria, Australia | date=1954 | publisher=Australian Publicity Council | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/19294668 }}</ref><ref>'Under Southern Skies: production story of a magnificent book', [[Morwell Advertiser]], July 05, 1954, p.7</ref>\n\nPoster design declined in the 1960s as magazines and travel institutions increasingly used more affordable colour photography rather than specially commissioning graphic illustrations, for the sake of faster turn-around and for more persuasive realism.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Reception==\nTrompf enjoyed a growing reputation alongside other poster artists [[James Northfield]], Walter Jardine, [[Eileen Mayo]], [[Gert Sellheim]] and C. Dudley Wood. In their 1940 report on the first annual show of the Australian Commercial and Industrial Artists\u2019 Association in Sydney, ''[[The Bulletin (Australian periodical)|The Bulletin]]'' characterised him as \"one of the few poster men whose signature is well known.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Citation | title=SUNDRY SHOWS (18 December 1940) | journal=The Bulletin | date=1940-12-18 | publisher=John Haynes and J.F. Archibald | volume=61 | issue=3175 | issn=0007-4039 }}</ref> In 1985, surveying Australian representations of beach culture, historian [[Geoffrey Dutton]] equates Trompf to [[Max Dupain]], [[Charles Conder]] and [[Sidney Nolan|Sydney Nolan]].<ref>{{Citation | author1=Dutton, Geoffrey | title=Sun, sea, surf and sand -- the myth of the beach | date=1985 | publisher=Oxford University Press | isbn=978-0-19-554411-4 }}</ref>\n\nThe colour lithography that Trompf used produced bold, simplified realism in an Art Deco style,<ref>{{Citation | author1=Biron, George | title=Lost and found - Percy Everett and Vanne Trompf | journal=Spirit of Progress | date=2018 | volume=19 | issue=4 | pages=26\u201327 | issn=1443-7554 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Lord, Jullie | title=The Percy Trompf story | journal=Spirit of Progress | date=March 2019 | volume=20 | issue=1 | pages=18\u201320 | issn=1443-7554 }}</ref> with wide appeal, especially during the [[Great Depression]]. Posters exhorted Australians to travel by rail, to eat more fruit to the benefit of the country's struggling primary producers and, against competition from cars and buses contributing to unsustainable rail service deficits, they sought to promote diversity of purposes for travel that might provide new sources of revenue.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Symes, Colin | title=\"Even our 2nd class cars are more comfortable than motor buses!\" : an analysis of victorian railway posters between the wars | date=2016 | publisher=Routledge | issn=1444-3058 }}</ref>  They promoted the simple joys of sun-worship,<ref name=\":2\" /> surfing<ref>{{Citation | author1=Walding, Murray | title=Surf-o-rama : treasures of Australian surfing | date=2016 | publisher=Miegunyah Press, an imprint of Melbourne University Publishing | edition=New | isbn=978-0-522-86997-2 }}</ref> and bushwalking,<ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy, 1902-1964, (illustrator.) | author2=Victorian Railways. Betterment and Publicity Board, (issuing body.) | title=Wonderful walks in Victoria | date=1931 | publisher=The Betterment and Publicity Board, Victorian Railways | edition=[New edition] | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/20606597 | accessdate=30 January 2020 }}</ref> which were then becoming popular alongside a general interest in 'body culture' then pervasive among the young,<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation | author1=Booth, Douglas | title=Australian beach cultures : the history of sun, sand, and surf | date=2001 | publisher=Frank Cass | isbn=978-0-7146-5167-5 }}</ref> famously celebrated in Trompf's best-known poster simply titled ''Australia.''<ref>{{Citation | author1=Kerr, Rosemary | title=Roads, tourism and cultural history : on the road in Australia | date=2019 | publisher=Channel View Publications | isbn=978-1-84541-668-3 }}</ref>\n\nIn recent evaluations, Gilfedder, in analysing, as a sample, the visual rhetoric of Trompf's poster for the British market featuring Captain Cook's landing at Botany Bay to invite the traveler to 'Discover Australia', concludes that such travel posters were early instances of 'country branding'.<ref>{{Citation|author1=Gilfedder, Deirdre|title=The visual rhetoric of Australian travel posters between the wars: Branding a new nation|journal=Cultures of the Commonwealth|issue=15/16|pages=95\u2013105|date=2010|issn=1245-2971}}</ref> Symes perceives that railway posters of this period using state-of-the-art techniques of the new field of commercial art developed Victoria's tourist geography, locating, labelling, visualising and imbuing places and regions with specific recreational and leisure attributes<ref>{{Citation | author1=Symes, Colin | title=Motion pictures : an analysis of the posters of Victorian railways during the 1920s and 1930s | date=2015 | publisher=Routledge | issn=1755-182X }}</ref> and Pocock attributes such responsibility, on a whole-of-Australia scale, to Trompf's 1933 poster <ref>{{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Queensland Government Tourist Bureau | title=The Marine wonders of the Great Barrier Coral Reef : for particulars & bookings apply Queensland Government Tourist Bureau, Brisbane, Sydney, Melbourne | date=1933 | publisher=Frederick Phillips, Government Printer | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/19832108 }}</ref>  in advancing the Great Barrier Reef as one of the most significant tourist destinations.<ref name=\"The author\"/> Dann<ref>{{Citation | author1=Dann, Graham | title=The language of tourism : a sociolinguistic perspective | date=1996 | publisher=CAB International | isbn=978-0-85198-999-0 }}</ref> and Barnes<ref>Barnes, Jillian E., \u2018Resisting the captured image: how Gwoja Tjungurrayi, \u02bbOne Pound Jimmy\u02bc, escaped the \u02bbStone Age.\u02bc\u2019 In {{Citation | author1=Hannah, Mark, (editor.) | author2=Macfarlane, Ingereth, (editor.) | author3=ANU E Press | title=Transgressions : critical Australian indigenous histories | date=2007 | publisher=ANU E Press and Aboriginal History Incorporated | isbn=978-1-921313-43-1 }}</ref> show how tourism marketing professionals including Trompf created a visual language of modernity, promotion and consumerism.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Spearritt, Peter | title=Symbols for Australia. [The changes to the iconography of political and corporate advertising.] | journal=Artlink | date=1997 | volume=17 | issue=3 | pages=58\u201360 | issn=0727-1239 }}\n</ref>\n\nBarnes cites Trompf's Commonwealth Railway poster as applying an American aesthetic in depicting Central Australia; replacing North American pueblos with Australian indigenous \u2018[[Arrernte people|Arunta]]' men. Juxtaposing modern, white, explorers-cum-tourists with 'primitive natives\u2019 each in formulaic groupings, positions and postures, the colonial figures and their vehicles are given centre- and stage-right to symbolise progress, while Aboriginal men are diminished in scale and backgrounded to represent their servility and symbolic position in the past.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Waitt, Gordon | title=Selling paradise and adventure: representations of landscape in the tourist advertising of Australia | journal=Australian Geographical Studies | date=1997-03-01 | publisher=Blackwell Publishers Ltd | volume=v35 | issue=n1 | pages=47(14) | issn=0004-9190 }}</ref><ref>Waitt, G. (1999). Naturalizing the \u2018primitive\u2019: A critique of marketing Australia's indigenous peoples as \u2018hunter\u2010gatherers\u2019. Tourism Geographies, 1(2), 142-163.</ref>\n\nThe nostalgic attractiveness and historical interest of Trompf's posters endure; they are frequently included in public exhibitions,<ref>{{Citation | author1=Butler, Roger | title=The streets as art galleries - walls sometimes speak : poster art in Australia | date=1993 | publisher=National Gallery of Australia | isbn=978-0-642-13020-4 }}</ref> they have become collectible national treasures<ref>{{Citation | title=Bondi gems beckon in UK | journal=Australasian Business Intelligence | date=2013-10-16 | publisher=COMTEX News Network, Inc | issn=1320-6680 }}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> and they fetch up to $A12,000 at auction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.invaluable.com/artist/trompf-percy-k2wg9l0dxo/sold-at-auction-prices/|title=Percy Trompf Paintings & Artwork for Sale {{!}} Percy Trompf Art Value Price Guide|website=www.invaluable.com|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.joseflebovicgallery.com/advSearchResults.php?action=search&orderBy=relevance&category_id=0&keywordsField=Percy+Trompf|title=Percy Trompf at Joseph Lebovic Gallery|last=www.bibliopolis.com|date=|website=Josef Lebovic Gallery|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 14 May 1932, Trompf married Vera Johns at the Methodist Church, [[Armadale, Victoria|Armadale]], Victoria, Melbourne, and they had two daughters.<ref name=\"ADB\"/><ref name=\"ADB\"/> His nephew (b.1940) was religious historian Professor Garry W. Trompf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://therha.com.au/garry-w-trompf/|title=Emeritus Professor Garry W. Trompf {{!}} Religious History Association|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Cusack, Carole M | author2=Trompf, G. W | author3=Cusack, Carole M., 1962- | author4=Hartney, Christopher | author5=ProQuest (Firm) | title=Religion and retributive logic : essays in honour of professor Garry W. Trompf | date=2010 | publisher=Brill | isbn=978-1-282-78641-7 }}</ref>\n\nTrompf died of a renal infection on 17 July 1964 in [[Heidelberg, Victoria|Heidelberg]], Melbourne.<ref name=\"ADB\"/>\n\n== Works ==\n=== 1920s ===\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways | title=The holiday spirit, Mt. Buffalo National Park | date=1920 | publisher=Victorian Railways | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/25941042 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways (issuing body.) | title=Take a day at the seaside : go down by train! | date=1923 | publisher=[Victorian Railways] | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/191664947 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways | author3=F.W. Niven Pty. Ltd, (printer.) | title=See the Better Farming Train | date=1924 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/177673637 |ref=none}}\n* {{Citation | author1=Trompf, Percy | author2=Victorian Railways | title=See the better farming train : a wonderful exhibi